<FIRST>r w PM-APAppointment     05-05 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Appointment,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>AP Names Assistant Bureau Chief in Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandy Johnson, a news editor in the Washington
bureau of The Associated Press, has been promoted to assistant
chief of bureau.
   The appointment was announced Thursday by Washington Chief of
Bureau Jon Wolman.
   Ms. Johnson, who joins David Espo as one of two assistant chiefs
in the bureau, has been an editor in Washington since 1983. She
directed AP's coverage of the 1986 and 1988 political campaigns, as
well as the 1988 political conventions, and was named news editor
in January.
   Ms. Johnson, 33, is a native of Revillo, S.D., and a graduate of
South Dakota State University. She began her AP career in Bismarck,
N.D., in 1978. She also worked in Pierre, S.D., and was
correspondent in Sioux Falls before transferring to Washington.
</TEXT>
