<FIRST>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0867 05-05 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0867,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS Fleisher; AMs separates moved as a0753 on Watson and a0801
on Younger. Fleisher also moved on the sports wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Douglass Watson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglass Watson, a actor who played Mackenzie
Cory on the NBC soap opera ``Another World,'' died Monday in
Arizona of a heart attack. He was 67.
   The role, which he played for nearly 15 years, earned him Emmy
Awards in 1980 and 1981.
   Watson won the Distinguished Flying Cross and two Purple Hearts
for his service in the Air Force in World War II.
   He appeared in more than 30 Broadway plays, including the title
role in ``Confidential Clerk.'' Other theater credits included
``Over Here,'' `Wisteria Trees,'' ``Romeo and Juliet'' and ``Glass
Clock.''
   Watson was awarded a New York Drama Desk award in 1974 for his
portrayal of Don Pedro in Shakespeare's ``Much Ado About Nothing.''
   He was also seen in the films ``Sayonara,'' ``Julius Caesar,''
``Ulzana's Raid'' and ``The Money Pit.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Evelle Younger</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evelle Younger, a former district attorney
who oversaw the prosecution of Charles Manson and Sirhan Sirhan,
died Thursday of arteriosclerotic cardiovascular disease. He was 70.
   Younger served eight years as state attorney general and won the
Republican nomination for governor in 1978 after careers as an FBI
agent, deputy city attorney, city prosecutor, municipal and
superior court judge, and district attorney.
   During his six-year tenure as Los Angeles County district
attorney, Sirhan was tried and convicted for the 1968 assassination
of U.S. Sen. Robert Kennedy. Younger's office also brought the
first indictments against Manson and his followers for the 1969
Tate-LaBianca slayings.
   In 1968, he headed President-elect Richard Nixon's Crime and Law
Enforcement Task Force. Younger was also chief of President Ronald
Reagan's Task Force on Administration of Justice.
   After losting the governor's race to Democratic incumbent Gov.
Jerry Brown in 1979, Younger became a senior partner in the law
firm of Buchalter, Nemer, Fields and Chrystie.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Herschel Loveless</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Herschel Loveless, a former governor of
Iowa, died Wednesday in Winchester, Va., at the age of 77.
   Loveless, who served as governor from 1957 to 1961, was the
first Democratic governor in 18 years when he succeeded Republican
Leo Hoegh in the governor's mansion. He left office in 1961 after
losing the 1960 U.S. Senate race to Republican Jack Miller of Sioux
City.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Larry Fleisher</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Fleisher, who founded the NBA Players
Association and as an agent represented some of the biggest names
in the sport, collapsed and died Thursday following a squash game.
He was 58.
   A Roosevelt Hospital spokesman said it was policy not to release
the cause of death.
   Under Fleisher's leadership of 26 years, NBA players became some
of the highest paid in sports and gained one of the best free-agent
systems. Fleisher also worked with the league in developing a model
drug-abuse program in which the union participated.
   When Fleisher started the association in 1961, the average
player's salary was $10,000. Under the six-year collective
bargaining agreement he negotiated in 1988, the average salary will
increase to $900,000 by 1993. It is now about $600,000.
   Fleisher operated the union under the title of general counsel.
He resigned last September, and a month later joined International
Management Group as head of its sports division.
   In addition to his union activities, Fleisher represented such
leading players as Bill Bradley, Jerry West, John Havlicek, Willis
Reed, Bob Lanier and Alex English.
</TEXT>
