<DOCNO> AP890505-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Wright-Loan     05-05 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wright-Loan,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Speaker Borrowed, Lost $100,000 in Investment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright borrowed $100,000 to
invest in a Texas nursing home company in 1983, and lost the money
when the company was liquidated in bankruptcy proceedings two years
later, according to pubished reports.
   Before the company failed, Wright received dividends on his
investment in Jewell Enterprises Inc., although other investors
received none, according to reports in The Boston Globe and The New
York Times.
   Wright's financial disclosure statements list ``investment
income'' from Jewell Enterprises of between $5,001 and $15,000 in
1983. But William Oldaker, Wright's attorney, said Wright also
received $17,000 around the beginning of 1985, The Times said in
its Friday editions.
   Only one other investor, a friend of Wright's who recommended
the investment to him, received payments from the company, The
Times said, citing interviews with 20 of the 27 other investors.
   The Globe reported on Tuesday that Wright borrowed all the money
for his purchase of $100,000 worth of stock in Jewell Enterprises
and used the stock as collateral for the loan. T.R. Jewell,
president of Jewell Enterprises, was also a director at the bank
that lent Wright the money, The Globe said.
   Jewell's bankruptcy made the stock worthless, but the loan still
had to be repaid. Wright also had to repay $13,500 of the dividends
he had received, the reports said.
   Wright finished paying off the loan last June, using some of his
$340,000 profit from a later gas well deal, The Globe reported. The
House ethics committee is looking into the circumstances of the
well venture.
   The speaker is currently defending himself against charges he
broke House rules 69 times over the past decade. The ethics panel
is expected to hold a hearing on the charges later this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
