<DOCNO> AP890505-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0250EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Economy     05-05 0889</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Economy,0907</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sugar, Salt &amp; Soap: Shortages Worsen Under Perestroika</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the town of Kimry, soap rationing began in
April, limiting each man and woman to one bar of household soap and
1} pounds of bath soap in local shops. Not each week or month, but
each year.
   The residents of Ufa, a city of 1 million people in the Urals,
are loading up on salt and matches due to rumors of pending
shortages.
   Sugar rationing went into effect in Moscow on May 1 for the
first time since World War II, and even the Soviet minister of
trade, Kondrat Terekh, has been issued a card entitling him to 4.4
pounds of sugar per month and no more.
   Those tales of consumer woe, and more, were cited in state-run
newspapers Thursday, along with an anguished complaint in the
weekly Moscow News that the Soviet retail trade system, caught
between President Mikhail S. Gorbache's reforms and old iron-fisted
bureaucratic habits, ``is literally breaking apart before our very
eyes.''
   Far from causing store shelves to brim with goods, Gorbachev's
campaign for ``perestroika,'' or economic and social renewal,
coincides with shortages in the consumer sector nationwide, and
some Soviets say the reforms, now in their fifth year, are the
direct cause. Others blame bureaucrats hostile to Gorbachev and his
reform drive.
   ``The feeling is such that under cover of the words `the
inescapable difficulties of perestroika,' shortages are being
created deliberately to indoctrinate this: perestroika on the one
hand brings glasnost, which you can't put into tea, and on the
other hand, a real worsening in the conditions of life,'' wrote
Georgy Afanasyev in this week's Moscow News.
   ``In a word, they're telling us: choose either the old order,
with tea and sugar, or perestroika and just boiled water with
glasnost,'' Afanasyev said. He opted for water and glasnost, saying
the Kremlin's openness policy was a precondition for manufacturing
enough ``tea, sugar and everything else'' to meet demand.
   In a speech last week to the Communist Party's policy-making
Central Committee, Gorbachev acknowledged his reforms had failed to
improve the average citizen's economic lot, and admitted what most
shopgoers already know from bitter experience: Shortages of
consumer goods are not shrinking under perestroika, but growing.
   ``The food problem is far from solved,'' Gorbachev said on April
25. ``The housing problem is acute. There is a dearth of consumer
goods in the shops. The list of shortages is growing. The state's
financial position is grave.''
   The Soviet leader blamed runaway government spending, people who
``forgot how to work'' and top government and party organs _
including the ruling Politburo, which he heads _ for failing to
keep up with the tasks confronting them.
   Gorbachev and other top officials have rejected calls to spend
more dollars earned abroad through the sale of Soviet oil and other
exports to buy consumer goods, saying the money should be spent to
modernize Soviet industry so more better-quality goods can be made
locally.
   But last month, Deputy Trade Minister Suran Sarukhanov told a
Soviet weekly that the equivalent of $8 billion had been added to a
$32.1 billion fund for imports of consumer goods, and that the
Kremlin would buy 15 million pairs of shoes, 300 million razor
blades, detergent, soap and other goods abroad to parry chronc
shortages.
   Pravda, the Communist Party daily newspaper, said the persistent
deficits of consumer goods were why people in Ufa believed rumors
that salt would be in short supply. In the resulting stampede to
the stores, salt purchases recently skyrocketed from the city's
average of 10 tons per day to 250 tons in 36 hours, the paper said.
   A boom in the sale of matches drove daily demand from the
customary 157,000 boxes to as many as 2 million, Pravda said.
   Twenty-six residents of the Krasnoyarsk region of Siberia who
wrote Pravda might well envy the people of Ufa. The Siberians are
forced to bring meat to their village store in exchange for goods,
they wrote, and in such quantities ``that for a family of 3-4
people to get shoes and clothe itself, it needs to give 4-5 cows.''
A sweatshirt costs 220 pounds of meat, they said.
   Pravda said money originally earmarked for heavy industry,
traditionally the priority sector in the Soviet economy, should be
diverted to help meet consumer demand ``and turn the wheel of
economics towards the social sphere.'' But a group of economists
and journalists writing in Moscow News said less government
interference, and not more, was the right recipe.
   The group, called ``Against Inflation,'' said the country was in
the grip of an ``inflationary crisis.'' Economists have projected
the Soviet budget deficit, acknowledged for the first time last
fall after years of secrecy, will reach $162 billion in 1989.
   ``Against Inflation'' said government control over prices should
be gradually lifted, and the mechanism halted that provides
automatic increases in pensions and subsidies as consumer goods
become more expensive. It also called the Gosplan state planning
agency and Ministry of Finance the greatest danger to Gorbachev's
reforms.
   ``What awaits us if the present fiscal and economic policy will
continue?'' the group asked. ``First of all, a total rationing
system for food. Already today, trade is literally breaking apart
under our very eyes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Duarte     05-05 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Duarte,0940</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dying President Hangs on for Succession</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exhausted by cancer, calamity
and revolution, President Jose Napoleon Duarte struggles to survive
and complete what may be his greatest victory _ peacefully handing
power to an elected successor.
   On June 1, Duarte will hand the presidential sash to
President-elect Alfredo Cristiani of the right-wing Republican
Nationalist Alliance. An adviser said the president ``feels
ambivalent, because he began by taking power away from the
oligarchy and now it may seem he's handing it back.''
   Although the transfer may be peaceful, it will occur in an
atmosphere of civil war, killings by death squads and political
assassinations.
   Duarte spent the past week in bed under an oxygen tent, wasted
by dehydration from vomiting and diarrhea caused by chemotherapy
for terminal liver cancer. He was strong enough Thursday, however,
to rise and receive the credentials of the new Argentine ambassador.
   The president appeared gaunt and stroked his aching throat
repeatedly. He spoke hoarsely but lucidly for 15 minutes,
occasionally sipping water because of mouth ulcers caused by the
chemotherapy.
   ``My government has laid the foundation for democracy in this
country. I have created here a new concept of politics,'' Duarte
said, and cited as his greatest disappointment ``not being able to
leave the country in a process of peace.''
   He is given little chance of reaching his 64th birthday in
November. The former engineer probably will be remembered for a
critical role in gradual and difficult transition from
authoritarianism to democracy, but he approaches the end of his
term and life burdened by failures and compromises.
   Duarte feels he is largely responsible for conditions that make
the peaceful succession possible and sees it as a crowning
achievement. He also considers Cristiani's party, known as Arena,
an authoritarian, anti-democratic movement that may erode gains in
human rights and civil liberties.
   Cristiani said in an interview with foreign correspondents:
``One must acknowledge President Duarte's democratic vocation. He
has ... promoted democracy, but I wouldn't go so far as to call him
the father of Salvadoran democracy.''
   Since terminal cancer was diagnosed last June, Duarte has made
periodic trips to Walter Reed Army Medical Center in Washington for
treatment. With rest and intravenous nourishment, he has been able
to overcome previous chemotherapy and return to government.
   His doctor, Jose Luis Saca, told The Associated Press the most
recent treatments have been particularly devastating but he is
optimistic Duarte will recover sufficiently to take part in the
June 1 ceremony.
   During Duarte's five-year term freedom of expression and labor
union pluralism have expanded, politically motivated murder has
declined and El Salvador has held three nationwide elections judged
free and fair by international observers.
   His main goals of ending the war and reviving a moribund
economy, however, remain as distant as when he took office.
   Leftist guerrillas have fought U.S.-backed governments for nine
years. They continue to dominate much of the north and east despite
more than $3.5 billion in economic and military aid from Washington.
   Security forces outnumber the 7,000 insurgents 8-1, but rebels
have demonstrated the capacity to attack major garrisons and keep
the army on the defensive in much of the country.
   Recently, in addition to murders in death-squad style, the
attorney general was assassinated and wholesale roundups of
leftists have been conducted. The home of the vice president-elect
was bombed.
   Attacks on prominent individuals appear designed to provoke or
undermine Cristiani.
   Arena and U.S. officials blame the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, the guerrilla alliance, but the rebels have not
made targets of high officials in the past. They normally claim
responsibility for attacks and have not done so in these cases.
   El Salvador's economy is a shambles and the country would be
virtually bankrupt without aid. Private investment, living
standards and production of coffee, sugar and cotton, the main
export crops, have declined drastically.
   Health care, potable water and primary education are little more
than dreams to most rural people. Corruption and nepotism in
Duarte's administration are described as widespread or rampant,
depending on who makes the assessment.
   The judiciary is ineffective. While death-squad activity has
declined, political murder continues.
   In his state-of-the-nation address last year, Duarte said: ``The
will of my people has caused me to navigate seas each day more
stormy and more dangerous because of crosscurrents. The absence of
fair winds and persistent adversity all along the route have joined
to prevent us from bringing about our high aims.''
   A ranking U.S. diplomat said Duarte ``didn't work miracles, so
he has taken a lot of knocks, some fair and some not. ... He merged
the party and the government and surrounded himself with some
unscrupulous people, but he must be credited with instituting the
democratic system itself. His great legacy is this transition.''
   The Rev. Ignacio Ellacuria, rector of Central American
University, criticized Duarte for presiding over a military junta
in 1981-82, when death squads and the military were blamed killing
up to 700 alleged leftists a month.
   ``Duarte accepted thousands of murders with the facile argument
that, if he were not (on the junta), there would be more,''
Ellacuria said.
   He agreed that Duarte had fostered ``formal democratic
liberties,'' but added:
   ``He never realized what little real power he had. He's not a
false man, but ... self-deceived. His hands were completely tied by
the United States and the armed forces.''
 
</TEXT>
