<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Jurors     05-05 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Jurors,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Jurors in the Oliver North Trail</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thumbnail sketches of the jurors in the Oliver
North Iran-Contra trial, along with some of their comments when
they were questioned by judge and lawyers before the trial began:
   DENISE ANDERSON _ 34, foreman of the jury and a clerical worker
at a hospital. She lives with her mother whom she refers to as
``news media'' because she likes to watch the news. Ms. Anderson,
on the other hand, said ``I don't like the news'' and when her
mother comes to her room to discuss current events, ``I always tell
her to get out.''
   JEAN I. JOHNSON _ 53, a cashier with a 12th grade education and
a husband who is disabled. She suffers from high blood pressure and
several times during jury deliberations complained of not feeling
well. During the trial, her aunt died, prompting the judge to
declare a one-day recess. She has a son who is a deliveryman for
The Washington Post. North lawyer Barry Simon, who lodged
objections to selection of almost all of the prospective jurors,
objected to her being included because she had read headlines and
was therefore exposed to North's 1987 congressional testimony.
   JUSTINE NEWELL PARRISH _ 39, worked for the Navy 21 years and
said the only thing she heard before the trial about North was that
he was ``selling weapons to the overseas people.''
   DEBORAH GRAY BELL _ 37, a statistician for the Labor Department
who said that when she reads the paper, she focuses on the comics
or the horoscope and that ``I really wasn't interested'' in North's
nationally televised congressional testimony in 1987.
   ERNEST W. NELSON _ 29, an electronics technician who works for
MCI and installs and maintains long-distance communications lines.
Regarding the Iran-Contra affair and North's congressional
testimony, he said that between headlines and TV ``I can't help but
see it,'' but didn't follow it. Enjoys playing basketball when he
isn't working.
   LISA KRISHAWN BROOKS _ 21, a clerk typist at the Department of
Labor, said ``the front page is the last thing I look at,'' and
that she changes channels when the news is on television. At the
time North was testifying on Capitol Hill in 1987, she said, she
was going to clerk-typist school by day and working in the evening.
All she remembered of North's congressional appearance was
``something about a woman.''
   PATRICIA BENNETT _ 39, an unemployed former office manager of an
advertising firm. She said she thinks she heard that North was
``selling something to Iran,'' recalled something about shredding,
and that she saw him on television ``going in and out of
buildings'' but didn't watch any of his congressional testimony in
1987. ``It didn't interest me that much.'' North's attorneys
objected to her selection, saying she read the paper and ``could
not miss headlines.''
   CASWELL GILBERT HARTRIDGE _ 61, a tow-truck driver who said that
in connection with North and the Iran-Contra affair, ``whatever I
heard I didn't understand.''
   BEVERLY TURNER _ 37, a typist in the Army chaplains' office at
the Pentagon who worked for the government 17{ years. She said she
knows only that North is ``the head of soldiers that went to Iran
or something like that.''
   HELEN GINA LYNCH _ 37, a pathology lab technician at George
Washington University. She said she heard that North ``shredded
some papers ... that's all I know.'' Her husband is a mental health
counselor at St. Elizabeths Hospital in Washington.
   EARL F. WILLIAMS _ 64, unemployed, served in Patton's 3rd Army
in World War II. His last job was as a security guard and he
formerly was a messenger for the State Department. He said ``I sure
would try'' to be fair to North and that his knowledge was limited
to seeing North's picture on the front page of the newspaper.
   TARA LEIGH KING _ 34, a Xerox operator who said ``I don't
remember'' anything about North's nationally televised appearance
in which he gave immunized testimony to Congress.
</TEXT>
