<DOCNO> AP890505-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-TheGermanProblem     05-05 0674</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-The German Problem,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: It May Be Time to Take a New Look at the East-West
Divide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George F. Kennan, the venerable retired
American diplomat, and Sen. Sam Nunn, the influential chairman of
the Senate Armed Services Committee, are challenging President Bush
to do some new thinking about West Germany.
   Kennan, who played a leading role in the post-World War II
``containment'' of the Soviet Union, says in his gentle, diplomatic
way that U.S. policy seems to be humming along without much
recognition of recent changes in Moscow.
   Nunn, who is not a diplomat, flatly accused the Bush
administration Wednesday of having no vision and ``shooting itself
in the foot'' by not seeking a compromise with a West German
electorate concerned about short-range nuclear weapons.
   The rift, with Chancellor Helmut Kohl demanding U.S.
negotiations with the Soviets and Bush saying that would be a
mistake, is straining the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   If it is not healed soon, the orchestration for a smooth Bush
summit meeting in Brussels May 29-30 with the leaders of the 15
other NATO countries could dissolve into dissonance.
   Most of the Lance missiles, which Bush and British Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher want to make more powerful, are in West
Germany as part of the 30-year-old NATO strategy of deterring
Soviet aggression with the threat of a nuclear response.
   In 1987, all U.S. and Soviet intermediate-range nuclear rockets
were banned. That changed the strategic picture in Europe somewhat.
   But the Lances, which now have a range of about 70 miles, are
visible reminders to the West Germans that the next war might very
well be fought on their territory _ and it could be a nuclear war.
   Kennan, writing for a Johns Hopkins University think tank before
the dispute boiled over, all but anticipated the problem.
   He noted: Medium-range nuclear missiles are coming out of
Europe. The Soviet Union is taking more forthcoming positions in
arms control negotiations. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
announced unilateral tank and troop withdrawals from Eastern Europe.
   ``All these could not fail to raise in West German minds the
question of whether the Soviet `threat' was still so serious as to
warrant the indefinite continuation of the military burdens West
Germany has been asked to bear,'' he wrote.
   While West Germans are divided on such questions, Kennan says,
many of them are looking for a fresh review of the dimensions of
NATO deployments in West Germany and the stance NATO is taking in
negotiating over non-nuclear forces with the Warsaw Pact in Vienna.
   But the former U.S. ambassador to Moscow and policy planning
chief at the State Department says he has looked in vain for
evidence that this view is accepted by U.S., British and French
officials.
   ``No appreciable changes have been made or planned in the actual
disposition of NATO forces, nor do there seem to have been any
significant changes in the Western stand on arms control problems
recently under negotiation,'' he said.
   The West German government, a coalition of conservatives headed
by Kohl and liberals led by Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher, actually is united on the short-range missiles _ and on
demanding a change in Washington and London.
   The Germans are saying they will not modernize the short-range
missiles and want to reduce, and perhaps eliminate, such weapons on
both sides of the East-West line.
   The Bush administration is saying no to all of the above, and is
prepared to air the dispute at the Brussels summit meeting. Marlin
Fitzwater, the White House spokesman, said Wednesday the Western
alliance is healthy enough to stand the disagreement, that
controversies are a sign of NATO's vitality.
   Nunn, however, is uncomfortable with the U.S.-German rift _ and
with the administration's approach.
   ``I don't see any strategy at all coming out of this,'' Nunn
said. ``I see both sides of this argument as having no vision.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid covers U.S. foreign policy for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
