<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ComputerSecurity     05-05 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Security,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commerce, Pentagon Security Agreement is Criticized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement between the Pentagon and the
Commerce Department to review government computer security plans
gives military intelligence too much influence over civilian
technology and data, critics of the plan say.
   The agreement ``invites'' the National Security Agency ``to
enter the offices of private information companies and government
contractors'' to help deal with computer security problems, said
Marc Rotenberg of Computer Professionals for Social Responsibility,
a public-interest group based in Palo Alto, Calif.
   Rotenberg was one of several witnesses to appear Thursday before
the House Government Operations subcommittee on legislation and
national security, which is reviewing the 1987 Computer Security
Act.
   The hearing focused largely on a memorandum signed March 24 by
officials of the NSA, the Pentagon's intelligency agency and the
nation's largest, and the National Institute of Standards and
Technology, a research arm of the Commerce Department.
   Under prodding from Congress, the two agencies have started
working closely together to review computer security plans
submitted by offices throughout the government for protecting
systems containing sensitive but unclassified data.
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the subcomittee,
said that under the 1987 legislation, ``the relationship between
NSA and Commerce was clearly intended to be advisory only, with NSA
serving as a technical facilitator to the Department of Commerce.''
   He said, however, that he agreed with many people who have
complained that the memorandum allows the security agency to
encroach upon the central role given Commerce under the statute.
   Conyers, also chairman of the full Government Operations
Committee, said any agreement that weakens civilian control in the
computer security area ``will result in unwarranted personal
intrusions and inhibitors to both domestic and international
commerce.''
   Also expressing concern over the interagency memorandum was
Albert R. Belisle, a Bank of Boston executive who testified on
behalf of the Washington-based American Bankers Association.
   ``Banks need independently developed security technology that is
not pre-empted by NSA control,'' said Belisle, a Bank of Boston
executive who was representing the American Bankers Association.
   James J. Hearn, NSA's deputy director for information security,
called the memorandum of understanding a ``substantial achievement
for both agencies.''
   He said that in negotiating the memorandum ``we have been able
to develop a better understanding of each other's mission and this
in turn has led to renewed confidence and trust.''
   ``Key senior officials in both agencies have worked hard to
build on the ongoing technical cooperation,'' he said.
   Also testifying in support of the MOU was Ray Kammer, acting
director of NIST, which is located in suburban Gaithersburg, Md.
   ``The (memorandum) provides a number of benefits to NIST and the
Department of Commerce,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Drugs-ForeignGovernments     05-05 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Foreign Governments,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>DEA Says International Cooperation Does Exist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top federal drug official says international
law enforcement teamwork to fight the war on drugs must be
``transparent to borders'' even when the partner is a country like
Panama.
   The possibility that drug traffickers might gain access to
detailed U.S. information on investigations ``makes things
complicated,'' said David Westrate, the Drug Enforcement
Administration's chief of enforcement.
   ``On the other hand, we do accomplish things, significant
things,'' he said Thursday, adding that, like the investigation of
the 1985 slaying of DEA agent Enrique Camarena in Mexico, the
United States can pursue dual probes, one involving the foreign
government and one on its own.
   The DEA, he said, maintains an extremely complicated
relationship with Panama, where the government is virtually
controlled by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   While Noriega has been indicted on drug-trafficking charges by
federal grand juries in Florida, the DEA finds it ``in the best
interests of the United States'' to work with the Panamanian
government, he said.
   ``Less than two weeks ago, they assisted us in a convoy of
cocaine from Colombia on its way to New York,'' he said. ``There
are a lot of examples like that.''
   Westrate praised the increased cooperation by foreign
governments in the war on drugs, and attributed their interest to
fears that they could become wracked by drug-related violence, as
Colombia has been.
   He singled out the Mexican government for praise, saying that
country is ``making good, solid progress'' in the drug war.
   The Mexican government's increased interest in cracking down on
the drug traffickers stems from successful efforts to curtail the
flow of cocaine through the Bahamas, which has pushed traffickers
to find other routes. The routes they found run through Mexico, he
said.
   All of the cocaine entering the United States used to come
through the Caribbean to southern Florida, but now one-third of it
comes through Mexico, he said.
   ``That has driven a marriage between the traditional Mexican
trafficking groups and the Colombian trafficking groups,'' Westrate
said.
   One reflection of Mexico's increased concern is its arrest April
8 of Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo, 43, that country's reputed drug
kingpin, and seizure of his assets.
   ``Some say that there is a potential behind this one trafficker
to have that government seize up to $1 billion in trafficker
assets,'' Westrate said. ``That's one crook. Think about the
enormous potential that that money brings in terms of power to
corrupt establishments, to buy businesses, to buy real property, to
do just anything a person wants. And that person's not unique.''
   Westrate said international cooperation is one of the few
hopeful signs in the drug war.
   European countries are becoming more concerned about cocaine
because there's a glut on the market here, with kilos selling for
as little as $9,000. The same cocaine can bring $50,000 to $60,000
in Europe, he said.
   ``The seizure rate there is going off the scope,'' Westrate
said, adding that when Europe establishes free and open borders
between countries in 1992, the situation will get worse. ``I think
the picture for Europe is grim.''
   As an example of international cooperation and the far-flung
activities of the DEA, Westrate cited several major operations,
without giving specifics on their targets. One involves five
countries, 28 DEA offices, 197 individual investigations and 20
wiretaps, 150 informants. Another involves 15 countries, 51 DEA
offices, 126 investigations, 60 informants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0029 </DOCNO>
