<SECOND>PM-Super 7,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retired Tug Captain Claims Share of Lottery Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last winners of North America's
largest lottery jackpot have come forward to claim their prize.
   A retired tugboat captain and his family on Thursday presented
Pennsylvania lottery officials with what is believed to be the 14th
and final winning ticket that qualified for a share of the $115.5
million Super 7 jackpot.
   Lottery officials expect to have some of the tickets from the
April 26 drawing validated and to start issuing checks by next
week. Each winning ticket is worth $8.3 million, payable in 26
annual installments of $317,524.
   ``It took a while for it to dawn on me that we had the winning
ticket,'' Henry G. Ronneberg told reporters after he and his family
turned in the ticket Thursday.
   His wife, Barbara, added: ``We were numb.''
   Ronnenberg said their annual share will be split with their son
and daughter and one of their grandchildren.
   ``They're just struggling,'' Barbara Ronneberg, 67, said of her
children.
   Ronneberg, 66, originally from Norway, has been in the United
States since he married in 1945. He worked on tugboats in New York
City Harbor from 1947 until 1984 for the Moran Towing and
Transportation Co. and served in Norway's merchant marines during
World War II.
   After his retirement, Ronneberg and his wife moved to the rural
Pennsylvania farmhouse in Wilcox where she was born.
   Ronneberg said he thought he might use part of the winnings to
visit his mother, Gunda, 89, in Norway.
</TEXT>
