<HEAD>Dukakis Returns To Alma Mater On 125th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SWARTHMORE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criticizing the health care provisions in
President Bush's budget, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis renewed
his call for universal health insurance while commemorating the
125th anniversary of his alma mater.
   Dukakis, who last spoke at Swarthmore College while seeking the
Democratic presidential nomination, told about 400 people, mostly
Swarthmore students, that plans to cut into Medicare are
``unconscionable and unacceptable.''
   He said the budget would cut Medicare by $2.7 billion.
   ``These cuts, if approved by the Congress, will continue to
shift costs to private insurance plans, a trend that is already
raising the cost to employers, who have to cut benefits, increase
co-payments and deductibles and require larger employee
contributions,'' he said.
   Dukakis graduated in 1955 from Swarthmore, whose charter was
approved by the Pennsylvania Legislature 125 years ago Thursday.
The liberal arts college, about 10 miles southwest of Philadelphia,
has an enrollment of about 1,320.
   Before his speech, Dukakis ate dinner with old classmates,
professors and students who campaigned for him.
   ``My only regret is we're not doing this on the East Lawn of the
White House,'' he said.
</TEXT>
