<FIRST>u i PM-Panama     05-05 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama's Presidential Race Winds Down Before Sunday Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-government candidate Carlos Duque
urged 100,000 followers to use their vote in the presidential
election as a weapon ``to cut off the hands of those who sold
Panama for $10 million.''
   Speaking Thursday in May 5th Plaza at his final major rally
before Sunday's election, Duque said though that he was willing to
resolve Panamanian differences with the United States ``on a basis
of respect and non-intervention.''
   Duque has leaned heavily on allegations Washington authorized
$10 million for the opposition and pointed to it as a U.S. attempt
to make Panama ``just another star on the American flag.''
   Duque faces opposition candidate Guillermo Endara in a race to
succeed acting President Manuel Solis Palma. The balloting,
however, is viewed as a referendum on strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, the Defense Forces commander indicted in Florida last year
on drug trafficking charges.
   International observers include two former U.S. presidents who
planned to monitor the balloting. Despite government insistence
that voting will be free and fair, the opposition and Washington
claim that the pro-government alliance will steal the election.
   Alleged American attempts to thwart Panamanian dignity and
independence have been rallying points of the pro-government
coalition throughout the campaign.
   ``Panama cannot be bought for $10 million nor for all the gold
in the world,'' Duque told a cheering crowd that waved colorful
party flags and stood under banners reading, among other
things,``USA: The World Is Watching You; Hands Off Panama!''
   Duque said the eight-party National Liberation Alliance he
represents is the only group that can guarantee stability, bring
together the Panamanian people and deal effectively with other
countries.
   Government employees, who make up about 20 percent of the work
force, were given the afternoon off to attend the rally and
thousands were trucked or bused to the capital from around Panama.
   Panamanian law mandates all campaigning end tonight at midnight.
   The Democratic Opposition Alliance held its final rally
Wednesday, saying Sunday's vote is ``the last peaceful opportunity
for change'' and hinting they would take to the streets if the
results appear rigged.
   There is no official U.S. observer delegation, although former
President Gerald Ford arrived Thursday at Howard Air Base near the
capital. Former President Jimmy Carter and the rest of the
delegation he heads, under the auspices of the Council of Freely
Elected Heads of Governments, were to due arrive today.
   There were reports from Washington that President Bush would
send a delegation despite Panamanian statements that an official
observer delegation would not be welcome.
   Panama has been under military rule since 1968 and has had only
one presidential election since then, in 1984. The opposition
contends a return to democracy in Panama is not possible with
Noriega as the head of the military.
   Noriega has denied the drug trafficking charges, calling them an
excuse to get rid of him in favor of someone more willing to
respect American wishes, especially regarding the Panama Canal.
   Under 1977 treaties signed by Carter and the late Panamanian
dictator Omar Torrijos, the canal is to be taken over by Panama at
the end of the century.
   Panama's government contends the opposition alliance will stop
or delay the Panamanian takeover of the waterway.
   In February last year Noriega allies in the National Assembly
ousted President Eric Delvalle, who tried to fire Noriega after the
drug indictments. Washington still recognizes Delvalle, now in the
United States, as Panama's legitimate ruler.
   The United States imposed economic sanctions against Panama last
year to try to force Noriega out.
   The opposition press has been closed for more than a year in
Panama. Thursday's pro-government rally was widely broadcast while
Wednesday's opposition rally, which drew a similar crowd, was not.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
