<DOCNO> AP890505-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0628EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NorthTrial-Editorials     05-05 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Editorials,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Verdict Applauded, Attacked in Editorials</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper editorials across the nation today generally applauded
Oliver North's conviction as showing no one is above the law, but
some papers said the former national security aide was persecuted
for political ends.
   ``The verdict should remind future officials in the executive
branch that they are not above the law, however just they consider
their cause and however much backing they enjoy from their
superiors,'' said the Rocky Mountain News in Denver.
   The Star Tribune in Minneapolis, Minn., said the jury ``rendered
a service to common sense and common decency,'' and The News &amp;
Observer of Raleigh, N.C., said North's conviction on three felony
charges ``reaffirms the American principle that even high
government officials are accountable to the law.''
   But some papers said North was a victim of political motivations.
   ``The offenses North was found guilty of were woven of political
gossamer and fashioned by a frustrated opposition,'' said The
Indianapolis Star. ``North is guilty of one thing, of
over-zealousness in the service of his country, his president, and
liberty. He should be pardoned.''
   North was found guilty of aiding and abetting an obstruction of
Congress as well as shredding and altering documents in November
1986 and of accepting a $13,800 home security system in mid-1986
from Iran-Contra co-defendant Richard Secord, whom North had
enlisted to run arms to the Contras.
   He was acquitted of nine other criminal charges.
   Many newspapers said North did not emerge from the trial as a
villain, but his conviction was a victory for the judicial system.
   ``The verdict is satisfying not as a triumph for opponents of
Mr. North's policies but as a vindication of law and orderly
process; that, and a solemn judgment that the law, however
politically disagreeable, must be respected by its servants,'' said
The New York Times.
   The Dallas Morning News said although North was found guilty on
just three counts, ``that was enough to make the all-important
constitutional point that even heroes must obey the law.''
   In one of the strongest editorials, The Atlanta Constitution
said North had a gift for appearing sincere ``and was a clever
embroiderer of fictions. In the surer light of the courtroom,
however, he was less than convincing. Ollie North, American hero,
is now a convicted felon.''
   Other newspapers expressed a different viewpoint, questioning in
particular the expense to prosecute North.
   ``Given the multimillion-dollar investigation and prosecution,
we would say that it is the taxpayers who are going to be paying
for the zealotry of Mr. Walsh and congressional liberals,'' said
the Richmond (Va.) Times-Dispatch.
   The Boston Herald said the trial proved ``that if you spend $13
million to prosecute one man, you're bound to get a conviction on
something.''
   The Daily News in New York said the verdict may have long-term
consequences for the executive branch of government.
   ``Oliver North's shadow long will hang over the sort of
free-wheeling, defiantly extra-legal dealing that North engaged in,
proudly. And that, ultimately, may be of far more consequence to
the health of American democracy than any of the damage done by
North's shallow indifference to the law.''
   Whether the nation will ever learn the full story of the
Iran-Contra scandal is still in doubt, according to The Arizona
Republic in Phoenix.
   ``The North trial, unfortunately, cast little new light on the
Iran-contra fiasco. The misguided scheme to aid secretly and
illegally the Nicaraguan Contras _ which turned into a scam to swap
arms to Iran for American hostages in Beirut, with the profits
plowed back into the anti-Sandinista cause _ remain a frustrating
whodunit, a pulp mystery with a convoluted plot and the last page
torn out of the book.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Philippines-Killings     05-05 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Killings,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldier Kills 6, Wounds 14, Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soldier went berserk in the
southern Philippines, killing six people and wounding 14 before
committing suicide, a military report said today.
   According to the Philippine Constabulary headquarters in Manila,
the victims were killed in two attacks on the outskirts of Cagayan
de Oro in Misamis Oriental province, about 500 miles southeast of
Manila.
   Constable 2nd Class Ramon Cabisada, armed with an M-16 rifle and
grenade launcher, opened fire Wednesday afternoon on a house in the
village of Upper Gusa, killing six and wounding 11, the military
said.
   Early Thursday, Cabisada traveled to the neighboring village of
Lower Gusa where he fired on another house with his grenade
launcher and wounded three people, according to the report.
   Cabisada then went to his boarding house nearby and shot himself
to death, the report said.
   It did not give a reason for the attacks.
</TEXT>
