<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-05 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tornadoes In Texas, Heavy Rains In Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tornadoes touched down near a number of Texas towns early today,
causing damage to property but no serious injuries, authorities
said, while heavy rains drenched Louisiana.
   A tornado at Possum Kingdom Lake in Texas damaged roofs on about
50 homes.
   Ten empty coal cars of a train were derailed near the Texas
Panhandle community of Dawn, possibly because of a tornado,
authorities said. No one was injured.
   ``We've had some softball-size hail,'' said a dispatcher in the
Johnson County Sheriff's office in Cleburne, which is 45 miles
southwest of Dallas. The National Weather Service described the
Cleburne hail as baseball sized.
   Similar sized hail fell near Bossier City, Louisiana. Smaller
hail was reported elsewhere in Louisiana and in Oklahoma and Texas.
   In the northern Louisiana city of Monroe, hail forced Lexington
Elementary School officials on Thursday to quickly move students
inside. The school suffered extensive damage.
   ``It hit our windows on the north side and we went into our
drills and got the kids inside,'' said principal Charles Roaner.
   Winds gusted to 80 mph in Granbury, Texas, a town of 5,000
residents 20 miles southwest of Fort Worth, damaging many mobile
homes, authorities said.
   Gusts also were reported to near 80 mph at Wichita Falls, Texas,
and 80 to 90 mph at Eldorado, Oklahoma. There were a large number
of reports of winds to near 100 mph from Dallas County, Texas, to
near Waco.
   Heavy rains _ 3 to 4 inches in spans of 45 minutes _ fell in
parts of Louisiana.
   Shreveport, La., had some street flooding after an inch of rain
fell in 30 minutes. Monroe, La., had more than 4 inches of rain in
the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT, while Shreveport, La., and Fort
Worth, Texas, had more than 2 inches. New Orleans had more than an
inch of rain in the same period.
   The high temperature in the nation Thursday was 110 degrees in
Laughlin, Nev.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extending
from southeast Texas across much of the Mississippi Valley, the
Great Lakes, the Ohio Valley, the eastern Gulf Coast region to much
of the Atlantic Coast. Thunderstorms were to be most numerous from
southeast Texas across the lower Mississippi Valley and the
Tennessee Valley, the central and southern Appalachians to the
middle Atlantic Coast. Strong and gusty winds were forecast across
the middle and upper Mississippi Valley and western portions of the
upper Great Lakes.
   High temperatures were expected in the 30s over northern
Minnesota; in the 40s and 50s from the upper Missouri Valley and
the central Rockies across the northern Plains, northern Nebraska
and the upper Mississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes states;
in the 80s from Florida and southern Georgia to the eastern and
central Gulf Coast region; in the 80s and 90s over Texas except the
Panhandle, across the southern Rockies and the southern Plateau to
inland California; and to 100 to 105 degrees over the desert
Southwest. The remainder of the nation was to have high
temperatures generally in the 60s and 70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Warroad, Minn., to 83 degrees at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 foggy; Boston 51 fair; Buffalo 57 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 70 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 56 foggy; Cleveland
54 drizzle; Detroit 53 drizzle; Miami 76 fair; Philadelphia 53
cloudy; Portland, Maine, 39 fair; Washington 57 showers.
   _Central: Bismarck 38 cloudy; Chicago 53 foggy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 61 cloudy; Denver 41 fair; Des Moines 51 windy; Indianapolis
56 foggy; Kansas City 53 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 41 windy;
Nashville 61 foggy; New Orleans 64 fair; St. Louis 57 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 60 fair; Anchorage 43 cloudy; Las Vegas 78
fair; Los Angeles 63 hazy; Phoenix 79 fair; Salt Lake City 49 fair;
San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 57 fair; Seattle 62 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 45 fair; Toronto 48 rain.
</TEXT>
