<FIRST>r a PM-JoggerAssault     05-05 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jogger Assault,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jogger Calls Her Father, Fights Fever</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mental condition of the Central Park jogger
who was raped and beaten into a coma last month continues to
improve, but doctors say her recovery is threatened by a 106-degree
fever.
   Meanwhile, Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward suggested Thursday
that cameras be placed in desolate areas of Central Park to alert
police to the presence of roving gangs like the one that allegedly
attacked the woman jogger.
   At Metropolitan Hospital Thursday, doctors said the rape victim
called her father ``Dad'' for the first time since the attack.
   ``We do feel, mental status-wise, that she is improving,'' said
Dr. Robert S. Kurtz, assistant chief of surgery. ``On the other
hand, we are obviously concerned about the source of the fever.''
   The 28-year-old woman, who remained in a coma for two weeks
after the April 19 attack, regained consciousness Tuesday, speaking
in a hoarse whisper to relatives and staff members. Her condition
remained critical despite her progress, Kurtz said.
   The woman's parents have maintained a vigil at the hospital
since the attack.
   Six teens have been indicted on charges of attempted murder,
rape, sodomy and assault in the case that has brought an outpouring
of concern from around the city.
   The woman, an investment banker, was on her regular jog through
Central Park when the mob pounced on her.
   The alleged attackers were members of a teen-age gang of more
than 30 youths who went to the park for a night of ``wilding'' _
random attacks on anyone they encountered while roaming the area,
police said.
</TEXT>
