<FIRST>r a PM-RapeAppeal     05-05 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rape Appeal,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Convicted In Rape Of Disabled Girl To Go Free On Technicality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old with muscular dystrophy
who was able to scream and push her attacker while she was raped
wasn't ``physically helpless'' under law, according to a court
ruling that sets the man free.
   The Florida Supreme Court decided Thursday that Lee Curtis
Davis, who's serving a life sentence for the crime, should not have
been charged with rape against a physically helpless victim.
   The 4-1 ruling upholds an appeals court decision that Davis
should go free because he was prosecuted under the wrong law.
   Although the girl, who uses a wheelchair, cannot move her legs,
testimony showed she screamed for help and tried to push the man
away as he raped her twice in the 1985 attack. By law, the high
court said she doesn't fit the definition of physically helpless.
   Davis, 46, was sentenced in 1987 as a habitual offender and
remains at the Marion Correctional Institution. Court officials
said he could be freed within 30 days.
   He cannot be tried again for the crime because of the U.S.
Constitution's provision against double jeopardy.
   ``This was our court of last resort in this case. The decision
leaves us with the conviction overturned,'' said Assistant Attorney
General Charles Corces in Tampa. ``There can be no more appeals.''
   In February, the 2nd District Court of Appeal in Lakeland ruled
that Davis was tried under the wrong sexual battery law.
   The victim was not ``physically helpless'' as defined in the
rarely used law that Davis was prosecuted under because she was not
``asleep, unconscious or physically unable to communicate her
unwillingness to the act,'' the appeal court ruled.
   The alleged rape occurred in Davis' Lake Alfred home, where he
was taking care of the girl.
   Ron Toward, the attorney who won Davis' appeal, said Thursday
that he was happy for his client.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
