<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Afghan     05-05 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Afghan,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Izvestia Says Soviet Troops Involved in 1979 Afghan Coup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet troops were involved in a coup in
Afghanistan before the new leader invited Soviet soldiers to enter
that country in 1979, a Soviet historian said in the government
newspaper Izvestia.
   ``I think the time has come to tell the whole truth, however
bitter it is,'' historian Y.V. Gankovsky said Thursday. ``Abroad,
books have been published on the subject. Silence from us only
causes rumors and speculation.''
   Western sources previously have reported that Soviet forces
moved into Afghanistan before leader Babrak Karmal, considered a
Soviet puppet, issued his invitation.
   But this is the first indication in a Soviet publication that
the Soviet Union may have engineered that invitation.
   Speaking of the attack on the president's palace on Dec. 27,
1979, which killed Hafizullah Amin and led to Karmal's takeover,
Gankovsky said, ``From conversations with our officers, I learned
that our unit, which was included in the limited Soviet military
contingent, also took part in the operation.''
   ``The clash did not take long,'' Gankovsky added. ``And, with
the exception of Amin's personal guards, nobody even made an
attempt to defend the regime he headed.''
   According to a book by Western journalist Jan Goodwin, ``Caught
in the Crossfire,'' Amin had just rejected a Soviet demand that he
either resign or make a formal request for Soviet troops to
intervene in Afghanistan.
   The next day, Babrak Karmal claimed power in a broadcast on
Kabul Radio, and asked for Soviet ``political, moral, military and
economic assistance,'' a request repeatedly cited by the Soviets as
the reason for their intervention.
   Goodwin says Karmal was actually in Tashkent in the Soviet Union
at the time and the broadcast was made using a prerecorded tape.
   Gankovsky also argued with reported statements by Gen. V.I.
Vanenikov that the intervention was necessary to protect the Soviet
Union.
   ``Of course, having a hostile government in power in a
neighboring country could not be satisfying to us. But it did not
follow that we had to react to the situation the way we did in
1979,'' he said.
   ``Political, diplomatic steps could have been taken,'' he said.
   Gankovsky also repeated earlier reports that the decision to
send troops to Afghanistan was taken by former President Leonid
Brezhnev and a handful of others. Former Soviet Foreign Minister
Andrei Gromyko has said Brezhnev's opposition to Amin was partially
motived by fury over the murder of Amin's precedessor, Marxist
President Nur Mohammed Taraki.
   ``Taraki's murder has to be taken into account when considering
the steps taken by the Soviet Union in Afghanistan,'' Gromyko told
the London Observer in a recent interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
