<FIRST>r a PM-RogersTrial     05-05 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rogers Trial,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oregon Man Convicted of Murder in Slayings of Six Women</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Andrejs I. Eglitis is cq in 6th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man already serving a life sentence
has been convicted of 13 counts of aggravated murder in the
abduction, torture and stabbing deaths of six women.
   Dayton Leroy Rogers put his head in his right hand, shook it,
and said ``No'' repeatedly as the first guilty verdict was read
Thursday night in Clackamas County Circuit Court.
   He covered his head with his hands, leaned forward onto the
defense table and looked away from the jurors as they individually
were asked their verdict.
   Rogers was charged with killing six women after kidnapping and
torturing them _ a total of 12 counts of aggravated murder under
state law. A 13th count of aggravated murder held that Rogers
killed one of the victims during sexual abuse.
   The conviction carries a sentence of life in prison or death by
lethal injection. Jurors will determine the sentence in the trial's
penalty phase, beginning May 22.
   Prosecutor Andrejs I. Eglitis refused to comment on the case
after the verdict was returned, saying the penalty phase still
needed to be heard.
   Lotus Flynn, the mother of victim Christine Lotus Adams, said
her family wasn't sure if it supported the death penalty, but was
glad Rogers was convicted.
   Rogers already is serving a life sentence for stabbing to death
a Portland prostitute in a suburban parking lot in 1987.
   The jurors heard 127 prosecution witnesses over five weeks,
while the defense called no witnesses.
   Rogers was convicted in connection with the deaths of the women,
all known or suspected prostitutes who were stabbed repeatedly in
the back. Investigators testified that feet were sawed from three
of the bodies.
   Their bodies, and a seventh that has not been identified, were
found in late August and early September 1987 on a hillside near
Molalla, about 30 miles southeast of Portland.
</TEXT>
