<DOCNO> AP890505-0064 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0745EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     05-05 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Charge 76 Radicals in Case of Burning Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today filed charges ranging
from murder to obstruction of official duty against 76 radical
students arrested in connection with the burning deaths of six
police officers.
   Police in the southern port of Pusan charged four student
leaders with arson and murder. The charges carry a maximum sentence
of death.
   Lesser charges of violent acts or obstruction of official duty
were filed against the other students.
   Police also said they were looking for 16 more students in the
case.
   Six riot troopers were killed and 11 others injured on Wednesday
when they tried to free five police officers held hostage by
radical students at Dongui University in Pusan.
   Authorities said the troopers became entrapped in flames when
students poured paint thinner in a corridor and set it ablaze to
stop the raid.
   Student leaders in Pusan and other parts of the country
expressed condolences for the dead officers. They described the
troopers as victims of President Roh Tae-woo's ``undemocratic
system'' and said they will not end their campaign to topple the
government.
   Students said they will wear mourning ribbons until the officers
are buried Sunday in a funeral ceremony.
   Following the deaths the governing and opposition parties agreed
to enact a law that would ban firebombs, a weapon commonly used by
dissidents and radical students in anti-government protests.
   A draft law calls for up to seven years' imprisonment for people
who use firebombs. Those who manufacture or carry firebombs could
be sentenced to up to three years in prison or fined up to $4,600.
</TEXT>
