<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0825EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a043upInc.ofSt.Paul
05-05 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Still Pressing for Answers After End of North Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs new Hamilton and Hyde comments after 3rd graf,
``We certainly''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The verdict in Oliver North's trial is not
likely to end revelations still trickling out from the Iran-Contra
affair, says one of the chief congressional investigators.
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, who was chairman of the House committee that
delved into the affair in 1987, noted that more trials are yet to
come, and that the House and Senate Intelligence committees are
looking into why some key documents that came out at North's trial
were never turned over to congressional investigators.
   ``We certainly didn't find out all the truth in the Iran-Contra
hearings,'' said Hamilton, D-Ind. ``We'll be learning bits and
pieces about Iran-Contra for years to come, and after the statute
of limitations runs out we'll probably find more.''
   ``The North trial raised a number of questions that I think are
still unanswered,'' Hamilton said this morning on NBC-TV's
``Today'' show.
   ``We still have many, many unanswered questions about
Iran-Contra and those should be pursued. And certainly important
documents that came out in the North trial, we should understand
why we did not get those documents,'' he added.
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said on ABC's ``Good Morning America,''
meantime, ``I think what you'll find when the investigation is
complete ... no documents were withheld. if there were, it was
inadvertant. there was certainly no conspiracy ....''
   The House Intelligence Committee moved Thursday to begin a staff
investigation into what key documents failed to reach Congress and
why those papers were not turned over by the White House. The
panel's Senate counterpart already had begun such a probe.
   ``The documents are important and clearly were within the scope
of the investigation,'' Hamilton said. ``It is up to us to pursue
the implications of those documents to their conclusion.''
   Documents introduced in North's trial indicated that
then-President Reagan approved a deal in 1985 in which the United
States would expedite economic and military aid to Honduras in
return for that country's continued help for the Contras, who were
encamped just inside Honduras along the border with Nicaragua.
Official U.S. aid to the Contras was banned at the time.
   The documents, together with trial testimony, suggested that
senior officials up to and including former President Reagan and
then-Vice President George Bush were more involved in the affair
than the congressional committees knew.
   Bush himself spoke out for the first time on the subject
Thursday, giving reporters ``the word of the president of the
United States'' that ``there was no quid pro quo.'' He said he
would turn over to Congress records of his 1985 meeting with the
Honduran president.
   One main document introduced at the trial, a 42-page admission
of facts stipulated by the government, said that Reagan did approve
a deal and that expedited aid did begin flowing to Honduras.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., chairman of the Appropriations
subcommittee that handles foreign aid, said he would hold up all
aid to Central America until the contradictions are cleared up.
   ``I simply feel we have an obligation to find out what the facts
were,'' Obey said. ``The sad truth is that Congress apparently has
been lied to for years.''
   The White House has offered to make available to Congress former
White House counsel Arthur B. Culvahouse Jr., who oversaw the
document search for the congressional Iran-Contra committees and
gave assurances that all relevant documents had been provided.
   Senate investigators already have identified at least six
documents made public during North's trial which failed to come to
light during the 1987 congressional probe. Most of them point to a
deal with Honduras to expedite U.S. aid in return for help for the
Contras.
   Among them are a Feb. 19, 1985, memo outlining such a plan and
approved by Reagan, and a memo dated the following day making it
clear that the administration knew it was forbidden to provide aid
under those circumstances.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
