<FIRST>r a PM-AIDSFreeZone     05-05 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS Free Zone,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Proposes AIDS Free Zone In Oregon County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plumber's proposal to turn a
southwest Oregon county into an AIDS Free Zone has gotten a cold
reception from authorities.
   ``This is an invasion of the rights of citizens,'' Josephine
County Commissioner Rebecca Brown said. ``It also reminds me of
Nazi Germany. This is much more frightening than any threat of the
AIDS virus.''
   She was reacting to a ballot measure proposed Wednesday by
George Heimos that would amend the county charter to require mass
testing for the AIDS virus and possible expulsion for those who
test positive.
   ``I decided that this county has a high Christian value to it
and that AIDS would certainly wipe out a huge portion of the
population should it start to spread very rapidly,'' the Grants
Pass resident said.
   He must gather 1,824 signatures to put the measure on the
ballot. The earliest election date available would be in May 1990.
   Heimos wants to administer widespread tests and publish the
results.
   Those to be tested under the proposal include children in public
schools, public employees, many jail inmates, applicants for county
permits or licences, people known to have had extra-marital affairs
and those who engage in high-risk behavior.
   The proposal calls for the county Health Department to
quarantine those carrying the virus or expel them from the county.
