<HEAD>Search Continues for 22 Taiwanese Fishermen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Searchers looking for 22 crewmen of a Taiwanese
fishing vessel that sank 1,150 miles northwest of Midway Island
have had to contend with 10-foot seas and 40- to 50-knot winds, the
Coast Guard said.
   A piece of a life raft believed to be from the Hun-Kuoa No. 2
was all that was found before darkness set in Thursday night, Coast
Guard spokesman David Goff said.
   The vessel sank Wednesday after colliding with a sister ship,
the Hun-Kuoa No. 1, which helped in the search along with three
other Taiwanese fishing vessels and two commercial vessels, Goff
said.
   The ships continued to search through the night, and were to be
joined today by a Coast Guard C130 search and rescue plane from
Honolulu and a Navy P-3 Orion patrol plane from Adak, Alaska, he
said.
   Rescue operations were being coordinated by the Coast Guard
cutter Jarvis, which was diverted from fishing patrol in the North
Pacific, Goff said.
   The crew of the sinking ship were seen jumping into the water in
lifejackets, but the Hun-Kuoa No. 1 was unable to pick them up
because it had temporarily lost power, Goff said.
