<FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh     05-05 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladesh,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stampede Kills 19 When Clothes Offered To The Poor In Bangladesh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of destitute women struggled
to get 500 free saris being distributed in Chandpur today,
triggering a stampede that killed at least 19 women and injured 70,
United News of Bangladesh reported.
   A wealthy merchant in Chandpur, 40 miles east of Dhaka, wanted
to hand out the saris to celebrate the Eid al-Fitr feast marking
the end of the holy Islamic month of Ramadan, the news agency said.
   But the sari distribution was halted after the stampede. Most of
the brightly colored lengths of cloth intended for the poor lay
scattered and bloodstained on the ground, the news agency said.
   More than 2,000 women, many of them dressed only in rags,
gathered outside merchant Fazlur Rahman's house before dawn, the
agency said. By the time a guard opened the gate at 8 a.m., the
crowd had swollen to more than 3,000.
   Some of the women surged through a small portico and swarmed up
the narrow stairs. In an effort to halt the onrush, the guard
closed the iron gate but the stampede grew worse, the news agency
said.
   Distribution of gifts is an Islamic tradition at the end of
Ramadan, the month of dawn-to-dusk fasting. The custom, called
``zakat,'' requires the rich to give the poor a portion of their
earnings in the past year.
</TEXT>
