<FIRST>r a PM-SeaFloorDiscovery     05-05 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sea Floor Discovery,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woods Hole Scientists Locate Thermal Vents On Floor Of Mediterrean
Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists using a camera-equipped robot that
scours the ocean floor have found the first known thermal vents in
the Mediterranean Sea, and they expect discoveries of exotic
creatures to follow.
   A leader of the undersea project by the Woods Hole Oceanographic
Institution said Thursday's finding will have broad implications
for marine biology and geology.
   Marine biologists previously have discovered foot-long clams,
12-foot tube worms and other exotic animals living on the floor of
the Atlantic and Pacific oceans near thermal vents, which are deep
cracks where hot minerals well up from the Earth's core.
   The Woods Hole team said it expects that never-before-seen
creatures also will be found near the Mediterranean vents,
discovered about 120 miles from where a remote-controlled
submersible robot will explore a sunken Roman ship in 2,100 feet of
water off the coast of Italy.
   ``Each place where thermal vents have been found before, we've
come across new animals. And each place, they've been different,''
said Shelley Lauzon, a spokeswoman for the oceanographic
institution on Cape Cod.
   The robot, named Jason, will transmit live pictures of the Roman
trading ship and ocean floor to an estimated 250,000 schoolchildren
at 13 museums from British Columbia to Florida.
   Robert Ballard, the oceanographer in charge of the $7 million
Jason project, found the first known undersea vents near the
Galapagos Islands in the eastern Pacific in 1976. Since then,
researchers have found similar vents in the western Pacific and
mid-Atlantic.
   Lauzon said all the vents have been surrounded by chemosynthetic
bacteria, unusual organisms living in darkness and feeding on
chemicals that are toxic to virtually all other forms of life.
   The bacteria, in turn, are believed to start the food chain that
supports exotic animals found nowhere else, including foot-long
clams and mussels in the eastern Pacific, and eyeless shrimp and
hairy snails in the western Pacific.
   The fact that vents have now been found in the Atlantic, the
Pacific and the Mediterranean indicates that they may well be in
all of the world's oceans _ which in turn implies that the
diversity of deep sea life may be far greater than previously
thought, Lauzon said.
   Some scientists also have said that the discovery of
chemosynthetic bacteria and organisms that feed on them makes it
more likely that life could exist on distant planets under extreme
conditions.
   David Gallo, Jason project coordinator and assistant director of
the Center for Marine Exploration at Woods Hole, said how the
discovery of the vents was made was itself a significant
technological advance.
   In the past, such explorations required scientists to spend a
month or more at sea, viewing videotapes of the ocean bottom that
were taken by submersible vessels.
   On Thursday, a satellite hookup enabled scientists at Woods Hole
to see the ocean floor as Jason's camera saw it and to summon
colleagues who could look and offer their opinions, Gallo said.
   ``This is remarkable, that I could get an authority here in two
or three minutes, who didn't have to dedicate a whole month at sea
to participate in this event,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
