<SECOND>PM-Soviet Defector, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0534,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Soviet Hockey Player Defects, Wants To Play In NHL</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-9 ``It was ...'' with 3 grafs to ADD background
on Soviet athletes in West; A version moved on the sports wire.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alexander Mogilny, regarded as one of
the best young hockey players in the world, defected to the West to
play in the National Hockey League, according to Soviet and Swedish
news reports.
   Mogilny, 20, failed to show up Thursday at Stockholm's airport
to join the Soviet National Team on its return to Moscow.
   The national news agency, TT, reported that Mogilny left this
morning on a Scandinavian Airlines System plane to New York.
   Spokesmen for the NHL and the Buffalo Sabres, who hold Mogilny's
rights, said they knew nothing of the defection. Sabres spokesman
Budd Bailey said Thursday night that general manager Gerry Meehan
left town Wednesday and did not leave word where he could be
reached.
   But a Gerry Meehan was registered Thursday at the Sergel Plaza
Hotel in Stockholm, where the Soviets won the World Hockey
Championships earlier this week. Meehan could not be immediately
reached for comment.
   Soviet sources indicated in an interview with FLT, a Swedish
news agency, that he was heading to the United States to join an
NHL team.
   Soviet athletes are playing in the West in increasing numbers,
with one of Moligny's former teammates, Sergei Priakin, joining the
Calgary Flames of the NHL in March, and deals in the works to bring
other top hockey players, basketball players and boxers to the
United States.
   It was unclear what effect the defection might have on relations
between the NHL and the Soviets. Four Soviet teams are scheduled to
tour the NHL next season, and the Calgary Flames and Washington
Capitals are to visit the Soviet Union in September.
   ``I can't answer for the Soviets. They have been known in the
past to do things the way they choose,'' Flames general manager
Cliff Fletcher said in Calgary. ``I hope our relationship is
stronger than one hockey player.''
   Fletcher said he did not anticipate any demand for the return of
Priakin.
   ``We have a contract with them for the next two years. I believe
the Soviets have a reputation of being solid businessmen and will
stick to their agreement,'' he said.
   Fletcher described Mogilny as ``the best young player in the
Soviet Union.'' He was voted the world's best junior player by NHL
scouts in a poll organized by The Hockey News.
   Viktor Tikhonov, the coach of the National Team, criticized
Mogilny.
   ``This incident soured our joyful homecoming after winning the
championships,'' Tikhonov told the Soviet news agency Tass. He said
he believed Mogilny was lured by the promise of a big NHL contract.
   However, he described relations between the Soviet Sports
Committee and the NHL as stable.
   Tass said Soviet sports authorities had planned to discuss
allowing other Soviet players to sign with NHL clubs after the team
returned from the world championships.
   In reporting the defection, Soviet television said National Team
officials and the Soviet federation asked the Soviet Embassy to
tell U.S. and Canadian embassies the ``consequences of this
situation for the NHL would be most serious.''
   The owner of the Stockholm hotel where the Soviet team stayed
during the world championships contacted team officials by phone at
the airport and said he had received an anonymous phone call
informing him of the defection.
   Mogilny, a member of the Soviet Central Red Army team, served a
10-game suspension earlier this season after a fight in a Soviet
league game against Spartak Moscow. A Swedish newspaper reported
last week that he also was penalized a month's salary.
   Mogilny, a junior army lieutenant, told the Aftonbladet
newspaper that he was not interested in a military career. ``I want
to do something else with my life,'' the newspaper quoted him as
saying.
</TEXT>
