<HEAD>Pope Calls For Peace Between Moslems, Catholics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with pope urging better relations between
Moslems and Catholics. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II appealed today for
improved relations between Roman Catholics and Moslems in this
southern African nation, which is experiencing a surge in Islamic
fundamentalism.
   ``What is required is mutual respect, as well as mutual
recognition of those things that we share in common,'' the pope
said in a speech to Catholic bishops on the last full day of his
nine-day African tour.
   John Paul repeated the statement he made to Moslems during his
trip to Morocco in 1985, saying that Christians and Moslems ``have
badly understood each other'' and that ``God invites us to change
our old practices.
   ``Both among Christians working for unity ... and among
believers of different religions, there is no place for aggressive
proselytism which disturbs and hurts, still less toward the use of
unworthy methods,'' John Paul said.
   There are about 2.5 million Catholics and 1 million Moslems in
this nation of 8 million people. Anglicans, Protestants and
animists make up most of the rest of the population.
   Since the early 1970s, Moslems have expanded their presence in
Malawi, building hundreds of mosques across the country, widely
believed to have been financed by Saudi dollars.
   Antagonism between Moslems and Catholics arose in 1983 and 1984
when several churches in Blantyre and Mangochi and the cathedral in
Zomba were set on fire by Moslem extremists.
   In August, several Catholic youths and an elderly religious
teacher were forcibly circumcised in a suburb of Blantyre by Moslem
fundamentalists, church officials said.
   Some Moslem leaders said they were upset that the pope was
visiting Malawi during the period of Ramadan.
   Vatican officials say the spread of Islam is one of the church's
main challenges in Africa.
   ``A big question is whether Africa will be a Christian or Moslem
continent 25 years from now,'' Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro
said today. ``The church cannot compete with the billions of
dollars that is financing Islam in Africa.''
   Earlier today, the pope celebrated Mass for more than 100,000
people gathered on the sloping meadow of Blantyre's Kwacha Park.
   In his homily, the pope referred to AIDS for the second day in a
row, urging his flock to treat the victims of the disease as ``we
would treat Christ himself.''
   According to health officials here, as many as 18 percent of
newborn children are infected with the AIDS virus. Navarro said
about 20 percent of prisoners and urban workers have the disease.
   The pope also referred to the 640,000 refugees who have fled to
Malawi to escape a civil war in neighboring Mozambique, urging his
audience to ``show love and kindness'' toward them.
   The ceremony was attended by Malawi's president-for-life,
Hastings Kamuzu Banda, who arrived in a Mercedes limousine
surrounded by his troupe of women dancers and singers and sat on a
stage decorated with two carved wooden lions.
   The pope came to Malawi after visits to Madagascar, Reunion and
Zambia and returns to Rome on Saturday night.
</TEXT>
