<HEAD>Former President Carter Says Bush Is Off To Good Start</HEAD>
<HEAD>By DARREN DOPP</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush is off to a surprisingly good
start as president, according to an unlikely supporter _ Jimmy
Carter.
   ``Bush has done a fine job so far,'' the former president said
Thursday. ``My only concern is that his administration respond more
vigorously to the chance to negotiate with the Soviets on further
arms control.''
   Carter, participating in the state University of Buffalo's
``Power and the Presidency'' lecture series, told the audience of
about 4,000 that every president must be ``competent, compassionate
and always tell the truth'' and that Bush seems to exhibit more of
these qualities than his predecessor, President Reagan.
   Carter expressed similar sentiments at a meeting earlier
Thursday in Atlanta with contributors to Cable News Network's
``World Report.''
   Carter said Bush has done an extraordinarily good job in several
areas, including Central America, the administration's plan for
reducing the debt of foreign nations and its relations with the
Palestine Liberation Organization.
   In a meeting with reporters in Buffalo before his talk, Carter
said it was clear that Oliver North was not acting alone when he
misled Congress on the Reagan administration's involvement in the
Iran-Contra scandal.
   ``I don't think there's any doubt about the fact President
Reagan knew what was going on and gave either direct or indirect
approval,'' he said.
   North was convicted Thursday on three of the 12 charges stemming
from the scandal, including one that he destroyed documents as part
of a cover-up.
   Carter said he didn't think the verdict would have a significant
effect on the Bush administration.
   On another topic, Carter said he was glad that Bush was moving
away from the Reagan administration policy of avoiding discussion
of American hostages in Lebanon.
   ``Ignoring them doesn't work,'' he said.
   Carter revealed that he once called Robert MacFarlane, Reagan's
national security advisor, and threatened to publicly denounce the
administration if it did not resume private briefings for the
families of hostage members on news concerning their loved ones.
   Carter was scheduled to leave for Panama today as part of an
international delegation that will monitor elections there Sunday.
