<FIRST>r a PM-MockKidnapping     05-05 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mock Kidnapping,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Charged in Mock Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOUTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four fraternity members have been
charged in connection with the mock kidnapping of a student from a
university classroom that a professor said looked terrifyingly real.
   One of the four, James E. Pennoyer III, the president of the
Lambda Chi Alpha fraternity, said today the charges were ``totally
ridiculous.''
   The student taken from the University of Rhode Island classroom
in December was a sorority member who was to be held until she
could raise her weight in food to be distributed to the poor.
   The four students surrendered to police and were arraigned
Thursday in District Court on charges of assault with a device
designed to be substantially similar in appearance to a firearm.
All were released on personal recognizance.
   The felony charge carries a potential prison term of three to 10
years upon conviction.
   Professor Margaret Haggerty said she brought the charges because
the university's discipline against the four was too light. Court
documents indicate they were placed on a year's probation by
university officials in March.
   According to the court records, the four burst into a classroom
Dec. 7 wearing bandanas and carrying replicas of Uzi submachine
guns and a fake handgun.
   Haggerty said the four were dressed like terrorists and she had
no idea the incident was part of a fund-raiser. ``I said, `Get out
of this room. Get out of this classroom.' I was more or less in
shock.''
   She said one masked invader pointed the handgun at her and
pulled the trigger as they left.
   The prank was inappropriate for the class, which explores the
impact of death on behavior, Haggerty said. About 40 students were
watching a film on medical ethics at the time of the mock
kidnapping, she said.
   ``A lot of students take that course because they recently
experienced death,'' she said.
   ``It was a philanthropic event, and this is a miscarriage of
justice,'' said Pennoyer, 21, of East Providence. ``We didn't do a
thing to her (Haggerty). We came in and took a student who knew we
were coming. It's totally ridiculous.''
   Also charged were David M. Jones, 20, of East Providence;
Antonio DaSilva, 23, of Pawtucket; and Michael I. Miga, 19, of
Warwick.
</TEXT>
