<FIRST>u w PM-Budget-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0453 05-05 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget-Glance, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to reflect congressional approval</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are outlines of the budgets approved
Thursday by the House and Senate, as required by last month's
bipartisan agreement with President Bush.
   _Totals: $1.2 trillion in spending, $1.1 trillion in revenues, a
$99.4 billion deficit.
   _New tax revenue: $5.8 billion. Of the total, $5.3 billion will
be from taxes Congress and Bush will have to agree to, and $500
million will be from increased enforcement by the Internal Revenue
Service. Bush proposed $5.3 billion in this category.
   _Other revenues: $2.7 billion by increasing fees for federal
services, such as national park entrance fees, $5.7 billion by
selling as yet unspecified federal assets.
   _Military: $299.2 billion, $4.2 less than needed to keep pace
with inflation.
   _Entitlement programs: $556.4 billion in spending for programs
in which benefits are paid automatically to people who qualify,
$6.8 billion less than expected growth. Reductions include $2.7
billion from Medicare, $1.9 billion in farm payments and $1.1
billion from Postal Service and federal pension changes. Bush asked
for $537.3 billion.
   _Other domestic programs: $181.3 billion, $4.5 billion above
Bush's original proposal and $300 million less than expected growth.
   _International affairs: $17 billion, down from Bush's $17.4
billion request when he took office.
   _Interest payments on the national debt: $181 billion.
</TEXT>
