<FIRST>u i PM-Britain-Thatcher 2ndLd-Writethru a0553 05-05 0609</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Thatcher, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0553,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Rebuffed by Welsh Election Upset on 10th Anniversary in
Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 10th, ``The 38-year-old...'' to CORRECT occupation of winner
to business studies lecturer. Pickup 11th pvs, ``The Conservatives ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Thatcher's Conservative Party today lost
a parliamentary seat it has held for 38 years, suffering a sharp
rebuff as she marked her 10th anniversary as prime minister.
   In a huge 12.5 percent swing against the government, the
socialist Labor Party captured the Vale of Glamorgan, a largely
rural Welsh district, with a 6,028-vote majority. That overturned
the Conservatives' 6,251-vote majority in 1987 general elections.
   ``This is what the new modern Labor Party can do ... Mrs.
Thatcher's days are numbered,'' declared victor John Smith, who won
a House of Commons seat left vacant by the death of a lawmaker.
   Defeated Conservative Rod Richards acknowledged votes were lost
over Mrs. Thatcher's plans to overhaul property taxes and the
National Health Service, and to sell off the national water and
electricity utilities.
   ``We have to win that debate in the country and it will take
time because we're changing something quite radically and people
are naturally concerned as to how it will affect them,'' he said.
   Smith retorted: ``My Conservative opponent had to defend the
indefensible. This was a test of Mrs. Thatcher's 10 years in office
and the people of the Vale of Glamorgan made it absolutely clear
that she's not wanted.''
   Health Secretary Kenneth Clarke dismissed the result as a minor
midterm setback.
   Labor also scored heavily off the two divided center parties,
whose support collapsed.
   Smith polled 23,342 votes to the Tories' 17,314. The centrist
Social and Liberal Democratic Party took only 2,017 and the Social
Democractic Party, its previous electoral ally, got 1,098. The
Welsh nationalist party Plaid Cymru also did badly with 1,672 votes.
   The election of the 38-year-old business studies lecturer shaved
Mrs. Thatcher's majority in the 650-member House of Commons to 101
_ still ample to assure passage of her ambitious reforms.
   The Conservatives have 375 seats, Labor 228, the Social and
Liberal Democrats 19 and the Social Democratic Party 3. Minority
regional parties hold the rest.
   It is only the fourth time in 25 years that Labor has snatched a
seat from the Conservatives in a by-election.
   The centrist parties acknowledged they paid heavily for their
split after the last general election in 1987, and the rivalries
that have become known as ``the muddle in the middle.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, who celebrated her 10th anniversary by declaring
she had transformed Britain, faced more problems on the industrial
front.
   She swept to power on a wave of anti-union sentiment May 4,
1979, after a winter of strikes in which garbage piled up across
the country, hospitals turned away the sick and the dead were left
unburied.
   But now, strikes over pay or conditions loom on the state
railroad, in the docks, the engineering industry, the electricity
supply service, the fire-fighting service, the London subway and
among news staff at the British Broadcasting Corp.
   London's liberal newspaper The Guardian predicted today Britain
is heading for its worst industrial strife since a yearlong coal
miners' strike collapsed in 1985.
   Some Conservative legislators claim the unrest may be an
organized campaign. ``This is beginning to look like a
conspiracy,'' said Tory legislator Harry Greenway.
   The Institute of Directors, an employers' organization,
meanwhile reported that confidence in the British economy among
company directors has fallen the last two months. It said those
listed as ``more optimistic'' dropped from 29 percent to 19
percent, while more than half said they were ``less optimistic.''
</TEXT>
