<HEAD>Bush Expectd to Name Reagan Aide to Social Security Spot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is expected to name Gwendolyn
King, a former aide to President Reagan, as the new head of the
Social Security Administration, an administration source said today.
   She would succeed Dorcas Hardy as commissioner of the
80,000-employee agency.
   Ms. King is the ``odds on favorite'' for the post, and her
nomination by Bush is anticipated, said the source who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   In a telephone interview today, Ms. King acknowledged she is
under consideration for the post but has yet to receive a call from
Bush.
   ``I stand ready to serve at the president's pleasure,'' she said.
   Ms. King worked in the Reagan White House as a presidential
deputy assistant and director of the Office of Intergovernmental
Affairs.
   She is currently vice president of Gogol and Associates, a
Washington-based government relations firm.
   She was previously an assistant to Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., and
former Pennsylvania Gov. Richard Thornburgh, who is now attorney
general in Bush's Cabinet. She headed Thornburgh's Washington
office.
