<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Estonia     05-05 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Estonia,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonia Ousts 22 Party Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party in the republic of Estonia
removed 22 party leaders in a sweep that gives greater strength to
reformers, officials and Estonian reporters said today.
   The 22 dropped from the Central Committee included former party
chief Karl G. Vaino, said Estonian Foreign Ministry spokesman Valle
Feldman.
   The party leaders were removed during a meeting Thursday of the
120-member Central Committee. The sweep strengthens newer party
leaders who generally are more progressive and tend to support
sovereignty for the tiny Baltic republic.
   Estonian People's Front leader Marju Lauristen, who spoke at
Thursday's meeting, accused some of the retiring members of
involvement in the exile of tens of thousands of Estonians in the
1940s and 1950s, an Estonian reporter said.
   Lauristen said several of the former Central Committee members
were ``big bosses who participated in the deportations,'' Estonian
radio reporter Sulev Hallik said in a telephone interview.
   Feldman said the Communist Party's declining popularity was a
factor in Thursday's action. A recent public opinion poll in
Estonia found that more than 50 percent of residents support the
People's Front, a grass-roots nationalist group, while only 7
percent back the Communist Party, he said.
   The Estonian Communist Party ``must now take radical steps and
quickly work out a program'' if it wants to hold its own among
other political groups that are flourishing in Estonia, Feldman
said.
   The 22 were removed ``according to their own request'' in a move
similar to the housecleaning last week in Moscow that dropped 110
former officials from the national Communist Party's leadership, he
said.
   ``They were, to a great degree, responsible for the sad position
we're in now, so of course they should take the consequences for
it,'' Feldman said.
   Vaino, who served as Estonian Communist Party chief for almost a
decade, was replaced in June 1988 after months of criticism for
inaction on pollution and corruption.
   His replacement, Vaino I. Vyalyas, is a reformer supported by
the Popular Front. Yet he mildly criticized the group during
Thursday's meeting for seeking to return Estonia to the past,
before the Soviets occupied it in 1940, Feldman said.
   Vyalyas attacked several of Estonia's newspapers for supporting
the radical Estonian National Independence Party, which seeks
Estonian secession from the Soviet Union, said Eve Parnaste, a
leader of that group.
   Feldman said Vyalyas also criticized Interdvizhenie, a largely
Russian group that objects to rising nationalism and political
reform.
</TEXT>
