<FIRST>r a PM-WhaleDeath     05-05 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Whale Death,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newly Arrived Pacific Black Whale Dies Suddenly At Marine Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at Sea-Arama Marineworld are
mourning the sudden death of a Pacific black whale that arrived at
the Galveston marine park only a month ago.
   Although the precise cause of death has not been determined, an
autopsy on the 13-foot whale revealed tumors throughout the
carcass, Cheryl Snyder, a caretaker at Sea-Arama, said Thursday.
   The whale, called Nami, was one of two such whales to arrive
April 2. Caretakers were making regular checks on Wednesday when
they noticed the whale was having difficulty swimming and
breathing. Although trainers swam with the whale and tried to keep
it breathing, it died within about 10 minutes.
   ``We were right there with her the whole time and we still don't
know what happened,'' Ms. Snyder said.
   ``It was just very emotional for all of us because it was so
unexpected. She had shown no sign at all of being ill earlier in
the day.''
   The second whale, called Tanoshi, appears to be healthy, she
says.
   The two whales were among four captured in December by
commercial fishermen in Japan. The two others went to a zoo in
Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
