<SECOND>PM-Defense Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0573,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Unisys Aide Sentenced in Chappell Contribution Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, Barrett pleaded to CORRECT date to Jan. 27 sted
Jan. 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today ordered a former
Unisys Corp. representative to perform 200 hours of community
service for conspiring to conceal illegal political contributions
from defense contractors.
   U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton also gave Robert D. Barrett,
55, a suspended three-year prison sentence and two years' probation.
   Barrett pleaded guilty Jan. 27 to conspiring to defraud the
Federal Election Commission and to causing the filing of false FEC
reports that concealed two $1,000 donations to former Rep. William
Chappell Jr., D-Fla.
   Barrett admitted to a complicated scheme to funnel the
contributions to Chappell's re-election campaign from companies
that, along with Unisys, provided technical services to the
Pentagon.
   Chappell, who died last month, denied knowing that his campaign
had received the illegal corporate donations. He was not charged in
the case.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joseph Aronica told the judge that
Barrett's cooperation with the ``Operation Ill-Wind'' probe of
Pentagon procurement fraud had ``resulted in the rapid movement of
the investigation and has opened up other areas of investigation.''
   Aronica noted that Barrett's cooperation led to several other
guilty pleas by Unisys officials. The company sells computer
equipment and fire control devices to the Defense Department.
   Defense attorney James Bensfield noted that Barrett's two
convictions were for charges that are ``usually prosecuted
administratively by the FEC.''
   ``We're not talking about bribes here. We're not talking about
the misuse of sensitive procurment information,'' Bensfield said.
   The fraud investigation has resulted in several convictions of
defense consultants and contractors charged with paying bribes to
obtain inside information on Pentagon procurement plans.
   Bensfield said Barrett was ``carrying out the orders of his only
boss in the corporation'' when he arranged to funnel the illegal
campaign conributions to Chappell's re-election fund.
   Barrett told the judge, ``I made the mistake of trying to be a
good soldier ... I've learned a lot this last year. I'll never make
the same mistake again.''
</TEXT>
