<FIRST>r a PM-BombDrop     05-05 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bomb Drop,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Accidentally Bombs Georgia Woods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRANTLEY, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force fighter pilot accidentally
dropped a live 500-pound bomb over a sparsely populated rural area,
narrowly missing homes in this west Georgia town. No one was hurt.
   The incident occurred Thursday afternoon as the F-16 ``Fighting
Falcon'' was returning to Moody Air Force Base at Valdosta after a
training exercise at Fort Benning, said Fort Benning spokesman Bill
Walton.
   The pilot, who was not identified, had tried to release the bomb
over Fort Benning's Kilo Impact Area during the exercise, but the
bomb did not release. About 3:15 p.m., when the plane was returning
to its home base at Moody, the bomb fell, Walton said.
   A Air Force spokeswoman at Moody, Capt. Cynthia Nelson, at first
said the bomb was only a dummy and could not have exploded, but
said she later learned it was live and did detonate.
   Marion County Sheriff Horace Snider said it landed in a wooded
area near Brantley, destroying some pine trees. ``If it was a
thousand yards up the road, it would have hit 10 to 15 houses in
the community of Brantley,'' he said.
   Snider said the impact also rattled windows and knocked pictures
from the walls of the nearest house.
   Fort Benning's Range Control reported the accident to post
authorities, and a search party was sent to look for the bomb. It
was found about 6:30 p.m., Walton said.
</TEXT>
