<FIRST>r a PM-HymnalDebut     05-05 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hymnal Debut,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Updated Methodist Hymnal Makes Its Debut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A controversial hymnal giving United
Methodists a mix of gospel standards and more contemporary hymns
drew rave reviews as the songbook made its formal debut at an
international gathering of church leaders.
   ``I think they have a good blend of the old and the new,'' said
Jackie Chrismon of Hope Mills. Her husband, Pete Chrismon, pastor
of Hope Mills United Methodist Church, said the inclusion of
worship guides would aid churchgoers.
   ``It looks like the hymns are very singable,'' said Curt Kollar,
a member of Benson Memorial United Methodist Church in Raleigh. ``I
like the fact that they dropped all those `amens' at the end.''
   At a ``service of thanksgiving and consecration'' Thursday
night, an overflow crowd at Edenton Street United Methodist Church
broke the paper seals around the updated hymnals, then sang a
rousing rendition of ``O For a Thousand Tongues to Sing'' by
Charles Wesley, brother of Methodist founder John Wesley.
   ``This is more than a collection of hymns; it is the book of
worship for our denomination,'' Bishop Rueben Job, chairman of the
Hymnal Revision Committee, told the congregation.
   The denomination's General Conference decided in 1984 to update
the hymnal and agreed on a final version last year, according to
Thomas McAnally, spokesman for the United Methodist Church.
   But what church leaders thought would be a quiet process erupted
into spirited protests with the suggestion that ``Onward Christian
Soldiers'' be eliminated because of its militaristic lyrics. The
hymn, without modification, is in the new hymnal.
   ``Little did we realize when we started to do a hymnal that it
would have any interest beyond the denomination,'' said McAnally,
noting the national attention the debate has received.
   Among the new inclusions are Andre Crouch's ``To God Be The
Glory'' and Bill Gaither's ``He Touched Me,'' McAnally said.
   ``Carlton Young, the book's editor, has observed that people
take their hymns very seriously and take their hymn books very
personally,'' said McAnally. ``It's in their memory banks and they
connect events in their lives, happy and unhappy, with hymns they
have sung.''
   Efforts to update hymns with more contemporary language and to
make male metaphors more gender-inclusive also drew long debate,
McAnnally said.
   For example, ``Good Christian Men Rejoice'' became ``Good
Christian Friends Rejoice.'' In the Wesley hymn ``Christ the Lord
is Risen Today,'' the line ``sons of men and angels say'' now reads
``earth and heaven and chorus say.''
   Raleigh was chosen for the hymnal's debut because it is the site
of this week's Council of Bishops, a meeting of 100 United
Methodist bishops from the United States, Europe, Africa and the
Philippines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
