  05-05 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial-Deliberations, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0558,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Bickered, Argued and Prayed, Member of Panel Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 17th graf, The husband, to CORRECT that Lynch was juror,
not foreman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAMIL HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North was a credible witness and warm
person, says one of the jurors who voted to convict the former
White House aide after days of deliberations often filled with
``bickering and arguing.''
   But the juror, Earl F. Williams, 65, also seems torn over
whether North, facing up to 10 years' imprisonment, should spend
time behind bars.
   ``I believed him,'' Williams said Thursday after the jury found
North guilty of three of 12 counts against him. ``No, I don't think
he should go to jail. Colonel North, I don't know if he's all that
bad or all that good. He made some mistakes.''
   But interviewed today on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,''
Williams first equivocated and then appeared to change his mind.
   ``Do you think he should go to jail?'' Williams was asked.
   ``Well, whether he should go to jail or not is not my, is not
for me to say,'' he replied.
   Pressed for his opinion, however, Williams said: ``Well,
personally, I feel that if he's guilty he should go to jail. Which
he is, so, you know ....''
   Williams, a former security guard who had served with Gen.
George Patton's 3rd Army in World War II, said the jury did not
agree on the guilty counts until Thursday, the 12th day of
deliberations, although some of the acquittals had been decided
earlier.
   The last charge to be decided was whether North altered and
shredded government documents, the District of Columbia resident
said. He said the question was over whether North had criminal
intent.
   North was also convicted of obstructing Congress and accepting
an illegal gratuity.
   ``The jury was split a while on some of the counts, and in a
case such as this there is a lot of bickering and arguing,'' he
said. ``But with God's help we prayed a lot and made a decision.''
   Williams said the nine female jurors, ``were really set in their
ways, but after prayer, a little consideration and friendly talking
they came right in with us.'' But he did not say in what direction
anyone had to be persuaded.
   Still, there were no dominant characters on the jury, Williams
said. ``We were all pretty strong ... it was touch and go ... at
one time this person might be a little strong and another time that
person might be a little strong.''
   Other jurors were too exhausted and ready to return to their
families to say much about the deliberations.
   Calling the verdict the hardest decision she ever had to make,
Justine Newell Parrish, a 39-year-old Washington resident, said
that ``I just want to be with my family.''
   ``I'm going to take my shower and catch the next flight out of
here to Jamaica,'' said juror Jean Johnson, a 53-year-old cashier
in the district.
   The husband of juror Gina Lynch, 37, a lab technician from
Washington, is hoping that life for the couple and their three
children will be back to normal in a few days.
   Frank Lynch, a mental health counselor, said his wife went into
seclusion, but not before taking their three children out for
seafood.
   ``I'm glad things will be back to normal,'' Lynch said because,
``the kids missed her.''
</TEXT>
