<FIRST>r i PM-Finland-Ozone 1stLd-Writethru   05-05 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Finland-Ozone, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0498,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Adopts Funding Proposal to Fight Ozone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with quote from Tolba. Pickup 4th
pvs, ``Industrial countries...'' Disregard a0570, which duplicated earlier
version.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATTI HUUHTANEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N.-sponsored conference today
called for financial aid, possibly including a new international
fund, to help developing countries phase out chemicals that damage
the earth's protective ozone shield.
   The compromise proposal for a world climate fund was adopted
after private consultations among delegates of nine industrial and
Third World countries.
   Mostafa K. Tolba, head of the U.N. Environment Program,
adjourned the meeting Thursday to break a deadlock whether to have
such a fund.
   ``This is the decision in principle that I wanted,'' Tolba told
reporters.``What remains is more difficult, to make it concrete.''
   Industrial countries objected to demands to a fund that they
said could be expensive to set up and administer. Third World
countries wanted to ensure that assistance would not be drawn from
existing aid programs.
   Earlier, the conference called for a worldwide ban by the year
2000 on chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, which are used in
refrigeration, some plastics and insulation.
   CFCs break down the ozone layer high above the earth that
filters out ultraviolet radiation from the sun, increasing the risk
of skin cancer and eye disease.
   The delegates agreed that developing countries needed assistance
to replace the technologies and equipment they inherited from the
industrial countries.
   Scientists said the threat of ozone depletion can be averted
only if CFC emissions are stopped altogether.
   The adopted resolution said the conference ``recognizes the
urgent need to establish international financial and other
mechanisms'' to help developing countries.
   It set up an ``open-ended working group to develop modalities
for such mechanisms ... that do not exclude the possibility of an
international fund.''
   The working group is to report next year to a second follow-up
conference of the 1987 Montreal Protocol, which was the first
treaty to establish controls on the production and use of CFCs.
   U.S. delegation leader Eileen Claussen said she is satisfied
with the funding resolution, which she said filled the ``obvious
need for some financing on an international level.
   ``The paper is fine,'' said Ms. Claussen, deputy director of the
Environmental Protection Agency. ``It was a good mood in the
working group. After all, we're all in this together trying to do
the same thing.''
   Finland's Environment Minister Kaj Barlund, who championed the
idea of a world climate fund, said the resolution was ``close to
what we wanted.''
   But he acknowledged that the vague wording may make it difficult
to get the fund working.
   The compromise was worked out among delegation heads from the
United States, Soviet Union, Japan, Mexico, China, Senegal, Tobago,
Malaysia, and New Zealand.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica     05-05 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Minister Proposes Black Role In Parliament</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Cabinet minister said
today the government wants to bring the black majority into
Parliament and the executive branch, but only if the white minority
cannot be overruled.
   Security for the country's 5 million whites can be ensured
``only in an environment of progress, safety and justice for all
the people of South Africa,'' Constitutional Development Minister
Chris Heunis said in a speech to Parliament.
   South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs and no representation in Parliament or the Cabinet.
   Heunis' speech was a relatively comprehensive summary of various
proposals he and other government officials have mentioned in
recent months. Heunis said details of a new constitutional system
would have to be negotiated, and thus he offered few specifics
about the new role envisioned for blacks.
   Thus far, no prominent black leaders have accepted the
government's invitation to participate in constitutional
negotiations. Militant blacks have rejected Heunis' plans, while
some moderate blacks have indicated they would negotiate if the
government freed imprisoned black leaders such as Nelson Mandela
and lifted bans on black opposition groups.
   Speculation the government may free Mandela after general
elections on Sept. 6 increased today when Mandela was visited at a
prison farm near Cape Town by Harry Gwala, a terminally ill
colleague freed from jail in November.
   Gwala, who is suffering from a neurological disease, refused to
say who initiated the meeting. Both men are 70 and have been
members of the African National Congress since the 1940s. Until
Gwala's release, both were serving life sentences for involvement
with the outlawed guerrilla movement.
   Previous attempts to free Mandela have been blocked by the
nationalist leader's refusal to renounce violence in the fight for
majority rule.
   In Parliament, Heunis rejected charges the government's
proposals are vague and insincere.
   ``Everyone has to become participants in legislative, executive
and judicial institutions because fairness demands it, and also
because this will ensure progress, safety and justice for the white
man,'' he said.
   He said the governing National Party wants a South Africa ``in
which the grievances of the past were dead and buried and in which
all people could walk tall.''
   Referring to policies which divide South Africans by race,
Heunis said the government remains committed ``to the protection of
those groups wanting to be recognized as groups.'' But he indicated
the government is willing to negotiate possible changes in laws
mandating racial classification.
   Government policies ``implied that all the political entities''
in South Africa could have a role in electing a head of state,
serving on the Cabinet and serving in Parliament. But he said the
National Party seeks a system ``in which numbers would not play a
decisive role.''
</TEXT>
