<HEAD>Judge Says Reported Kidnap Won't Affect Hamadi Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to ADD apparent government skepticism over kidnap
reports, television reports. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Lebanon-Kidnap, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief judge in the trial of
TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi said today the proceedings will
not be influenced by the reported kidnapping of West Germans in
Lebanon.
   A Palestinian guerrilla officer in south Lebanon said three West
German relief workers were seized in connection with the Hamadi
case. He said two were freed today but that the third was still
held.
   There was no confirmation of the report.
   ``It has already been said several times that the work of the
court cannot be influenced by such events,'' Chief Judge Heiner
Mueckenberger said in a brief telephone interview.
   Hamadi is on trial in Frankfurt in connection with the hijacking
of TWA Flight 847 on June 14, 1985. U.S. Navy diver Robert Stethem
was killed and 39 Americans were held hostage for 17 days. Hamadi
admitted taking part in the kidnapping but denies killing Stethem.
   Prosecutors have urged a murder conviction and life sentence,
and the judge has said a verdict could come this month.
   Shortly after Hamadi's arrest in January 1987, two West Germans
were seized in Lebanon. A pro-Iranian group, Holy Warriors for
Freedom, claimed responsibility for the abductions and said their
eventual releases were a ``goodwill gesture'' to win a lenient
sentence for Hamadi.
   Hamadi's elder brother, Abbas, was convicted in West Germany of
those kidnappings.
   Mueckenberger said he was not familiar with all the details of
the latest incident in Lebanon, which apparently began Thursday
evening.
   The Sunni Moslem Nasserite militia in Lebanon said Heinrich
Struebig and Petra Schnitzler were released at 5 a.m. today. 1st
Lt. Maarouf, a Palestinian guerrilla officer in charge of security
at the base where the two work, said the West Germans ``told me
that the kidnappers are keeping their colleague Marcus Michael ...
in connection with the case of Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, Hanns Schumacher, said only that
the trial ``could lead to a threat against Germans, that is clear.
But everything else is pure speculation.''
   He noted that Struebig and Ms. Schnitzler ``disappeared for a
certain period of time and then suddenly reappeared'' in April
1988. He said the government had no information about Michael.
   His comments prompted the ARD television network to comment in
its 1 p.m. newscast: ``The federal government obviously has doubts
whether the two actually were victims of a kidnapping.''
   ARD claimed the government believes it is ``peculiar'' that in
1988 the pair disappeared under similar circumstances and
reappeared a short time later.
   In 1988, Steubig and Ms. Schnitzler were thought to have been
kidnapped and held two days, but the humanitarian group for which
they work, Asma-Humanitas, denied they were taken hostage.
   It said a pro-Iranian Shiite group involved with their
disappearance apologized after discovering their identities and
sheltered them to protect them from fighting in the area.
   Another Foreign Ministry spokesman, Rainer Mueller, said
officials had warned Asma-Humanitas workers many times about the
dangers of working in Lebanon.
   There are 15 foreigners held hostage there, including nine
Americans. The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March
16, 1985.
</TEXT>
