<FIRST>r a PM-KilroyCommittee     05-05 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kilroy Committee,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Of Cult Victim Unveil Anti-Drug Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTE FE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a University of Texas
student killed and mutilated by cultist drug smugglers in Mexico
are starting a committee to lead a campaign to fight drug dealing
and drug usage.
   ``There will be change only when the people demand it,'' James
Kilroy told a group of about 600 people at a town meeting called by
him and his wife, Helen.
   ``Drugs cross state lines,'' Kilroy said. ``Drugs are a problem
defeating our nation.''
   Their committee is called Make A Reponsible Kommitment _ or MARK
_ named after their son, Mark, who was abducted from a street in
Matamoros, Mexico, during a spring break trip. His mutilated body
was found in a shallow grave on a ranch near Matamoros, the victim
of a drug smuggler cult that believed human sacrifice would protect
their drug operation.
   ``We want to let everybody know there is a lot of outrage in
this country against drugs,'' Kilroy said. ``The only way to to
that is to try to unite all the organizations _ churches, clubs,
anybody.''
   Mrs. Kilroy said she hoped her son's death would serve as a
rallying point.
   ``I think every parent, brother and sister see their brother,
sister or son in Mark,'' she said.
   The group is calling for mandatory drug tests after auto
accidents and arrests, mandatory three-year terms in drug
rehabilitation and education for drug users and similar four-year
terms for sellers, and 10-year work programs for second offenders.
</TEXT>
