<FIRST>r a PM-OceansideQuake     05-05 0139</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oceanside Quake,0142</SECOND>
<HEAD>3.4-Magnitude Quake Felt in San Diego County</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OCEANSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake below the ocean floor
shook a wide stretch of San Diego County today, but there were no
immediate reports of damage or injuries.
   The temblor registered 3.4 on the Richter scale, struck at 7:11
a.m. and was centered beneath the seabed 27 miles southwest of
Oceanside, said Amy Branch, a seismologist at the California
Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
   The county Sheriff's Department received no immediate reports of
damage or injury.
   Two residents of El Cajon, which is east of San Diego and
perhaps 50 miles from the epicenter, called Metro Weather, a radio
service, to report shaking, said forecaster Tim Root.
   Scientists believed the temblor was an aftershock of a
5.3-magnitude quake that struck July 13, 1986, Ms. Branch said.
</TEXT>
