<FIRST>r a PM-HoffmanWill     05-05 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hoffman Will,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoffman Gave Away Fortune, Left $2,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abbie Hoffman gave away hundreds of
thousands of dollars during his lifetime, but left an estate worth
only about $2,000, according to his attorney.
   ``It's not that he didn't take in a lot of money. It's just that
he didn't keep it,'' Gerald Lefcourt said Thursday.
   Hoffman, 52, who committed suicide April 12 in his apartment
near New Hope, named Johanna Lawrenson as sole beneficiary in his
will, which was filed Wednesday in Bucks County.
   Ms. Lawrenson and Hoffman had lived together for several years.
   The 1983 will was accompanied by a death certificate listing his
full name as Abbott Howard Hoffman and his self-described
occupation as ``Jewish Road Warrior.''
   He left instructions in the will for Ms. Lawrenson to choose a
final resting place for his ashes and said disposal ``shall be as
inexpensive as possible.''
   Hoffman had several hundred dollars in the bank, a small
retirement account and personal effects of an undetermined value,
Lefcourt said. A $10,000 bank loan was covered by an insurance
policy.
   The $2,000 figure ``is just an approximate value of his
estate,'' Lefcourt said. ``I'm not sure if it's realistic.''
   Hoffman gave away ``hundreds of thousands of dollars, maybe
millions'' he had earned through his books, magazine articles and
speaking engagements, Lefcourt said.
   In 1970, Hoffman received a check for about $40,000 after
negotiating a movie contract for his book, ``Revolution for the
Hell of it,'' and immediately signed the check over to the Black
Panther bail fund, Lefcourt said. ``It didn't even go through his
account.''
</TEXT>
