<HEAD>Fire In Legislative Palace Kills Security Guard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with security guard killed, one
injured. Pickup 4th pvs, ``The state ...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A predawn fire in the legislative palace
blazed out of control for more than an hour today, killing a
security guard and heavily damaging the massive structure,
officials said.
   A Red Cross spokeswoman, Leticia Calderon, identified the victim
as Miguel Soriano, 33, who suffocated from noxious fumes.
   Another guard, Juan Arias, was treated for smoke inhalation at
nearby Balbuena Hospital. Doctors said his condition is not serious.
   Tall plumes of dark smoke rose from the marble-faced structure
hours after the fire broke out, and television showed that
firefighters were still on the scene. Fire officials said they
suspect a short circuit caused the blaze.
   The state news agency, Notimex, quoted Fire Chief Ignacio Ponce
de Leon as saying the fire damaged at least 40 percent of the
palace, called San Lazaro.
   The blaze began about 3:00 a.m., and it took more than 160
firefighters over an hour to bring the blaze under control, he told
Notimex.
   The fire destroyed the huge central chamber where Congress meets
in joint session for major official events such as the president's
annual state of the union address, news reports said. The palace
was opened in 1981.
