<DOCNO> AP890505-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1207EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0540 05-05 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polish Prime Minister Says Economic Possibilities Limited</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 5th, ``Rakowski blamed...'' to UPDATE
with report that Bush to visit Poland in July. Pickup 6th, ``At a...''
Subs 1 graf for last pvs, ``Poland's leader...'' to conform. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski
today told 1,500 Communist Party delegates vying for election that
prospects for improving the economy are limited but ``we cannot and
we do not give up.''
   Opening the last day of a two-day conference to choose
candidates and adopt a platform for new, partially democratic
elections June 4, Rakowski urged a realistic, rather than a
pessimistic, outlook on the economy.
   ``I don't want to prove to anybody that it is good in Poland. I
only want to disagree with the spreading opinion that there is not
only stagnation but also a constant decline,'' he said.
   In its first competition with independent candidates, the party
wants to present itself as champion of economic and political
reforms.
   Rakowski blamed part of Poland's problems _ which include acute
shortages of housing, consumer goods and commodities _ on the rapid
population growth from 35.7 million in 1980 to 37.8 million last
year.
   President Bush, who last month announced a package of economic
aid to Poland, will visit Warsaw in the first half of July at the
invitation of Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski, the official
news service announced today.
   Bush gave the aid in recognition of the restoration of legal
status to the independent Solidarity trade union and the scheduling
of the June elections.
   The exact date for the Bush visit was not announced in the
one-sentence dispatch by the state's PAP news service.
   At a news conference later today, party spokesman Jan Bysztyga
said the party will not announce its candidates until May 10.
Opposition candidates nominated by the Solidarity Citizens'
Committee already have been chosen.
   Also today, Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and Poland's Roman
Catholic Primate, Cardinal Jozef Glemp, met privately for the first
time in nearly two years to discuss ``what's going on in the
country,'' Walesa said.
   He and Glemp refused to discuss details.
   Walesa said he thanked the church for helping Solidarity survive
during seven years as a banned organization.
   The church helped set up the talks between the government and
the opposition that concluded April 5 with a historic package of
political, union and economic freedoms, including legalizing
Solidarity.
   Under the agreement, the opposition will vie for 161 seats, or
35 percent of the existing unicameral parliament called the Sejm.
   Elections will be totally democratic for a new 100-member Senate
that will be the East bloc's first freely elected parliament
chamber.
   The two houses will elect the president, a new office.
   Jaruzelski is expected to win owing to the party's guaranteed
majority.
</TEXT>
