<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-05 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gunners Shell Christian Enclave; New Dispute Over Cease-Fire Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Druse gunners shelled the
coast of Lebanon's Christian enclave today, and sources said there
was a new dispute on how to enforce a cease-fire called by the Arab
League.
   Beirut newspapers said Kuwaiti army Brig. Gen. Ali Al-Momen had
been appointed commander of a 321-man observer force drawn from six
Arab nations to monitor the fraying truce.
   Intermittent shellfire struck the shoreline between the ports of
Jounieh and Byblos north of Beirut, keeping the only escape routes
closed for 1 million Christians in the beleaguered enclave, police
said.
   Mortar salvos also were lobbed from positions around
Syrian-policed Moslem west Beirut into the residential districts of
Hazmieh and Ein Rummaneh in the city's Christian sector, police
said.
   They said the mostly Christian units of the army commander, Gen.
Michel Aoun, who has pledged to respect the cease-fire proclaimed
one week ago, did not return fire.
   There were no casualties reported from the new hostilities in
the latest round of Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war. The violence
has killed 278 people and wounded 1,010 since March 8.
   Two Arab League envoys _ Lakhdar Ibrahimi, an Algerian, and
Abdel-Aziz Al-Jassem, Kuwait's ambasssador to Syria _ left Lebanon
on Thursday after two days of talks with Moslem and Christian
leaders to consolidate the cease-fire.
   They said they would return late next week to work out
arrangements for deploying an Arab observer force in Lebanon.
   But chances of an early deployment of the force appeared dim.
   Moslem sources, requesting anonymity, said the Syrian-Druse
alliance served notice it would not stop shelling Christian ports
before the force arrived.
   The sources said the alliance also has demanded the force block
ships carrying Iraqi arms supplies to Aoun from reaching the
Christian enclave.
   Iraq is Syria's main Arab rival. It expressed support for Aoun
when he declared his ``war of liberation'' against Syria, which has
40,000 troops stationed in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Aoun has denied receiving weapons from Iraq.
   ``We're going to have a half truce,'' said the independent
Beirut daily An-Nahar.
   The current confrontation broke out two days after Auon imposed
a blockade on illegal militia-run ports. Militiamen of Druse
warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party retaliated by
shelling the Christian enclave's shoreline.
   The Syrians later joined the bombardment and sealed off land
exits of the 310-square-mile enclave.
</TEXT>
