<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Uganda-Strike     05-05 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Uganda-Strike,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>University Teachers to End Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers at state-run Makerere University
agreed to return to work Monday after the government promised to
look into their complaints.
   The teachers called off a three-day strike after meeting with
top officials from the ministries of education and finance.
   A member of the Makerere University Academic Staff Association
who attended the meeting said the officials had agreed to create a
committee to look into the teachers' complaints and submit its
findings by May 17.
   The committee will examine ways to improve wages,
accommodations, medical facilities, education for teachers'
children and meals, he said.
   A full professor at Makerere earns the equivalent of $35 a
month. Lecturers are paid about $300 a year.
   There are about 7,000 students at the Kampala school. Uganda's
only other institution of higher learning is the Islamic University
in Mbale that has about 500 Moslem students.
</TEXT>
