<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1307EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MississippiMarker     05-05 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mississippi Marker,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>State OKs Marker Near Site of `Mississippi Burning' Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state has approved a privately funded
historical marker to be erected near the site of the 1964 murders
of three civil rights workers whose deaths were depicted in the
movie ``Mississippi Burning.''
   Herb Anderson, program director at WKXI-AM, a black-oriented
station in Jackson, launched efforts in February to raise money for
the marker. The station so far has raised about $1,000.
   Elbert R. Hilliard, executive director of the state Department
of Archives and History, confirmed in a letter received by the
station Friday that the marker had been approved, but he said no
decision had been made on the location. The ideal spot would be
along a state highway, Hilliard said.
   Anderson said the marker may be located along Mississippi 21
near the earthen dam where the bodies of the three men were found.
   Archives officials have said that no state historical marker was
erected because public money has not been appropriated for such
markers since 1980. Hilliard had said that private groups may
purchase state historical markers for $925, but the department must
approve the marker and the text on them.
   ``It is certainly fitting that historic sites in Mississippi can
be designated with appropriate markers so that Mississippi's
citizens and out-of-state visitors can study and enjoy the
interesting heritage of our state,'' Hilliard said in his letter to
Anderson.
   Anderson began his fund-raising drive about the time
``Mississippi Burning'' was first shown in the state.
   The movie is a fictionalized account of the federal
investigation of the murders of Andrew Goodman, James Earl Chaney
and Michael Schwerner in Neshoba County in 1964. Their bodies were
found near the town of Philadelphia six weeks after their deaths on
June 21, 1964.
</TEXT>
