<DOCNO> AP890505-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-China-Press     05-05 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Press,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Give Wide Coverage to Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cracks appeared Friday in China's tightly
controlled media as newspapers gave unprecedented and even
sympathetic coverage to a huge student demonstration for democracy
and freedom.
   The development was significant because one of the main student
demands has been for a free press. Marches in the last three weeks
had received scant attention by the state-run media.
   About 300 journalists also joined Thursday's march of thousands,
adding their voice to the growing call for a freer and more
democratic China. ``Our mouths cannot say what we want to,'' read
one of their banners.
   Still, it was uncertain whether Friday's reporting on the march
would filter into other areas, such as corruption, mismanagement
and the incompetence of bureaucrats.
   Major newspapers used stories from their own journalists, a
change from the protest of April 27 when 150,000 students and their
supporters also marched to Tiananmen. The next day all of the
papers used a report from the official Xinhua News Agency, China's
most conservative media outlet.
   Unlike previous reports, several newspapers quoted bystanders as
saying they supported the march.
   The Science and Technology Daily quoted an old woman with tears
coming down her face as saying the students were speaking on behalf
of the people.
   The quote was an important one because in China the ruling
Communist Party is supposed to speak for the people.
   The article also used quotes to challenge the Xinhua report
which said only 20,000 students from 30 schools took part in the
march.
   ``More than 100,000 must be here,'' one person told the
newspaper.
   ``There must be more than 70 schools,'' said another.
   Science and Technology, a paper for intellectuals, has been at
the forefront of reporting about the movement. But it hasn't been
easy.
   Its April 23 edition, devoted to a demonstration during which
tens of thousands of students spent the night at Tiananmen Square,
came out only after its reporters threatened to quit. Ultimately,
they had to deliver the paper themselves.
   Friday's Xinhua story didn't include veiled criticism of the
movement.
   The report also mentioned the protest put on by 300 journalists,
saying simply that ``more than 200 young reporters also
demonstrated.''
   The People's Daily implicitly acknowledged the widespread public
support for the marchers, saying ``Tens of thousands of onlookers
stood by and many of them actively donated drinks and food.''
   The paper also reported that after the protesters left Tiananmen
Square some passed by its offices where they ``yelled slogans.''
   The paper, the organ of the Communist Party, has been subject to
heavy criticism by the students because it published an editorial
April 26, accusing them of trying to overthrow the state.
   The China Youth News, a relatively liberal paper, praised the
students for conducting an orderly march.
   It reported a large group of students ``are not satisfied'' with
talks held between the government and the students. However, the
article did not explain that students want the government to
conduct talks with their independent student association and not
with officially-appointed student representatives.
   It also said protests occurred in at least 11 other cities.
   The Legal Daily reported that one protest, in Xian, was actually
legal. It said the Northwest Polytechnical Institute had applied
for permission to demonstrate on May 4, the 70th anniversary of
China's first student movement, and the Public Security Bureau had
agreed.
   The Chinese constitution guarantees the right to demonstrate but
most cities have laws saying demonstrators must apply for a permit.
Technically, all of the protests in Beijing have been illegal
because students did not apply for permits.
   A senior editor at one major newspaper said the reports Friday
came out because of the pressure many journalists put on their
newspapers to publish.
   ``But behind this there is no move to change the structure of
the media in China. We are still owned and run by the state,'' she
said. ``Until that changes, I see no possibility for real
progress.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
