<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1332EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     05-05 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Urges Catholics, Moslems to Ease Rivalry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLANTYRE, Malawi (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II, reflecting the
church's concern about the spread of Islamic fundamentalism in
Africa, urged Roman Catholics and Moslems on Friday to avoid
aggressive tactics in the battle for converts.
   In a speech to Malawi's Catholic bishops on the last full day of
his nine-day African tour, the pope raised the issue of the
church's tense relations with Moslems in this southern African
nation.
   ``What is required is mutual respect, as well as mutual
recognition of those things that we share in common,'' the pope
said.
   ``Both among Christians working for unity in obedience to Christ
and among believers of different religions, there is no place for
aggressive proselytism which disturbs and hurts, still less for the
use of unworthy methods,'' he added.
   The pope quoted from his speech to Moslems in Morocco in 1985:
   ``Christians and Moslems ... have badly understood each other,
and sometimes, in the past, have opposed and even exhausted each in
polemics and in wars. I believe that today God invites us to change
our old practices.''
   There are 2.5 million Catholics and 1 million Moslems in this
country of 8 million people. The rest of the population is made up
mostly of Anglicans, Protestants and animists.
   Islam has been growing rapidly in Malawi since the early 1970s.
Financed in part by Arab petrodollars, Moslems have built hundreds
of mosques across the country.
   Tensions grew after Moslem extremists set fire to several
Catholic churches in Malawi in 1983-84. Last August, several
Catholic youths and an elderly religion teacher were forcibly
circumcised in a suburb of Blantyre by Moslem fundamentalists,
church officials said.
   Some Moslem leaders here have said they are upset that the
pope's visit to Malawi came during the Moslem holy period of
Ramadan.
   The issue has significance for all of Africa. Church officials
have expressed concern about the spread of Moslem fundamentalism in
Nigeria, Sudan and other African countries. The Vatican in February
criticized the imposition of Islamic law on non-Moslems.
   Vatican officials say the competition for converts in Africa is
crucial.
   ``A big question is whether Africa will be a Christian or a
Moslem continent 25 years from now,'' said Vatican spokesman
Joaquin Navarro. ``The church cannot compete with the billions of
dollars that is financing Islam in Africa.''
   The pope also celebrated a morning Mass for more than 100,000
people at Blantyre's Kwacha (Freedom) Park, addressed at least
60,000 youths at the Kamuzu sports stadium and met with the
Catholic laity and representatives of other Christian faiths and
other religions.
   In his homily, he urged his flock to treat victims of AIDS as
``we would treat Christ himself.''
   Malawi has one of the highest rates of AIDS in Africa. According
to local health officials, as many as 20 percent of newborn
children are infected with the AIDS virus.
   At the stadium ceremony, school children wearing colorful
uniforms danced and sang to gospel-rock music as the pope arrived
in a glass-enclosed vehicle. Young boys dressed in grass skirts,
faces striped with red paint, danced a vigorous traditional dance
in a circle, screaming and stamping their feet.
   In his address to the lay people, he briefly expressed concern
for the first time on his trip about polygamy, which is common in
Africa.
   The pope travels Saturday to Lilongwe, Malawi's administrative
capital, to celebrate the final Mass of his voyage before returning
to Rome. He has visited Madagascar, Reunion and Zambia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0442 05-05 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0442,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>House, Senate Pass Budgets, Negotiators to Seek Compromise Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf, ``We are,'' with White House reax</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate and House leaders say they expect
speedy completion of a compromise federal budget, now that both
chambers have passed mirror-image $1.2 trillion spending plans that
cause little political pain.
   Lawmakers on both sides of the Capitol approved fiscal 1990
budgets on Thursday, obediently consenting to proposals whose
foundations were laid in talks last month between congressional
leaders and Bush administration officials. With bipartisan amity
that has been glaringly absent in most budget debates, the Senate
adopted its plan 68-31, while the House signed off 263-157.
   ``We are pleased that the process is moving forward, and in a
quicker manner than in past years,'' White House spokesman Marlin
Fitzwater said today. ``We will continue to work with the Congress
on the budget and we find these resolutions provide a very
optimistic prospect for reaching agreement.''
   Supporters said the budgets were the best available solutions to
the gridlock created by President Bush's ``no new taxes'' pledge
and Democratic reluctance to slash domestic programs. Yet they
conceded that their talks with the White House, which lasted about
as long as the biblical flood, had not yielded a perfect instrument.
   ``We didn't produce what Noah did,'' said Sen. Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, ranking Republican on the Senate Budget Committee.
``Some even think we barely produced a rowboat.''
   There are few significant differences between the two plans,
mainly because overall totals for revenues, deficit reduction and
defense, domestic and foreign aid spending were cemented in the
White House-congressional budget pact.
   House-Senate negotiators will have to settle relatively minor
differences in how the two chambers would distribute money among
education, science, criminal justice and other domestic programs.
   Congressional leaders have said their goal is to complete work
on a compromise budget by mid-May, which if accomplished would be
the earliest date of completion in 11 years. That bargaining should
begin next week.
   ``We should be able to resolve our differences quickly,'' said
House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif.
   Both houses' budgets claim to chop the $163 billion deficit
expected in fiscal 1989, which ends Sept. 30, to just over $99
billion next year. The plans have been criticized, however, for
relying largely on overly optimistic economic projections,
accounting gimmicks, and one-time savings, therefore doing little
to truly ease the government's long-range deficit ills.
   ``So the heck with the next generation, and whoopee for the next
election,'' said Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C. A Hollings amendment
that would have forced $32 billion in savings by holding most
spending at this year's levels was rejected, 82-18.
   Democratic and Republican leaders in both chambers flexed their
legislative muscles all day Thursday, quashing a slew of amendments
aimed at scuttling the budgets' taxing and spending formulas.
   Among the defeated proposals were a House amendment by the
Congressional Black Caucus that would have cut defense spending,
raised taxes on the wealthy and beefed up domestic programs, and a
motion by Sen. Herbert Kohl, D-Wis., that would have given the
Senate Budget Committee three days to produce deeper cuts.
   Under both the House and Senate proposals, federal receipts
would rise by $14.2 billion next year: $5.3 billion in unspecified
taxes, $5.7 billion in unnamed sales of federal assets, $2.7
billion in higher fees for government services, and $500 million by
boosting the Internal Revenue Service's ability to collect levies.
   Defense spending would reach $299.2 billion, about $4.7 billion
below the amount President Bush sought when he presented his
original budget proposal to Congress in February. Foreign aid would
receive $16.7 billion, enough to compensate for inflation over the
last year.
   On the domestic side, $2.3 billion in savings would come from
restraining Medicare payments to doctors and hospitals.
   Another $6 billion would come from reductions in other programs
the law says must be financed, including $1.1 billion in
yet-undecided reforms in the postal service and federal pension
programs. Critics have said some of these savings are of
questionable validity, such as $1.7 billion by moving the postal
service ``off-budget,'' and $477 million by claiming savings from
unused food stamps.
   Recipients of benefit programs, such as Social Security, would
receive their regularly scheduled annual cost-of-living increases.
   Programs for low-income people such as handicapped education and
employment for the elderly would receive high enough increases over
this year to cover the bite of inflation. Programs for children,
such as Head Start and child care, would be boosted by even more.
   Federal assistance would also be signficantly beefed up for
anti-drug programs, AIDS research and treatment, space, science,
aviation and the homeless.
   The budget resolution, once the two chambers complete a
compromise, is used as a guide by Congress when it writes its
spending and tax legislation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
