<FIRST>r a PM-FoodTampering 1stLd-Writethru a0602 05-05 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Food Tampering, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Illinois Food Tampering Cases Solved, Police Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS last graf to UPDATE with federal charge filed.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say a 15-year-old who put a
straight pin in a jar of his family's baby food apparently did it
to get some attention, solving the last of three food tampering
cases reported in the state this week.
   There were no injuries in any of the cases.
   A Jacksonville family reported Monday that they found a pin in a
jar of apricot-yogurt baby food they bought last week at an Eagle
store.
   Jacksonville Police Chief Thomas Weeks said Thursday that after
investigators interviewed the family extensively and the family
agreed to take polygraph tests, the 15-year-old son admitted to
placing the straight pin in the baby food jar.
   ``I think it has something to do with his getting attention,''
Weeks said of the teen-ager. ``Apparently he had heard about the
situation in Springfield and apparently decided it wasn't a bad
idea.''
   The youth has not been charged, police Lt. Don Cook said today.
   The Jacksonville incident followed one in Springfield Friday in
which a baby sitter said she found pins in two jars of Heinz baby
food. Authorities said Barbara Rexroad reported finding the pins to
make herself look good to the parents.
   Ms. Rexroad, 42, was charged Wednesday with communication of
false information of tainting of a consumer product, a felony
carrying a maximum sentence of five years in prison and a $250,000
fine, said U.S. Attorney J. William Roberts. She was released on
her own recognizance.
   The third case was a candy-tampering hoax in the Decatur area,
police said.
   Kevin Gentry, a 26, of Lovington, was charged Wednesday with
making a false report to police. Gentry reported Tuesday that candy
he bought from a vending machine contained sharp metal pieces. He
was released on $1,000 bond.
   Gentry also is being charged with a federal felony count of
communicating false information of tainting of a food product, U.S.
Attorney Bill Roberts announced today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
