<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-US 1stLd-Writethru a0641 05-05 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0641,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan-U.S. Trade Talks End Without Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7-9 to CORRECT spelling of tariff.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan and U.S. officials ended five days
of trade talks Friday without reaching any agreement, and the
United States urged Taiwan to further liberalize its trade
practices.
   During Friday's session, Taiwan officials provided full details
of the government's plan to cut its trade surplus to the U.S.
delegation, headed by Deputy Assistant U.S. Trade Representative
Mark Orr.
   ``In many areas, the plan has made a positive contribution,''
Orr said, ``but in other areas, the plan is not as ambitious as it
could be.''
   Taiwan presented outlines of the four-year plan to Washington in
March to try to avoid possible trade retaliation by the United
States.
   Under the plan, Taiwan is to liberalize its financial and trade
markets to reduce this island's trade imbalance by at least 10
percent each year and gradually cut import tariffs until they
average 7 percent in 1992.
   Last year, Taiwan registered a trade surplus of $10.4 billion
with the United States.
   However, the U.S. delegation said the plan still allows Taiwan
to maintain high tariffs on agricultural products. The United
States also called for the lifting the ban on Taiwan's imports of
several agricultural products.
   Taiwan's import tariffs for agricutural items currently average
25.99 percent and will be lowered to 19.82 percent in 1992 under
the action plan.
   Officials here argued that the government can only agree to
smaller tariff cuts in agricultural items to protect the interests
of local farmers.
   Donald Bishop, spokesman for the American delegation, said the
U.S. side recognized Taiwan's efforts in the direction of
liberalization, but ``Taiwan is still encouraged to do more.''
   He said Taiwan was also urged to open more access to the United
States to set up bank branches, insurance companies, and security
firms here.
   Last week, Taiwan was cited in a report by the Office of the
U.S. Trade Representative as one of 34 countries which allegedly
impose unfair barriers in trade with the Unied States.
   The U.S. trade representative is expected to select nations by
May 30 for possible sanctions for unfair trade practices under the
``Super 301'' provision of the U.S. Omnibus Trade Act. Many believe
Taiwan, which ranked fourth among the 34 countries may be placed on
the priority list.
   The United States accuses Taiwan of maintaining barriers through
import licensing, limits on access to the insurance market,
agricultural export susidies, ineffective intellectual-property
protection and monopoly practices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
