<SECOND>AM-Iran-Germany,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tehran Office of German Airline Attacked</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tehran office of the West German
airline Lufthansa was attacked by an unidentified group of people
while it was closed Friday for the Moslem weekend, Iran's news
agency reported.
   The office ``sustained some damage,'' said the official Islamic
Republic News Agency. It gave no details.
   The incident followed calls in Iranian newspapers for expulsion
of West German diplomats from Tehran reflecting an anti-Western
trend that is being fueled by a fundamentalist revival.
   The Farsi-language Kayhan daily said last month that West German
diplomats in Iran were ``spies disguised as diplomats.''
   Iranian Prime Minister Hussein Musavi said a few days earlier
that West Germany was implicated in a CIA spy network allegedly
uncovered by Iranian intelligence.
   He said that a network of Iranian agents working for the U.S.
Central Intelligence Agency had been exposed, many of whom were
communicating with the agency through West German embassies in
Europe.
   Intelligence Minister Mohammad Mohammadi-Reyshahri later said
the spies were linked with the American military base in Wiesbaden,
West Germany, where many had received training.
   Iran also has accused West Germany of supplying its enemy Iraq
with technology to build long-range missiles and chemical weapons.
   Before relations deteriorated, West Germany was favored by
Tehran to assist in ambitious reconstruction efforts planned after
the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the eight-year Iran-Iraq war.
   West Germany joined the other European Economic Community
nations in temporarily recalling its ambassador from Tehran to
protest Iranian leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's Feb. 14 death
sentence against British writer Salman Rushdie, for allegedly
blaspheming against Islam in his novel, ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Iran later severed ties with Britain over the affair.
</TEXT>
