<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-US     05-05 0631</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-US,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Calls On Palestinians To Kill Americans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran on Friday called for a worldwide
campaign of terror against Americans and urged Palestinians to kill
five Westerners for every Arab slain in the Israeli-occupied lands.
   Parliament Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani, shown on Iranian TV
leaning on an AK-47 assault rifle, urged Palestinians to ``declare
open war on American interests throughout the world.
   ``Why don't you hijack planes in order to swap prisoners in
Israeli hands, or blow up factories in Western countries?'' he said
in a sermon during the weekly Shiite Moslem prayer session at
Tehran University.
   Rafsanjani, whose emotional speech was broadcast on Tehran Radio
and monitored in Nicosia, was interrupted by thousands of Shiite
worshipers who chanted ``Death to Israel!''
   In Washington, White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Rafsanjani's comments were ``appalling'' and ``another step
backwards for Iran from the community of civilized nations.
   ``It is an exhortation for Palestinians to commit terrorism and
only serves to confirm that terrorism remains an integral feature
of Ayatollah Khomeini's regime,'' he said.
   Fitzwater said the United States would hold Iran responsible for
any attacks on American interests or citizens.
   He compared the comments to Iran's threats against British
author Salman Rushdie, author of the book ``The Satanic Verses.''
Many Moslems say the book blasphemes Islam and Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini has called for the author to be killed.
   After Rafsanjani's remarks, the official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported that the Tehran office of the West German airline
Lufthansa was attacked Friday while it was closed for the Moslem
weekend.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, gave no details but said the
office ``sustained some damage.''
   In his remarks, Rafsanjani stressed that the United States
should be singled out as Israel's main backer but that Britons and
Frenchmen also should be targets.
   ``If for every Palestinian martyred in Palestine (the
Palestinians) kill five Americans, Britons or Frenchmen outside,
the Zionists would not dare continue these wrongs,'' Rafsanjani
said.
   ``It isn't so hard to kill Americans or Frenchmen, because
they're all over the globe. It's a bit difficult to kill Israelis,
because there aren't as many of them around in other parts of the
world,'' he said.
   At least 460 Palestinians and 20 Israelis have died in the
17-month-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, which Israel seized from Jordan and Egypt in the
1967 Middle East war.
   Rafsanjani denounced Palestine Liberation Organization leader
Yasser Arafat's peace initiative, in which he has renounced
terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   The speaker said Israel and its allies ``will never allow the
formation of ... a Palestinian state. It is impossible.''
   The extremist remarks by Rafsanjani, which came on the last
Friday of the Moslem fasting month of Ramadan, underlined a new and
growing anti-Western trend in Iran that is part of a radical
resurgence.
   Khomeini, soon after coming to power in the 1979 Islamic
revolution, set aside May 5 as Qods Day, the Arabic name for
Jerusalem. He has called on Islamic nations to free Jerusalem,
Islam's third holiest city after Mecca and Medina, from Israeli
rule.
   As Rafsanjani spoke, Iran's official Islamic Republic News
Agency reported that millions of Iranians took to the streets in
Tehran and other cities to pledge support for the Palestinians,
chanting ``Death To Israel! Death To America!''
   Rafsanjani, who also is Iran's acting commander-in-chief, said
the West would now say he was ``officially called for acts of
terror.
   He declared: ``Let them say it. Aren't they already saying it?''
   ``They commit atrocities under the guise of human rights? We
will do the same,'' Rafsanjani said. ``We too will strive in the
name of our rights to defend our people.''
</TEXT>
