<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-05 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOSSBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Catherine Watkins told her husband she
loved him, but it took 45 years for Arthur Watkins to get the
message.
   The couple were bowling in Mansfield a couple weeks ago when
Lester Crumb of Mansfield appeared with five ``V-Mail'' letters
Mrs. Watkins had written to her husband while he fought in Europe
during the waning days of World War II.
   That was the first time Watkins had seen the letters.
   Crumb said he found the mail in some boxes he bought for $40
during an auction of the Edward Russell Jr. estate in Mansfield on
April 22. He said Russell probably inherited the letters from his
father.
   But how did letters mailed to an Army unit in Europe end up in
Russell's hands?
   The letters spanned the period from December 1944, the month
Watkins was taken prisoner by German forces during the Battle of
the Bulge in Belgium, to March 4, 1945.
   Mrs. Watkins continued to write after she learned on Jan. 3,
1945, that her husband was missing in action and before she found
out four months later that he was still alive.
   And therein may lie an explanation for what happened to the
letters.
   ``The postmaster knew my wife's father,'' said Watkins. ``Maybe
he thought the letters coming back might upset her and gave them to
Russell.''
   In any event, ``Something told me he was coming back,'' Mrs.
Watkins said.
   The long-lost letters will be kept in a secure place.
   ``I ought to have them laminated,'' Mrs. Watkins said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   College geology departments across the
nation have been threatened with extinction because of declining
enrollment, but they're on the rebound because of a totally extinct
subject, says a researcher.
   Brisk sales of dinosaur cereal, noodles, toys and books have
inspired educators to use dinosaurs in the classroom, said Bruce
MacFadden, a natural science curator at the Florida Museum of
Natural History who surveyed 50 colleges and universities
nationwide.
   High unemployment in the oil and mining industries and changing
academic requirements had discouraged enrollment until dinosaurs
were emphasized, he said.
   ``People have always been fascinated by dinosaurs, but they're
enjoying renewed interest because of revolutionary new theories
about these giant prehistoric creatures,'' he said.
   ``Enrollment in most dinosaur courses far exceeds other new
courses, sometimes by twice as much,'' said MacFadden, whose
research appears in the May issue of Geotimes magazine.
</TEXT>
