<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Arts     05-05 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Arts,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Sought For London Arts Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The South Bank Center, which claims to be the
world's largest arts complex, is looking for a marketing manager in
the United States after failing to find anyone suitable at home.
   ``We have not been getting the right person in response to our
advertisements here over several weeks so we are going to try in
the United States, particularly in New York and Los Angeles,'' said
Rosalyn Fry, the center's press officer.
   She said the first advertisements will appear in the Los Angeles
Times on Sunday and The New York Times on May 14. The job will pay
$40,000 a year.
   The center on the south bank of the Thames includes the Royal
Festival Hall and two other halls for concerts, a total seating of
4,300; the Hayward Gallery for major art exhibitions; and the
Jubilee Gardens for outdoor events.
   Miss Fry said the center had income last year of $51 million,
including ticket sales, shops, franchises and a government subsidy
of $18.7 million.
   The center has been under pressure to earn more to enable the
Arts Council, which distributes government money for the arts, to
reduce the subsidy.
   The center sold 2.5 million tickets for all events last year but
had 6 million visitors because entry to parts of it is free and
anyone can use the catering facilities.
   Richard Pulford, the center's general director for
administration, said he hopes to visit Los Angeles later this month
and he will interview applicants for marketing manager if the
advertisements draw a response.
</TEXT>
