<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     05-05 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Sending Top Aide To Middle East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III, in a
move to accelerate Arab-Israeli negotiations, will send a top aide
to the Middle East next week to test support for U.S. peace
efforts, it was announced Friday.
   Dennis Ross, who heads the State Department's policy planning
staff and counsels Baker on events in the region, will hold talks
in Israel and Egypt, the State Department spokeswoman, Margaret
Tutwiler, said.
   Ross will be accompanied by Daniel Kurtzer, a specialist on the
Middle East who is on his staff, and hold talks in Jordan as well,
said another U.S. offical who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   Ross will go to the Middle East from Moscow after participating
in talks Baker will hold with Soviet leaders. The search for a
negotiating formula is one of the the major regional issues Baker
intends to discuss with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Ms. Tutwiler said Ross would provide a briefing on the Moscow
talks and also look into ``the next steps in the peace process.''
   Baker has endorsed a proposal by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir for elections among Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and
in Gaza. The winners would negotiate with Israel arrangements for
temporary self-rule. Israel, Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinians
then would negotiate an overall settlement.
   The Arab League and the Palestine Liberation Organization have
rejected the proposal, while Egypt and Jordan have taken ambiguous
positions. Baker has asked all sides to withhold final judgments
until the details are worked out.
   His approach to the Soviets, another U.S. official said, will be
to ask their support for direct Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
This would mean a shift away from Moscow's persistent call for an
international peace conference.
   The United States is lukewarm to a conference unless it is no
more than a device to further direct negotiations. Since the
Soviets would be one of the sponsors, a conference could provide an
opportunity for them to wield their influence on the outcome.
</TEXT>
