<FIRST>r w AM-RFKAwards     05-05 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-RFK Awards,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheehan, Kozol Receive RFK Book Awards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authors Neil Sheehan and Jonathan Kozol
received the ninth annual Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Book Awards at
a luncheon Friday at the late senator's Hickory Hill residence in
suburban McLean, Va.
   Ethel Kennedy, widow of the late Democratic senator from New
York and 1968 presidential contender, presided over the awards
lunch in the living room of her home. Her guests included several
Kennedy children; Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., and the judges
for the book awards.
   Sheehan received a $2,500 check for ``A Bright Shining Lie,''
his Pulitzer Prize-winning book about U.S. involvement in the
Vietnam War focusing on Army officer John Paul Vann. The same prize
was presented to Kozol for ``Rachel and Her Children,'' which dealt
with homeless families in America.
   The awards were announced in late March by John Seigenthaler,
editor and publisher of the Nashville Tennessean and chairman of
the book awards. Seigenthaler said both winners reflected ``the
power of the human spirit to survive barriers of adversity and to
overcome bars of injustice, ineptitude and deception.''
   A third book, ``Within Our Reach'' by Lisbeth and Daniel Schorr,
received honorable mention.
   The awards judges who were invited to the luncheon were author
Frances Fitzgerald, journalist Jeff Greenfield, editor Ed Guthman
and historian Alex Haley. The awards were created with a grant from
scholar Arthur Schlesinger Jr., a former White House adviser to
President Kennedy.
   The awards are intended to recognize literary works that deal
with issues that were of special concern to Robert Kennedy,
including the poor and powerless in American society.
</TEXT>
