<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-EasternEurope     05-05 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Eastern Europe,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush to Travel to Eastern Europe to Demonstrate Support for Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, making the first trip to
Eastern Europe by a U.S. president in more than 11 years, will
visit Hungary and Poland in July to demonstrate support for their
political and economic reforms, the White House said Friday.
   The stops, most likely to fall July 11-13, will come immediately
before Bush arrives in Paris for the annual economic summit of the
world's seven richest nations. The summit will be July 14-16.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said other
countries may be added to Bush's itinerary after Paris. Likely
candidates include Portugal and the Netherlands.
   ``I look for a lengthy and productive trip,'' Fitzwater said.
   The possibility of a Bush visit to Yugoslavia was raised by
sources close to the Yugoslav government. The sources said
prospects of a Bush visit will be discussed soon. However, White
House officials said privately that such as stop was unlikely.
   Announcing the stops in Warsaw and Budapest, Fitzwater said that
the United States has been trying ``to prod movement towards
democracy and economic incentives in Poland.
   ``This is an opportunity for the president to reinforce the
United States' commitment, to express directly to the Polish people
our support for the direction in which they are moving, express our
support for Solidarity and the work of Lech Walesa,'' Fitzwater
said.
   ``And the president's very personal interest in this should make
this a very interesting trip,'' he added.
   Bush has frequently talked about being deeply moved by his
September 1987 visit to Warsaw, where he met with Walesa and the
mother of a slain Roman Catholic priest.
   Bush will be only the third sitting U.S. president to visit
Eastern Europe since World War II. The last was Jimmy Carter who
went to Poland in December 1977. Richard M. Nixon also visited
Poland and Romania.
   In September 1983, as vice president, Bush went to Yugoslavia,
Romania and Hungary.
   Hungary and Poland, military allies of the Soviet Union, are
undergoing changes in their economic and political structures that
are seen here as promising.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III met in Vienna earlier this
year with the Hungarian and Polish foreign ministers and authorized
U.S. officials to speak positively of developments in the two
countries.
   Hungary is making big strides in economic changes, and even has
a small stock market in operation, while Poland has recognized the
independent trade union movement Solidarity.
   On April 17, Bush announced economic incentives to reward Poland
for steps taken toward democracy and to encourage further political
and economic reforms. The package included asking Congress to lower
tariffs on certain Polish imports and seeking congressional
approval of U.S.-guaranteed loans to stimulate private investment
in Poland.
   The president also announced a new U.S. willingness to work with
other Western financial leaders to help Poland deal with its $38
million foreign debt.
   Fitzwater did not release any details of Bush's trip, but
sources said the initial itinerary calls for Bush to spend a day in
Budapest and a night in Warsaw before the Paris meeting.
</TEXT>
