<FIRST>r a AM-DefenseProbe     05-05 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Probe,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Unisys Aide Sentenced in Chappell Contribution Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Unisys Corp. representative was
ordered to perform 200 hours of community service Friday for
concealing illegal political donations from defense contractors to
a congressman.
   Robert D. Barrett, 55, who is cooperating with the Justice
Department's ``Ill Wind'' investigation of Pentagon procurement
fraud, was given a suspended three-year sentence and placed on two
years' probation by U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton.
   Barrett was sentenced for his admissions that he concealed from
the Federal Election Commission two $1,000 donations he collected
from defense firms and funneled to the re-election campaign fund of
the late Rep. William Chappell Jr., D-Fla.
   Barrett pleaded guilty Jan. 27 to conspiring to defraud the FEC
and causing a false report to be filed with the agency to conceal
the donations.
   Chappell, who was not charged in the case, denied ever knowing
his campaign had received illegal corporate donations. Chappell,
who died last month, was defeated for re-election in a close vote
last fall.
   During the brief sentencing hearing, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Joseph Aronica said Barrett's cooperation with government
prosecutors ``resulted in the rapid movement of the investigation
and has opened up other areas of investigation.''
   Several Unisys officials had entered guilty pleas as a result of
Barrett's cooperation, Aronica noted. The prosecutor did not oppose
a defense request that Barrett be placed on probation.
   Among those whose convictions Barrett helped obtain was that of
Charles F. Gardner, a former general manager of Unisys's
surveillance and fire control systems divsion in Great Neck N.Y.
   Gardner has pleaded guilty to bribery, conspiracy and filing
false statements. He has admitted bribing Melvyn Paisley, a former
assistant Navy secretary for research, engineering and systems, by
purchasing Paisley's Sun Valley, Idaho, condominium at an inflated
price.
   Paisley has not been charged, even though he is under
investigation.
   At Friday's hearing, defense attorney James Bensfield said
Barrett ran afoul of the law when he followed Gardner's orders.
``Basically, he was carrying out the only orders of his only boss
in the company at the time,'' Bensfield said.
   ``We're not talking about bribes here. We're not talking about
the misuse of sensitive procurment information,'' Bensfield said.
   Barrett told the judge, ``I made the mistake of trying to be a
good soldier ... I've learned a lot this last year. I'll never make
the same mistake again.''
</TEXT>
