<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1920EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Baltics     05-05 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Estonians Clean Out Leadership, Latvians Mull Language Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Estonian Communist Party has removed 22
officials in a bid to halt its own waning popularity, officials and
journalists said Friday.
   The housecleaning strengthens newcomers to Estonian party
leadership who are generally more progressive and tend to support
the tiny Baltic republic's declaration of sovereignty.
   The 22 dropped from the Central Committee on Thursday already
had either left the republic or retired, said Estonian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Valle Feldman. The group included former party
chief Karl G. Vaino, Feldman said.
   Estonian People's Front leader Marju Lauristen, who spoke at
Thursday's party meeting, accused some of the retiring members of
involvement in the deportation of tens of thousands of Estonians to
Siberia and the Far North in the 1940s and 1950s.
   Lauristen, also a Communist Party member, said several of the
retirees were ``big bosses who participated in the deportations,''
Estonian radio reporter Sulev Halek said in a telephone interview.
   Feldman said the Communist Party's declining popularity was a
factor in Thursday's action. A recent public opinion poll in
Estonia found that more than 50 percent of residents support the
People's Front, a grass-roots nationalist group, while only 7
percent back the Communist Party, he said.
   The Estonian Communist Party ``must now take radical steps and
quickly work out a program'' if it wants to hold its own among
other political groups that are flourishing in Estonia, Feldman
said.
   The 22 were removed ``according to their own request'' in a move
similar to the housecleaning last week in Moscow that dropped 110
former officials from the national Communist Party's leadership, he
said.
   ``They were, to a great degree, responsible for the sad position
we're in now, so of course they should take the consequences for
it,'' Feldman said.
   Vaino, who served as Estonian Communist Party chief for almost a
decade, was replaced in June 1988 after months of criticism for
inaction on pollution and corruption.
   His replacement, Vaino I. Vyalyas, is a reformer supported by
the Popular Front.
   In a speech Thursday, Vyalyas attacked several newspapers for
supporting the radical Estonian National Independence Party, which
seeks Estonian secession from the Soviet Union, said Eve Parnaste,
a leader of that group.
   Feldman said Vyalyas also criticized Interdvizhenie, a largely
Russian group that objects to rising nationalism and political
reform.
   In neighboring Latvia, the republic's parliament on Friday
adopted a law opposed by Interdvizhenie declaring Latvian the
official language of the republic, according to residents and the
official Tass news agency.
   The Latvian Communist Party leadership on Thursday approved the
draft law in the republic's capital of Riga despite opposition from
many non-Latvian residents, said Latvian Foreign Ministry official
Albert Liepa.
   Liepa said the law was proposed because ``in many ways, the
Latvian language has taken second place to Russian'' in much of the
republic.
   Lithuania and Estonia adopted similar language laws last year.
</TEXT>
