<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1816EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-McCarthyCeremonies     05-05 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCarthy Ceremonies,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual McCarthy Ceremonies Marked By Lawsuit, Birch Society Arrival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SOLOMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>APPLETON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A memorial for Sen. Joseph R. McCarthy,
held yearly with little fanfare, has gained attention with a
lawsuit against talk show host Morton Downey Jr. and the relocation
of the John Birch Society to this city.
   ``It will certainly make Appleton a hotspot for conservatism,
although I don't think they want to be,'' Milwaukee lawyer Thomas
Bergen said Friday. He joined McCarthy's anti-communist efforts
after the two met in 1934 at Marquette University Law School.
   For each of the 32 years since McCarthy died, Bergen's Sen.
Joseph R. McCarthy Education Foundation Inc. has honored the
Republican senator with a ceremony at McCarthy's grave at St.
Mary's Cemetery. This year's ceremony is Sunday.
   McCarthy, a native of nearby Grand Chute, led a crusade in the
early 1950s, alleging communist influence in government,
entertainment and other areas of U.S. society.
   His methods led to his censure by the Senate in 1954. He died in
1957.
   The new exposure has not been accepted well by all officials in
the city of 65,000 located on the banks of the Fox River in eastern
Wisconsin.
   ``I cannot help where McCarthy was born. In fact I can remember
the McCarthy hearings ... But I don't feel I have to comment about
it. McCarthy is dead and gone,'' said Mayor Dorothy Johnson.
   Birch Society head G. Allen Bubolz, who political organization
emphasizes fighting communism and reducing the size of the U.S.
government, said his group decided to relocate in Appleton for
convenience. It was ``just a bit of wonderful irony'' that it would
be in McCarthy's hometown, he said.
   Bergen's lawsuit against Downey directly involves Sunday's
ceremony and comes at a time when Downey is a focus of national
controversy about free-speech rights.
   A full-page advertisement that ran Friday in USA Today reads
``Burn Mort? Why not just burn the Constitution. We believe in Mort
... We believe in freedom.'' It is signed by 25 people from a range
of professions, including real estate developer Donald Trump,
entertainer Robert Goulet, Harvard law professor Allen Dershowitz.
   The suit filed this week in Outagamie County Circuit Court seeks
$110,000, claiming Downey promised Jan. 16 to be a guest speaker at
the ceremony and then withdrew in April.
   Downey said Friday he talked with Bergen in January and told him
he would speak at the McCarthy ceremony only if he did not have a
schedule conflict.
   ``What do they have to do, sue people to get people to come
there?'' Downey asked during a phone interview from his New York
office.
   ``I made an oral agreement with Mr. Bergen ... that I would
appear if the dates did not conflict and the dates conflict,'' he
added. ``As much as I would like to be there I cannot because I
have contracts, written contracts. Now Mr. Bergen, being a lawyer,
should understand that.''
   Bergen said Downey's oral contract constituted the same binding
agreement as a written contract under Wisconsin law.
   Bergen also said Downey's office had told him it would send a
videotape of the talk show host to use at the ceremony, but it was
not received.
   Michael O'Brien, a history professor at University of Wisconsin
Fox Valley Center in Menasha and author of a book on McCarthyism,
dismissed renewed interest in McCarthy and the Birch Society as
fleeting.
   ``I don't think there is a rebirth of McCarthyism. I think it's
a pretty shallow thing on the whole,'' he said.
   ``It was more of an accident that Joe McCarthy was born here and
more of an accident that the John Birch Society is moving here,''
O'Brien said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1558EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-NATO 1stLd-Writethru a0689 05-05 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-NATO, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Kohl Talk by Phone; No Resolution in Missile Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Norwegian prime minister in 2 grafs at end</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's spokesman accused the Soviet
Union of working ``assiduously'' to divide NATO partners on Friday,
as Bush and West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl conferred without
apparent progress in a dispute over short-range missiles in Europe.
   The two leaders' 20-minute phone call did little to settle
differences concerning Kohl's support for East-West talks on
eliminating battlefield nuclear weapons from Western Europe, said
White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``The United States' posture has not changed,'' Fitzwater said.
He said Kohl initiated the phone call.
   ``Discussions that would lead to a ... de-nuclearization of
Europe would not be welcome,'' Fitzwater added.
   The spokesman voiced sharp skepticism toward peace initiatives
by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and suggested the Soviets
are seeking to exploit the current NATO rift.
   ``The Soviets have worked assiduously to try to divide the
alliance. General Secretrary Gorbachev has made any number of
proposals trying to convince people that there is no longer a
threat from the Soviet Union. And we are very wary of that
approach,'' Fitzwater said.
   In Vienna, Soviet and East German diplomats used Friday's
resumption of East-West talks on conventional weapons to emphasize
Warsaw Pact support for parallel talks on reducing short-range
nuclear weapons.
   East German Ambassador Klaus-Dieter Ernst insisted such
negotiations are vital to Germans, telling a news conference: ``The
shorter the range of the rockets, the more dead Germans.''
   West Germany and some European NATO members want superpower
talks on reducing tactical nuclear weapons, but the United States
and Britain oppose such talks at least until the Soviet superiority
in conventional weapons is erased.
   The Bush administration also wants to modernize the aging
arsenal of Lance missiles clustered in Western Europe, many of them
in West Germany.
   Fitzwater said Friday that while the United States is open to
talks within NATO on resolving the rift, ``it does not appear a
basis for agreement is there.''
   Of Friday's Bush-Kohl phone conversation, Fitzwater said, ``I
would not characterize it as moving the situation one way or
another.''
   The flap threatens to disrupt a North Atlantic Treaty
Organization summit late this month, called to celebrate the
alliance's 40th anniversary.
   But Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, who met with
Bush this week, predicted a solution would be found at the summit,
based on a linkage between cuts in conventional and short-range
nuclear arms agreed on by the allies last year.
   Speaking at the National Press Club, Brundtland said Friday,
``We can negotiate for lower levels both in conventional and
short-range (weapons), and I do think it is possible to reach
common ground on that basis.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
