<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AfricaPerformers     05-05 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa Performers,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>From Pygmy Dancers To Electric Guitars, `Africa Oye!' Runs Musical
Gamut</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kandia Kouyate, in flowing, sequined gown and
matching turban, glides onstage singing tales of her West African
people.
   Coming to the stage of Boston's Opera House after Pygmy dancers,
Nigerian horn players and Pende dancers from Zaire, Kouyate is the
diva of ``Africa Oye!'' a presentation of traditional and modern
African music that launched a 10-week U.S. tour Thursday night.
   She sings in her own language of the centuries-old history of
the Mandingue people, a technique of oral history that makes her a
virtual walking library.
   ``Don't even try to pierce the mystery that the Mandingue hides.
   ``Don't disturb the spirits at their eternal rest.
   ``Don't enter dead cities to question the past,'' reads a
translation of her song provided by the show's producers.
   Although the sell-out crowd of 2,600 may not understand the
words, her rich, high voice brings it to its feet.
   After five concerts in Boston, the tour goes on to New York,
Baltimore, Washington, San Antonio and Los Angeles.
   For the performers, it is an odyssey as much as a tour since
many are seeing skyscrapers, elevators and superhighways for the
first time.
   ``In my country, the dancers and musicians are repressed because
it is thought to be primitive,'' said Botika Ekalaka, a member of
the Batwa-Ekonda Pygmy performers, speaking in French through an
interpreter. ``It's quite extraordinary to find it appreciated
here.''
   Ekalaka said of the evening's performance that he had never seen
so many people together in one place.
   For some participants, ``Africa Oye!'' is not the first time
they've appeared on stage. Pop singer Papa Wemba has toured the
world with his nine-piece band playing a blend of African rhythms
and Western instruments.
   Kouyate has been broadcast across Africa and performed on
television.
   The show, more than two years in the making, is no mere
collection of African music, its producers say. They scoured remote
regions of Africa for the masters of various traditional and more
modern musical techniques. Among the 52 participants in nine groups
are artists from Zaire, Senegal, Mali, Guinea and Niger.
   ``The key to this is the variety, the musical sophistication and
the raw power,'' said Mel Howard, producer of the American tour.
``African art is very direct. It doesn't go to the mind for
analysis. It goes directly to the emotions.''
   Some of the performers began their pieces on the stage and in
the audience creating a thunderous stereo effect.
   ``One of our tests is to keep the audience where they are,
because there is a tendency for an audience to join in,'' said
Jeremy Alliger, head of an avant-garde performance group called The
Dance Umbrella, which is presenting the Boston shows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
