<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Suriname     05-05 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Suriname,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Strike Paralyzes South American Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARAMARIBO, Suriname (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers protesting an ailing economy
and the military's role in the government staged a general strike
Friday, shutting down schools, businesses and mass transit.
   No violence was reported, but streets in Paramaribo, the
capital, were crowded with private cars and pedestrians curious
about the success of the strike.
   Employees reported for work at the state-run Suriname Aluminum
Corp., the former Dutch colony's main source of foreign revenue,
and at the government power company. Police and firefighters were
exempt from the strike.
   The 24-hour general strike called by four labor federations
closed about 80 percent of businesses, schools and government
offices. Public transportation, including buses and river ferries,
was halted.
   The strike was called to show discontent with the government of
President Ramsewak Shankar, who took office in January 1988 after
almost eight years of military dictatorship.
   Labor leaders said they called the strike to protest the
deteriorating economy, which includes 60 percent inflation, and
growing drug trafficking.
   Union leaders also want Shankar to rein in the politically
powerful 3,000-man army. Civilian leaders have little control over
the military, and army critics and human rights leaders are often
arrested by military police.
   Another aim of the strike was to press the Netherlands to renew
a $1.5 billion aid program begun in 1975, when Suriname gained
independence.
   The Hague suspended aid after the military killed opposition
leaders in late 1982. Negotiations over renewal have stalled, with
Suriname objecting to the Netherlands' demand for more control over
how the money is spent.
</TEXT>
