<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     05-05 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Send U.S. Observers for Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, over Panamanian objections,
will send a 14-person commission to observe what he predicts will
be fraudulent elections in the Central American nation Sunday, the
White House said Friday.
   The observers, led by Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., will leave
Saturday and fly to a U.S. air base in Panama to avoid that
nation's visa requirements, said White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater.
   Naming the observer panel is part of the Bush administraion's
strategy to focus world attention on the election in Panama, where
the United States has tried unsuccessfully for more than a year to
get Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to relinquish power as the
country's de facto ruler.
   Panamanian officials have made it clear the offical U.S.
observer team would not be welcome.
   One U.S. official noted that if Panama blocks the U.S. observers
from visiting polling places, the action would serve the
administration's purposes of casting Noriega in a bad light.
   Bush and administration officials have predicted Noriega will
steal the election for his presidential candidate, Carlos Duque.
They cite numerous instances of registration and ballot
improprieties in the election preparations.
   Fitzwater said U.S. officials ``have informed the appropriate
authorities'' in Panama about the team's arrival. However, he said
he did not know how the Panamanians had responded.
   ``We're sending them in without visas. They probably won't have
to have them,'' Fitzwater said.
   But reports from Panama have quoted officials as saying the
observers would not be welcome and that only those invited by the
government will be allowed to observe the balloting.
   ``That in itself would be a comment on the `free and open'
nature of their elections,'' Fitzwater said when asked about
Panamanian objections to a U.S. team.
   ``We would expect this delegation to be able to observe many
aspects of the election. ... We expect they will have access to a
number of opportunities'' to view the polling places,'' Fitzwater
said.
   ``We have every reason to believe they'll be able to carry those
out.''
   Private observer teams also have been organized, one headed by
former Presidents Carter and Ford under the auspices of the
non-profit National Democratic Institute for International Affairs
and the National Republican Institute for International Affairs.
   Other members of the official U.S. observer team are Reps. Larry
Smith, D-Fla.; Lawrence Coughlin, R-Pa.; Alan Mollohan, D-W.Va.;
Dan Glickman, D-Kan., and Robert Lagomarsino, R-Calif., plus Sens.
John McCain, R-Ariz.; Bob Graham, D-Fla., and Connie Mack, R-Fla.
   Also in the delegatin are Miami Mayor Javier Suarez, former
Ambassador to Panama Jack Vaughn, former Sen. Richard Stone of
Florida, Andrew Gibson of the Panama Canal Commission and Michael
Kozak, acting assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs.
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said the
government's electoral tribunal has released figures showing that
more than 1.18 million Panamanians are registered to vote in
Sunday's elections, ``an unbelievable increase of over 160 per cent
of the total numnber of votes cast in the 1984 elections.''
   Under questioning, she said any increase of such magnitude would
indicate the figures are falsified.
   She also said that so-called ``dignity battalions'' in Panama
are being armed to intimidate the opposition and to discourage all
thoughts of organized protest after the election.
</TEXT>
