<FIRST>r w AM-MIARemains     05-05 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Remains,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Remains of 4 More Servicemen Identified</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army laboratory has identified the remains
of four American servicemen missing from the Vietnam War, the
Pentagon said Friday.
   The four were identified by the Army's Central Identification
Laboratory in Honolulu after being repatriated to the United States
by Vietnam last December, the Pentagon added in a statement.
   All four of the servicemen were aviators in the Air Force lost
in combat over North Vietnam. The remains will be flown Tuesday
from Hickam Air Force Base in Hawaii to Travis Air Force Base,
Calif., ``for their final journey home,'' the Pentagon said.
   It said the family of one of the four had asked that his name
not be released. The other three were identified as:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Lt. Col. Charles E. Cappelli of the Air Force, born March 14,
1930, lost over what was then North Vietnam Nov. 17, 1967. He had
listed his home of record as Providence, R.I.
   _Lt. Col. Robert J. Panek Sr. of the Air Force, born June 10,
1939, lost over North Vietnam Jan. 28, 1970. Listed his home of
record as Chicago.
   _Capt. George B. Lockhart of the Air Force, born Feb. 17, 1947,
lost over North Vietnam Dec. 21, 1972. Listed his home of record as
Alexandria, Va.
   The Pentagon said the four sets of remains were among 38
repatriated by Vietnam Dec. 15. Fourteen remains from that group
have now been identified.
   With the latest identifications, 2,360 Americans continue to be
listed as missing in Indochina as a result of the Vietnam war, of
whom 1,726 are listed as missing in either Vietnam, 545 in Laos, 83
in Cambodia and six in China.
   All told, the remains of 193 Americans have been repatriated
from Vietnam and subsequently identified by the Army lab since the
end of the war. An additional 28 have been identified after
recovery from Laos and two after recovery from China.
   ``The U.S. government appreciates the increased efforts of the
Vietnamese government that resulted in accounting for these
Americans and hopes that unilateral turnover of information and
remains will continue to bring accelerated results, and that joint
investigative efforts will become increasingly productive,'' the
Pentagon said in its statement.
</TEXT>
