<SECOND>AM-People-Duke,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actress Asks For Mental Health Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Academy award-winning actress Patty Duke went
to Capitol Hill on Friday to plead for greater federal spending for
mental health research.
   Duke also delivered petitions containing 400,000 signatures of
relatives of victims of mental illness to the Senate Appropriations
subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services.
   ``There is treatment. You do get well,'' said the actress, whose
own battle against manic-depression was chronicled in the
autobiography ``Call Me Anna.''
   ``Having been through it, you don't want others to go through
it,'' she added, speaking on behalf of the National Alliance for
the Mentally Ill.
   NAMI, a network of 70,000 families whose members have been
affected by mental illness, backs a $157 million 1990 budget
increase for the National Institute of Mental Health. The current
budget is $345 million.
   ``You're asking for $502 million. That's less than the cost of
one B-2 bomber,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who heads the
subcommittee.
   ``If you want to make an impact this is the way to do it,'' said
Harkin as he accepted the petitions from Duke.
   Duke was the youngest actress to win an Academy Award when she
was named best actress in 1963 for her portrayal of the blind, deaf
and mute Helen Keller in the film version of ``The Miracle Worker.''
