<FIRST>u a AM-PerfectVictims Bjt   05-05 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Perfect Victims, Bjt,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highway Killer's Victims Played A Dangerous Game of Drugs And Prostitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Randy hikes her black spandex
miniskirt up a little further before stepping away from the doorway
and into the thick springtime rain falling on Purchase Street.
   No customers in sight.
   Gray and empty, it's a slow afternoon along the six-block
stretch of rundown storefronts and restaurants known as Weld
Square, a section of this old whaling port where the easy money is
in sex and drugs.
   The lure is strong enough to draw women like Randy onto the
streets, even as police continue a well-publicized hunt for a
serial killer who has found them such easy marks that he has
murdered at least nine in the past year, many of them single
mothers with drug habits. Two more women are missing.
   ``The girls are getting killed because they're easy to grab and
easy to lure into a car,'' said Mary, a former prostitute
struggling with a recent relapse into heroin addiction. ``And even
though they try to keep an eye on each other, there's no real
protection.''
   Big-city prostitution in crowded areas like New York's Times
Square offers protection that's missing in New Bedford.
   There are few pimps and no local by-the-hour hotels. The streets
are not busy with pedestrians.
   In New Bedford, prostitution is a business conducted away from
people, often in cars parked under railroad trestles or in shadowy
alleys.
   City Clerk Janis Davidian likened the Weld Square strip to a
shopping mall, where any stranger can take a highway off ramp to
easy sex.
   ``It's a small-town kind of prostitution, not sophisticated,''
she said. ``But anyone who is required by their job to get into
cars with strangers is certainly vulnerable.''
   Recent affidavits filed in a case against a New Bedford-area man
charged with several assaults paint a vivid picture of the dangers
the women face.
   Twelve prostitutes interviewed by state police provided
strikingly similar portraits of violence against them by the
26-year-old man, who appeared Friday in district court.
   They said he would pick them up in his truck and promise drugs
or money. He would take them to a cemetery and force them into sex.
He didn't pay and, to protect their business, the women didn't
complain to authorities until state police sought them out as part
of the serial killings investigation.
   ``Their relationship to drugs is what ties these women together.
Men turn to crime and women turn to prositution,'' said Debra
Robbin, director of the New Bedford Women's Center. ``It's a
survival tactic borne out of desperation. It's not a career
choice.''
   Norman, a general contractor and longtime resident of Weld
Square, says he has never been a customer but has watched his
sister-in-law and other friends turn to prostitution as they
wrestle powerful addictions to heroin and cocaine. ``You start out
selling a little and then you sell a little more,'' said Norman,
who like most other residents interviewed asked that his last name
not be used. ``Then all of a sudden all you've got left to sell is
yourself. That's when they become back-alley girls. If you can give
them 15 minutes and $20 then you've got a deal and they've got a
fix.''
   Mary, who said she straightened out six years ago after deciding
to go back to school and get a teaching degree, said drugs are what
push scores of prostitutes to endure constant threats and repeated
assaults.
   ``When somebody is sick from needing a fix, they are in a
tremendously vulnerable position,'' she said. ``All they need is
someone _ I don't care who it is _ to offer them a little bit of
dope, just a little bit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
