<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0500,0550</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WEST ALTON</HEAD>
<HEAD>Investigators: Parents Are Suspects, Arrests Forthcoming</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with parents suspects. Picks up
6th graf, `Police refused...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a 6-week-old girl whose body
was found in a trash barrel in Missouri are suspects in the death,
investigators said today.
   Robert and Paula Sims had told authorities the baby was abducted
much like another infant daughter three years ago who also was
found dead.
   ``The focus of the investigation is now leading to the
parents,'' said Detective Sgt. Rick McCain of the Alton Police
Department. ``An arrest is forthcoming.''
   But McCain did not say when an arrest might be made.
   He said the parents had never been ruled out as suspects because
of the similarities between Heather's disappearance and that of
their firstborn daughter, Loralei, in 1986.
   A thorough search late Thursday of the couple's home and two
vehicles, and the home of Mrs. Sims' mother, produced valuable
evidence, McCain said.
   Authorities broke windows to get into the Sims home in this town
several hours after an autopsy across the Mississippi River in West
Alton, Mo., confirmed the identity of the body found there.
   The Simses were not at home, but went to the Alton police
station to answer questions later Thursday, said West Alton Sgt.
Rick McCain.
   Police refused to say what they were looking for at the home.
   Dr. Mary Case, the St. Charles County medical examiner, would
not comment on Heather's cause of death, but said it was a homicide.
   At the old lock and dam, a popular spot for fishing and boating
30 miles north of St. Louis, at least two dozen federal, state and
local investigators, assisted by dogs, searched for evidence where
Heather's body was found.
   ``We really want to solve this case, that's all we're worried
about right now,'' said a sheriff's officer who helped seal off the
area and did not want to be identified. ``We've got a whole bunch
of people here because solving this case is our top priority.''
   A fisherman found the baby's body Wednesday night. He searched
the barrel and found the body in a plastic bag after he saw someone
acting suspiciously, said St. Charles County Sheriff Ed Uebinger.
   Uebinger refused to say whether the fisherman had been able to
describe the person seen near the barrel.
   The couple told police that a masked man approached Mrs. Sims
while she was taking out trash Saturday night, and that the gunman
forced her back into the home, knocked her unconscious and took the
infant. Sims said he was at work at the time.
   In June 1986, the Simses, who then lived in Brighton, Ill.,
reported to police that an armed intruder barged into their home _
again while Robert Sims was at work _ and took their 13-day-old
baby, Loralei.
   Loralei's remains were discovered a week later near the couple's
home. The cause of death never was determined and no one was
charged. Investigators have said the Simses were suspects, although
the couple denied any involvement in the baby's disappearance.
   The couple has a 15-month-old son.
</TEXT>
