<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2101EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-JapanFighter     05-05 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan Fighter,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engine Production for FSX Is Unresolved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese co-production of American-designed
jet engines is a ``viable alternative'' for the FSX fighter plane,
but the issue remains to be firmly resolved, Pentagon officials
told Congress Friday.
   The officials sought to assure a House panel, however, that
manufacturing technologies for critical engine components would not
be provided to Japan.
   Under the $7 billion FSX deal, St. Louis-based General Dynamics
and Japan's Mitsubishi Heavy Industry are to jointly co-develop and
co-produce a new fighter, based on the U.S. F-16, for deployment by
Japan in the late 1990s.
   Congressional critics have charged that the agreement amounts to
a ``giveaway'' of valuable advanced technology that may be used by
Japan to propel its own aircraft industry into head-to-head
competition with the United States. They say Japan instead should
buy American-made F-16s and help reduce the $55 billion trade
deficit with Japan.
   Resolutions of disapproval to try to stop the deal have been
introduced in the House and Senate. Even if the resolutions were
passed, however, it would require a two-thirds vote of both houses
to override a likely veto by President Bush.
   The engine issue arose at a hearing before the House Banking
subcommittee on economic stabilization, chaired by Rep. Mary Rose
Oakar, D-Ohio.
   Glenn A. Rudd, deputy director of the Pentagon's Defense
Security Assistance Agency, said jet engines for six FSX prototype
planes to be built under the development phase of the project would
be provided a U.S. manufacturer _ either Pratt &amp; Whitney or General
Electric.
   Oakar asked if the ``real goal'' of the Japanese was to
manufacture as many of the engines as possible in Japan when the
FSX goes into production about five years from now. Current plans
call for 130 aircraft to be built.
   Rudd replied: ``I think the Japanese certainly would have an
interest in licensed co-production under the production phase'' of
the project. He added: ``We have agreed with the Japanese orally
that that is a viable alternative.''
   The engine question will not be firmly decided, Rudd said, until
a separate U.S.-Japan memorandum of understanding is negotiated
covering the production phase.
   Another Defense Department official, Air Force Lt. Gen. Ronald
Yates, said that if co-production of the engines is undertaken, the
United States does not intend to transfer to Japan proprietary
manufacturing processes used for critical components.
   Asked whether the Japanese could simply copy the American
manufacturing technologies, Yates said: ``The metallurgy is in fact
not something that you can reverse-engineer.''
   In another development, Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., renewed
his criticism of the Pentagon's role in negotiating the FSX deal
during the Reagan administration without consulting the Commerce
Department.
   After the Bush administration took office, Commerce Secretary
Robert Mosbacher expressed concern over economic implications of
the agreement, prompting Bush to send the deal back to Tokyo for
``clarifications'' on the U.S. share in the project and technology
transfer questions.
   Danforth said ``one thing in this whole mess is abundantly
clear: we must never go through such a flawed process again. My
concern is that we have zero assurance that this won't happen
again.''
   Danforth and Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., have introduced
legislation to require the Commerce Department to be an equal
partner in all agreements with other countries on the ``research,
development and production of defense equipment.''
   In testimony Wednesday before the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, Mosbacher said he is now satisfied with terms of the FSX
deal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
