<FIRST>r w AM-US-Austria     05-05 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Austria,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Austrian Chancellor Says Bush Eastern Europe Trip `Very Welcome'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitzky said
Friday that President Bush's planned trip to Poland and Hungary was
a ``promising undertaking'' that could help efforts to dismantle
communism in Eastern Europe.
   Vranitzky said Bush had quizzed him about recent economic and
political reforms in Eastern Europe at a 45-minute White House
meeting. ``The president took a good deal of interest in our
assessment,'' he told reporters.
   Vranitzky said he and Bush ``agreed on the necessity that the
West should in a careful approach lend a helping hand to promote
the success'' of the Eastern European reforms.
   Bush intends to visit Austria's neighbor, Hungary, as well as
Poland in July to underscore U.S. support for the reforms.
   On April 17, Bush announced economic incentives to reward Poland
for steps taken toward democracy and to encourage further political
and economic reforms. The package included asking Congress to lower
tariffs on certain Polish imports and seeking congressional
approval of U.S.-guaranteed loans to stimulate private investment
in Poland.
   Austria, a neutral nation bordering the Soviet bloc, has been at
the forefront of encouraging reform in Eastern Europe. Bush's
visit, Vranitzky said, ``is a promising undertaking. If this visit
could lead to a deeper conviction on both sides that ending
communism should be a goal to be strived for, ... it is very
welcome from our point of view.''
   The chancellor, who heads Austria's Socialist Party and the
country's coalition government, said the removal this week of a
barbed wire fence on the Austrian-Hungarian border was ``a very
significant step'' signaling Hungary's intention to remove all
barriers between it and the West.
   Vranitzky said he had assured Bush that although Austria was
considering joining the 12-nation European Economic Community, this
``will not dilute her position of neutrality.''
   Under the 1955 State Treaty approved by the Soviet Union, the
United States, Britain and France, Austria vowed to maintain
neutrality to win the withdrawal of the allied forces which
occupied the country because of its association with Nazi Germany
in World War II.
   The chancellor told reporters that the necessary Austrian
political decisions will be made soon so that the EEC application
can be made ``in the course of this year, probably.''
</TEXT>
