<FIRST>r w AM-SpottedOwl     05-05 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spotted Owl,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forest Service Wants To Appeal Logging Injunction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Forest Service wants to appeal a
federal court injunction barring sales of nearly 1 billion board
feet of ancient timber in the national forests of the Northwest
where the spotted owl lives, according to a letter released by an
Oregon lawmaker Friday.
   Forest Service Chief F. Dale Robertson, in a letter to
Democratic Rep. Peter DeFazio, said he had ``requested that we
appeal the judge's injunction.''
   Robertson has formally asked the Agriculture Department's office
of general counsel to pursue the appeal, a Forest Service
spokeswoman said.
   Agriculture Department lawyers will review the request and make
a recommendation to the Department of Justice, which will make the
final decision on whether to appeal, said Dianne Hitchings
   Ms. Hitchings declined to release a copy of the request
Robertson had sent to Agriculture Department lawyers, adding that
such requests do not have to be made public.
   In March, U.S. District Judge William Dwyer in Seattle issued
the injuction in a suit involving challenges to the Forest
Service's spotted owl habitat management plan.
   Environmentalist charge the plan fails to set aside enough of
the region's old-growth forests to ensure the survival of the owl
and the timber industry has said that plan closes too many acres to
logging.
   Dwyer's injunction covered more than 140 sales representing
about one-fifth of the agency's planned sales program for this
fiscal year.
   The judge has set a trial for June 13.
   About 2,000 breeding pairs of owls are thought to live almost
exclusively in the old-growth forests of Oregon, Washington and
northern California. Their fate has touched off a raging dispute
between environmentalists and the region's timber industry.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service last week proposed protecting
the owl as a threatened species.
   DeFazio was in a Alaska for a House Interior Committee hearing
on the Prince William Sound oil spill and had no comment on
Robertson's decision to seek an appeal.
</TEXT>
