<FIRST>u a AM-Hatcher     05-05 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hatcher,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attorney Vows Extradition Fight For North Carolina Indian Activist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian activist Eddie Hatcher's attorney
said Friday that his client stands no chance of a fair trial if he
is extradited to North Carolina to faces charges of kidnapping 14
people at a newspaper office.
   Charles Garry told a news conference at the Hall of Justice that
he will fight efforts by Robeson County authorities to try Hatcher
on state charges of kidnapping. Garry said racism is rampant in the
mostly rural North Carolina county, which has roughly equal numbers
of whites, blacks and Indians.
   Hatcher, 31, appeared briefly in San Francisco Municipal Court
but was ordered to return May 23 after Garry has a chance to review
case documents and decide whether to pursue an appellate court stay
of Hatcher's extradition or request a full hearing before
California Gov. George Deukmejian. Garry officially joined the case
Friday morning.
   Hatcher and fellow Tuscarora Indian Timothy Jacobs were accused
of holding hostages for 10 hours in the offices of The Robesonian
Newspaper in Lumberton, N.C., in February 1988. They said they were
trying to draw attention to involvement by local law enforcement
officials in drug trafficking.
   The two were tried and acquitted on federal charges but later
charged by the state. Garry said the state charges constitute
double jeopardy.
   Jacobs pleaded guilty Thursday to all 14 charges. He was
sentenced to six years in prison, followed by a six-year suspended
sentence and up to five years of probation.
   Hatcher was arrested in San Francisco March 10 after
unsuccessfully seeking asylum at the Soviet Consulate. His bail has
been set at $1 million.
   Garry, who defended Black Panthers Bobby Seal and Huey Newton
and wrote the book ``Streetfighter in the Courtroom,'' said he
would appeal to the governor's ``compassionate side and see if it
works,'' as well as his ``Armenian sense of justice.''
   The latter was a reference to Armenia's history of genocide and
racism at the hands of greater powers. Deukmejian is of Armenian
descent and Garry was born in Massachusetts to Armenian immigrants
named Garabedian.
   The attorney said he would present ``ample, reliable evidence''
of the alleged racism in Robeson County.
   ``The governor of California could do us a great justice by
keeping Eddie Hatcher here,'' said the Rev. Leon White of North
Carolina as he flanked Garry.
   Hatcher's mother, Thelma Clark of Pembroke, N.C., attended the
hearing and news conference, wearing a gray suit and white banner
with red letters that read, ``Eddie Hatcher is my son.''
   ``If the governor of California sends my son back, he might as
well hold a gun to his head and pull the trigger,'' she said.
   The Rev. Ben Chavis, a San Francisco State University professor
and executive director of the United Church of Christ Commission
for Racial Justice in Washington, D.C., said the commission will
lobby with the public on Hatcher's behalf.
</TEXT>
