<FIRST>r i SouthAfrica     05-05 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>South Africa,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mandela Urges South Africans to Strive for Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAHM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nelson Mandela urged South
Africans to work for peace among themselves, said a colleague who
was allowed to visit the imprisoned black leader for five hours
Friday.
   Harry Gwala, terminally ill with a neurological disease, was
accompanied by his lawyer and a friend to see Mandela at the Victor
Verster prison farm outside Cape Town. He would not reveal who
initiated the meeting or give details, but he said part of the
conversation was about violence in Natal province.
   A senior Cabinet minister said Friday the government wants to
bring South Africa's black majority into Parliament and the
executive branch, but on condition that the white minority cannot
be overruled.
   Security for the 5 million whites can be ensured ``only in an
environment of progress, safety and justice for all the people of
South Africa,'' Chris Heunis, constitutional development minister,
said in a speech to Parliament.
   South Africa's 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs.
   Gwala, who lives in Natal, said Mandela gave him a message
saying South Africans should ``try and strive for peace among
themselves and to keep up their determination to bring about a new
South Africa.''
   He and Mandela, both 70, have been members of the African
National Congress since the 1940s. Until Gwala's release in
November, both were serving life sentences on convictions stemming
from their involvement with the outlawed guerrilla movement.
   Friday's meeting was their first since 1982, when Mandela was
moved from Robben Island prison to the Pollsmoor penitentiary.
Gwala told journalists he had not expected to see Mandela again
because ``we were doing life. We only had hope that we would see
each other in a free country.''
   Mandela apparently does not entertain hopes of beeing released
soon, Gwala said, but ``he seemed in good health. From what we had
heard he was very much improved.'' He said Mandela wore civilian
clothes and no guards observed their meeting.
   The Heunis speech in Parliament was a summary of proposals he
and other government officials have mentioned in recent months. He
said details of a new constitutional system must be negotiated and
offered few specifics of the new role envisioned for blacks.
   No black leaders have accepted the government's invitation to
constitutional negotiations. Militant blacks have rejected plans
put forth by Heunis, but some moderates have indicated they would
negotiate if the government freed Mandela, among others, and lifted
bans on black opposition groups.
   Speculation that Mandela would be freed after the Sept. 6
general elections increased with the Gwala visit. Previous efforts
to win his release have been blocked by the nationalist leader's
refusal to renounce violence in the campaign for majority rule.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
