<FIRST>r i AM-Pakistan-Afghanistan     05-05 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pakistan-Afghanistan,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islamabad, Kabul Trade Charges Over Missile Attack, Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan accused Afghanistan of
hitting it with a missile, and the communist Kabul government
countercharged on Friday that Islamabad and Washington were
preparing a chemical attack on an Afghan city.
   The official newspaper, The Pakistan Times, said Friday that the
Foreign Ministry summoned the Afghan charge d'affaires to protest
that a Soviet-made SS-1 Scud missile hit a refugee camp inside
Pakistan on Thursday, killing two people and wounding 14.
   However, local officials and witnesses said the blast was caused
by a bomb dropped by one of two Afghan warplanes that flew about 70
miles into Pakistan's North West Frontier province.
   No explanation was made for the discrepancy.
   Pakistan and the United States are major backers of Afghan
Moslem rebels who for the past 11 years have fought to topple the
Soviet-backed Kabul regime and establish an Islamic government.
   In Kabul, the government denied the allegation and called it a
plot by Pakistan to divert attention from the ``military aggression
and internal interference in Afghanistan.''
   An Afghan Foreign Ministry spokesman deflected U.S. and rebel
charges that communist troops were getting ready to use chemical
weapons against guerrillas besieging the eastern city of Jalalabad.
He said in a statement broadcast over official Radio Kabul that
instead, the United States and Pakistan were giving such
internationally outlawed weapons to the guerrillas.
   The statement said Kabul was ready to welcome United Nations
experts ``in order to assess these baseless allegations. ... The
Republic of Afghanistan has acquired no chemical weapons of any
type whatsoever. It does not, and will not seek to obtain such
weapons, the use of which it considers a crime against humanity.''
   Rebel commanders and some U.S. officials in Washington have
reported that troops defending Jalalabad recently received gas
masks and protective garb in preparation for the use of chemical
weapons against the insurgents.
   The guerrillas have been attacking Jalalabad, 42 miles from the
Pakistan border, since March 6.
   Soviet forces ended nine years of military intervention on the
Kabul side on Feb. 15.
   The guerrillas reportedly are preparing new offensives around
Afghanistan after Ramadan, the Moslem holy month of fasting, which
ends next week.
</TEXT>
