<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Japan     05-05 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Japan,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan, Soviet Union Report No Progress In Border Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's foreign minister ended talks with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other officials Friday without
making any progress on a bitter dispute over the Kuril Islands.
   ``The northern territories have always belonged to Japan
alone,'' Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno told a news conference.
   ``Russians are entitled to believe they are entirely Russian,''
said Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Igor Rogachev, who addressed
reporters after Uno.
   Completion of a peace treaty formally ending World War II
hostilities between the two countries and a visit by Gorbachev to
Japan both depend on resolution of the crisis.
   The Soviet Union occupied the islands north of Hokkaido after
the end of fighting in 1945 and have rejected Japanese demands to
give them back. Both sides claim the islands belong to them
historically and culturally.
   Gorbachev told Uno that Japan was using a double standard in
pressing for the islands. In remarks carried by the Tass news
agency, the Kremlin chief asked why Japan doesn't consider that its
similar claims to China and South Korea are obstacles to full-scale
relations with those countries.
   ``There must be no room for a lopsided attitude to sovereign
interests of states and the existing views of a people on some or
other aspects of its relations with other peoples,'' Gorbachev
said. ``Mutually observed balancing of interests is very important
in bilateral relations. And it is also important to avoid
ultimatums in posing some or other questions.''
   The Soviet Union is improving relations with China, opening
avenues to South Korea and seeking to boost its trade with the
booming economies of the Pacific Rim. Many Japanese companies have
operated for years in the Soviet Union.
   The Soviets have pledged to remove 200,000 soldiers from the
Pacific region as part of an overall reduction of their military
force worldwide.
   Gorbachev also blasted Japan for building up its military
potential at a time when the Soviet Union is pursuing disarmament.
   Officials in Japan are pressing for a Gorbachev visit after the
Kuril Islands issue is settled, but Rogachev said the Soviets
insist ``there must be no preconditions on either side.''
   ``The visit of Mikhail Gorbachev is on the political agenda and
it will all depend on how we advance in our preparatory work,''
Rogachev said.
   The Soviet president, in the remarks carried by Tass, said a
visit to Japan should be discussed early next year.
   Gorbachev's schedule this year is full, with a trip to Peking
for the first Soviet-Chinese summit in 30 years scheduled next
week, a trip to West Germany in June, to France in July, and to
Finland and Italy in fall.
   Uno said he would meet once again with Soviet Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze at the United Nations in September, and that
he was confident the two sides eventually could work out an
agreement.
   But he acknowledged that besides stepping up the work of a joint
commission on the problem, neither side had tabled any compromise
proposals during his visit to the Soviet Union, which began April
30.
   Rogachev said the Soviets were disappointed in Uno's reaction to
their proposal to begin Soviet-U.S.-Japanese talks on disarmament
in the Pacific region.
   He said his country views such talks as a starting point for a
broader disarmament discussion such as the one encompassing the
NATO and Warsaw Pact countries in Europe.
   But Uno said modernization and increases in Soviet military
forces ``makes us very apprehensive,'' and that ``U.S. forces exist
as a means of contributing to the stability of the region.''
</TEXT>
