<FIRST>r w AM-Briggs     05-05 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Briggs,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ambassador to Get NSC Post</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush has decided to name Everett
Ellis Briggs, now U.S. ambassador to Honduras, as the senior
National Security Council aide for Latin America, an administration
source said Friday.
   In the job, Briggs who has held several foreign postings, would
be the chief White House official on a number of key foreign policy
issues, including the Contra question in Nicaragua, U.S. relations
with Panama and military support for Latin democracies such as El
Salvador and Guatemala.
   The NSC position, with the title of senior director, does not
require congressional confirmation. Briggs appointment was
confirmed by a source who declined to be identified.
   Briggs has been ambassador to Panama from 1982 to 1986 and was
the deputy assistant secretary of state for Inter-American Affairs
from 1981 to 1982. In that State Department post, he had a hand in
shaping the Reagan administration's Central America policies.
   He has also held diplomatic posts in Bolivia, West Germany,
Portugal, Angola, Paraguay and Colombia.
   In his early days in Panama, Briggs was embroiled in controversy
when he accused by the National Guard commander of using his
diplomatic assignment to conduct spying activities and of
interfering with the country's internal affairs. U.S. officials
denied those charges.
   Briggs was appointed by then-President Reagan to the Honduras
post in the fall of 1986, serving there during the time when
disclosures came out about the Reagan administration's clandestine
efforts to aid the Contra rebels during the congressional ban on
aid.
   Relations with the Hondurans were a key factor in the private
Contra aid operation, with the Contras using Honduras as a base of
operations.
   The Bush administration has adopted a non-military approach to
the Contra issue, giving the rebel forces non-lethal aid until next
February when elections will be held in Nicaragua.
   The Contra army is encamped in Honduras near the Nicaraguan
border and the U.S. aid is to be released also for repatriation for
those who want to return to their homeland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
