<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     05-05 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Troops in Philippines To Avoid Conflict with Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military said Friday that it
seized communist rebel documents apparently calling for more
killings of U.S. military officials starting in June, the state-run
Philippines News Agency reported.
   The rebels killed U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe on April 21
as he was riding to work at the headquarters of the Joint U.S.
Military Assistance Group.
   The New People's Army said it carried out the attack because of
purported U.S. involvement in President Corazon Aquino's
counterinsurgency campaign.
   The commander of U.S. forces in the Pacific, Adm. Huntington
Hardisty, said Friday that U.S. troops will defend themselves if
attacked but will avoid taking action that will put them in direct
conflict with the rebels.
   ``Certainly, if we are under attack or if your life is
threatened, you're going to take appropriate action,'' Hardisty,
commander in chief of the U.S. Pacific Command, told reporters at a
breakfast meeting.
   ``But I will only think that would be the bottom line in any
involvement. We certainly would not put ourselves, nor our
commanders allowing our forces to be put in a situation, where
there would be confrontation with the (rebels).''
   The Philippines News Agency said the documents were seized
Thursday. It quoted police officials outside the U.S.-run Clark Air
Base, 50 miles north of Manila, as saying the attacks on Americans
are intended to ``create a propaganda impact'' for the rebels.
   Hardisty said Rowe's death and threats against Americans were
rebel attempts to grab headlines but would not deter U.S. support
for the Aquino administration.
   ``We will not be intimidated by New People's Army terror
tactics,'' he said.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt meanwhile welcomed Mrs. Aquino's
announcement that the Philippines will begin discussions with U.S.
officials before yearend on whether to extend the U.S. bases' lease
here, which expires in 1991.
   The military also reported Friday that a soldier ran amok
outside of Cagayan de Oro in Misamis Oriental province in the
southern Philippines, killing six people and wounding 14 before
committing suicide.
   It said Constable 2nd Class Ramon Cabisada fired an M-16 rifle
and grenade launcher in attacks Wednesday and Thursday on Upper
Gusa and Lower Gusa villages, then went to his nearby boarding
house and shot himself to death.
   No motive was given.
</TEXT>
