<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2134EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-NewCaledonia     05-05 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Caledonia,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Men Held in New Caledonia Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Friday they were
holding three men for questioning about the killings of two
independence leaders in this French Pacific territory.
   Police say Jean-Marie Tjibaou and Yeiwene Yeiwene were shot to
death Thursday on the island of Ouvea by Djubelly Wea, a separatist
opposed to Tjibaou's moderate policies. Tjibaou's bodyguards killed
Wea after the attack.
   Witnesses said other gunmen were involved.
   Premier Michel Rocard of France said he would fly to New
Caledonia for the funeral Sunday of Tjibaou, president of the Kanak
Socialist National Liberation Front, and Yeiwene, his chief aide.
   Rocard said New Caledonian elections planned for June 11 would
be postponed because they would interfere with the traditional
period of mourning. No new date was announced.
   Prosecutors identified those held as Paoula Wea, a nephew of
Djubelly Wea; Andre Tangopi, and Fessen Tuet. Tangopi was reported
wounded in the exchange of gunfire and was under police guard in
the hospital at Noumea, the provincial capital.
   The senior surviving leader of the front, Leopold Joredie, said
the group would continue participating in a ``peace process'' that
began last year and is to culminate in a 1998 referendum on
independence.
   ``The word of Jean-Marie Tjibaou will be respected, and we
pledge to make sure that the process is followed to its
conclusion,'' he said.
   Foreign Minister Gareth Evans of Australia said in Sydney: ``All
Australians will join right-minded New Caledonians in deploring
this shocking act of violence. Jean-Marie Tjibaou was an
inspiration to his people and one of the great apostles of
moderation in New Caledonia's recent troubled history.''
   In New Zealand, Foreign Minister Russell Marshall called Tjibaou
``a man of conviction and vision. All those of us who met him and
knew him were impressed by his courage and purposeful moderation.''
   Joredie, a witness to the killings, said he thought at least
five or six gunmen were involved.
   His organization canceled ceremonies on the first anniversary of
an assault by French military police May 5, 1988, on a cave where
separatists were holding more than 20 other officers hostage.
Nineteen hostage-takers and two policemen were killed.
   Tjibaou, Yeiwene and Joredie were in Ouvea for the ceremonies
when the shooting occurred.
   Native Melanesians known as Kanaks make up 43 percent of the
people in New Caledonia, a group of islands 1,000 miles east of
Australia, and most favor independence. Nearly all European
settlers and descendants of settlers, 37 percent of the population,
want the islands to remain part of France.
   The rest of New Caledonia's residents, Polynesians and Asians,
also generally favor staying with France. The Melanesian population
is growing much faster than the others and is expected to regain
the majority early in the next century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
