<FIRST>r w AM-ToxicCites     05-05 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toxic Cites,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Proposes 10 Waste Clean-up Sites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency on Friday
proposed 10 additional hazardous waste sites for cleanup under the
federal Superfund law, saying they pose a long-term threat to
health and the environment.
   The 10 locations will be put on the EPA's priority cleanup list
after a 60 day comment period. There 1,173 sites that already have
been proposed or selected for action under the Superfund law.
   The additional sites proposed Friday are in Idaho, Iowa,
Missouri, Michigan, North Carolina, New York, Pennsylvania and Utah.
   The newly proposed sites were identified by the EPA as Eastern
Michaud Flats Contamination, Pocatello, Idaho; Kerr-McGee Chemical,
Soda Springs, Idaho; Monsanto Chemical, also in Soda Springs,
Idaho; Sheller-Globe Corp. Disposal, Keokuk, Iowa; Allied
Paper-Portage Creek-Kalamazoo River, Kalamazoo, Mich.; three
locations, although considered a single cleanup site near the St.
Louis Airport as well as on land belonging to Hazelwood Interim
Storage and Futura Coatings Co., in St. Louis County, Mo.;
Hevi-Duty Electric Co., Goldsboro, N.C.; Tri-Cities Barrel Co.,
Inc., Port Crane, N.Y.; Publicker Industries Inc., Philadelphia,
Pa.; Utah Power &amp; Light-American Barrel, Salt Lake City, Utah.
</TEXT>
