<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Strike     05-05 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Strike,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 20,000 Copper Miners on Strike For Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 20,000 copper workers from the
official trade union alliance and from Solidarity have gone on
strike at four mines in southwestern Poland to demand higher pay,
an activist said Friday.
   Jan Sugalski, a local Solidarity activist, said the miners were
demanding a 50 percent increase in pay. He said miners earn between
$118 and $176 a month.
   Sugalski said the miners had formed a strike committee composed
of representatives of the official OPZZ trade union alliance and
Solidarity, the independent trade union. He said they remained on
the surface of the pits and were carrying out maintenance
underground.
   The strikers handed over a list of demands, all of which
concerned pay, and they were rejected by management, Sugalski said.
   Solidarity was legalized April 17 after a seven-year ban as a
result of agreements reached between the opposition and communist
authorities at round-table talks. The talks were proposed by the
government during a serious wave of strikes last August.
   Workers were striking at the Lubin, Polkowice, Rudna and
Sieroszowice mines near the city of Lubin, 203 miles southwest of
Warsaw, Sugalski and the state-run news agency PAP reported.
   PAP said the miners went on strike on the morning shift and were
joined by workers on the afternoon shift. The agency gave no
figures on the number of strikers.
   Talks between management and representatives had brought no
results by evening, PAP reported.
</TEXT>
