<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Press     05-05 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Press,0140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislator Withdraws Bill Designed to Protect Privacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Conservative lawmaker, acknowledging a lack of
support from his own party, withdrew a bill Friday to curb media
intrusion into people's private lives.
   It was the second time in recent weeks that proposals to control
news organizations have foundered.
   Parliament member John Browne said he withdrew his privacy bill
because he believed it would be defeated. It was opposed by the
Conservative government, which holds a large majority in Parliament.
   The bill was to be debated Friday in the House of Commons. It
would have given people the right to sue when certain information
was published without their consent.
   An opposition Labor lawmaker last month gave up a bill to force
newspapers to publish corrections. The governing party also opposed
that measure.
</TEXT>
