<FIRST>r i AM-Bulgaria-Farming     05-05 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria-Farming,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Decree on Farming Adopted; Concern Over Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party leaders announced Friday
that private farming will be expanded and land will be leased to
farmers for up to 50 years, the official news agency BTA reported.
   It said the measures were in a Politburo report presented by
party chief Todor Zhivkov at a two-day Central Committee on
agricultural policy that ended Friday.
   The agency also indicated there was disagreement over policy on
food prices. BTA quoted Stoyan Ovcharov, the economics and planning
minister, as telling the committee a new pricing system is needed
to stimulate production, but said nothing of agreement on such a
policy.
   As in the Soviet Union, which recently adopted similar farming
reforms, orthodox Communists worry that food prices might climb
rapidly if government purchase prices are raised and private
farmers produce more food.
   Privately cultivated plots account for only 13 percent of the
land farmed in Bulgaria, but yields almost one-third of total milk
production, about 40 percent of meat and 50 percent of the eggs
produced.
   Economic reformers argue that agriculture should be allowed
freer rein to develop.
</TEXT>
