<FIRST>r a AM-MockKidnapping     05-05 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mock Kidnapping,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teacher Files Charges Against Student `Terrorists' Who Disrupted
Class</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A University of Rhode Island professor
filed criminal charges against four fraternity students who dressed
as terrorists and staged a mock kidnapping in her classroom.
   Margaret Haggerty said Friday she brought the felony charges
because she felt the university's decision to put the Lambda Chi
Alpha fraternity on probation for at least one year was too light.
   ``My goal wasn't to put these kids in prison,'' Haggerty said in
a telephone interview. ``My goal is to give them a sense of
accountability and acceptable behavior and hope it would never,
ever happen again in a classroom.''
   Haggerty was teaching a nursing class on death and dying Dec. 7
when four men dressed as terrorists and carrying toy assault
weapons and a toy handgun allegedly burst into the room and
kidnapped a sorority president.
   The young woman willingly went with them after the fraternity
members spoke to her in Greek, said Lt. James McDonald of the
campus police.
   ``As they were leaving, the man with the handgun turned around,
about 10 feet from the instructor, and pulled the trigger,'' he
said. ``It made a popping sound.''
   For at least a decade, sorority presidents have been kidnapped
and ransomed for food, which is donated to a local charity, said
Thomas Dougan, assistant vice president for campus life.
   ``It was a philanthropic event, and this is a miscarriage of
justice,'' said one of the students arrested, James E. Pennoyer
III, who is the current fraternity president. ``We didn't do a
thing to her (Haggerty). We came in and took a student who knew we
were coming. It's totally ridiculous.''
   The teacher filed a complaint with campus police March 2 after
the university reported its disciplinary decision. The four
students, Pennoyer, 21, and David M. Jones, 20, both of East
Providence; Antonio DaSilva, 23, Pawtucket; and Michael I. Miga,
19, Warwick, were arrested and arraigned Thursday on charges of
felony assault by use of devices similar in appearance to a firearm.
   The charge carries a maximum penalty of three years in prison in
this case, since no serious injury occurred.
   The students were released on personal recognizance. A felony
screening date of June 7 was set, at which time the campus police
will turn the matter over to the attorney general's office. The
state office has not decided whether to pursue the charges, said
spokesman Tom Connell.
   Haggerty, an associate professor of nursing, said the four were
``dressed like terrorists,'' and she had no idea the incident was
part of a fund-raiser.
   ``I said, `Get out of this room. Get out of this classroom,' ''
Haggerty said. ``I was more or less in shock.
   ``It's not an acceptable way to raise money for the poor. Using
violence and terrorism to achieve a good just isn't appropriate,''
said Haggerty, who maintains she did not know the weapons were fake.
   Dougan said he felt the university's probation of the fraternity
was sufficient. The fraternity ``was extremely cooperative, they
apologized, they were extremely embarrassed. Certainly their
intention was not to disrupt or upset individuals in the classroom.
It's the strongest punishment I can give a fraternity short of
closing the chapter.''
</TEXT>
