<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Chamorro     05-05 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Chamorro,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Criticizes Sandinistas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Friday met with Nicaraguan
newspaper publisher Violeta Chamorro and criticized the leftist
Sandinista government for restricting that country's press, the
White House said.
   Mrs. Chamorro is the widow of the publisher of the widely read
newspaper, La Prensa, who was gunned down in the streets of Managua
at a time when his newspaper was harshly critical of the dictator
Anastasio Somoza.
   Mrs. Chamorro continues to publish the newspaper which has now
staked out an opposition stance to the Sandinistas who deposed
Somoza.
   She was in Washington at the invitation of the National
Endowment for Democracy, a non-profit foundation. She also met with
Rep. Frank Guarini, D-N.J., and other members of Congress to
discuss the ongoing peace process regarding the Contra rebels.
   A White House statement called Mrs. Chamorro and La Prensa
``symbols of freedom of expression and the struggle against tyranny
and dictatorship throughout Latin America, beginning with the
struggle against the Somoza government.
   Bush told Mrs. Chamorro that Nicaragua's new media law, passed
in anticipation of next year's elections, ``does not guarantee the
free-functioning of the media and unrestricted political
expression,'' and gives the Interior Ministry excessive latitude to
prosecute the media, White House statement said.
