<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-ABA-Judges 1stLd-Writethru a0716 05-05 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA-Judges, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,920</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA Can't Consider Ideology in Judges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to include comments from ABA, Thornburgh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Bar Association won't be allowed
to screen federal judicial nominees unless it stops considering a
candidate's political and ideological beliefs, the Justice
Department said Friday.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said he intended to hold the
ABA to an agreement he says it made to revert to old language in
its guidelines that doesn't specifically provide for any
consideration of such views.
   One of Thornburgh's top aides, David Runkel, said that unless
the ABA accepts the agreement, ``I don't think they will be
involved'' in screening judicial candidates.
   The ABA's Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary will be able
to resume its participation in screening professional
qualifications of prospective nominees as soon as it accepts the
agreement as described by the attorney general, Runkel said.
   The dispute broke out Tuesday when ABA leaders disavowed a
statement Thornburgh made to the House Judiciary Committee that
they had agreed to stop considering political and ideological
philosophy.
   And that position was reiterated Friday night by ABA President
Robert Raven, who said in a statement the bar group ``does not
examine and make value judgments about candidates' political or
ideological views.''
   ``Problems of wording and problems of perception are curable,''
Raven said. ``We look forward to working out mutually acceptable
language with the attorney general.''
   ``They got our language, go back to what it was in 1979,''
Thornburgh said in reply. ``That's what they agreed to and we
expect them to honor it.''
   Concern among conservatives over the ABA guideline surfaced
after the Senate's 1987 vote against confirming Robert Bork to the
Supreme Court. Thornburgh told the House Judiciary Committee on
Tuesday he shared the concern.
   The Bush administration is preparing to fill some 50 vacancies
on federal district and appellate courts. Traditionally, the ABA
has confidentially canvassed a candidates' peers to assess
professional abilities at the request of the administration.
   It advises the president of its findings and delivers a rating
to the Senate Judiciary Committee during the confirmation process.
   The issue is particularly sensitive because Robert B. Fiske Jr.,
Thornburgh's choice to be his deputy attorney general, has been
criticized by conservatives for the way he conducted the screening
process when he chaired the ABA panel in the early 1980s.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., has charged that Fiske improperly
told a liberal activist group the names of judicial nominees under
review.
   Humphrey said Fiske was guilty of ``leaking information which
was provided to the ABA in confidence to groups that use that
information to mount campaigns against persons who are not yet
nominated.''
   At Tuesday's hearing, Thornburgh credited Fiske with obtaining
the agreement from the ABA.
   Runkel said the attorney general ``stated what he believed was
an agreement and prior to that and subsequent to that, that's our
understanding.''
   During his congressional testimony, Thornburgh said ``we are
pleased that the American Bar Association standing committee has
seen fit to withdraw from an area not only contentious but in my
view improper for their consideration _ that is to say the
political and ideological views of the prospective nominees.''
   But Raven and Harold R. Tyler Jr., chairman of the standing
committee, denied that the ABA had ever considered political views
except to assess whether they affected a person's professional
qualifications.
   In his statement Friday night, Raven said ``If a candidate's
personal philosophy, however, incorporates racially prejudiced
views, for example, we woud not agree that the candidate has the
open-mindedness and freedom from bias requisite for a position on
the bench.''
   ``Our practice in this regard has remained unchanged,'' he said.
   Tyler acknowledged only that the ABA had ``expressed a
willingness'' to delete a sentence from the latest version of the
``backgrounder'' it publishes to describe the screening process.
   The sentence that has raised the ire of conservatives reads:
``Political or ideological philosophy are not considered, except to
the extent they may bear upon the other factors.''
   Runkel released copies of letters exchanged between Tyler and
Thornburgh last month that he said had formed the basis of the
agreement. The agreement was sealed in a telephone call from Tyler
to the attorney general's executive assistant, Robert Ross, Runkel
said.
   In an April 21 letter to the attorney general, Tyler wrote that
the sentence ``has generated confusion'' and charges that the panel
considers political or ideological beliefs.
   ``This committee does not believe that that is the case,'' Tyler
added. ``Nevertheless, to make that as clear as possible, we
certainly are prepared to accept your suggestion of abandoning the
language.''
   ``In sum,'' Tyler concluded, ``be assured that, to track the
earlier language, this committee does not investigate a prospective
nominee's political or ideological philosophy, except to the extent
that extreme views on such matters might bear upon judicial
temperament or integrity.''
   In an April 27 reply, Thornburgh said ``I am concerned about the
final sentence of your letter.''
   The attorney general wrote that in his meetings with Raven and
Tyler, ``I thought I had expressed clearly my view that the
Standing Committee should in fact revert to its policy statement in
effect prior to 1980, which excluded any consideration of a
prospective nominee's political or ideological philosophy.''
   ``I would hope we are in agreement on this point,'' Thornburgh
said.
</TEXT>
