<FIRST>r a AM-CincodeMayo     05-05 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cinco de Mayo,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Americans Celebrate Mexican Holiday With Gusto and Efforts at Social
Change</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   CIUDAD NUESTRA SENORA LA REINA DE LOS ANGELES DE PORCIUNCULA
(AP) _ Americans wrapped themselves in the red, white and green
Friday as they embraced the Mexican holiday of Cinco de Mayo at
fiestas and toasted a 127-year-old victory over colonialism with
cervezas and margaritas.
   Schoolchildren celebrated in the plaza at El Pueblo de Los
Angeles, where a fiesta will bring at least 25,000 people a day
through the weekend.
   ``There's lots of margaritas to be had,'' said bartender Tom
Madruga, mixing the icy tequila concoctions at the Mexican Cafe in
San Diego's Old Town, where the Battle of Puebla will be re-enacted
over the weekend.
   Similar festivities got under way elsewhere in Southern
California and across the Southwest, even on the East Coast.
   ``People are getting used to the idea. We run some flyers so
that everybody remembers May 5th,'' said banquet manager Rosalinda
Arrieta at an El Torito restaurant in Secaucus, N.J., that planned
``pinata madness.''
   Ms. Arrieta, judge of a contest to see how many fiery jalapeno
peppers customers could consume, said guessing how many margaritas
would be served during Cinco de Mayo ``would be very hard.''
   Cinco de Mayo marks the stand of an outnumbered Mexican force
against a superior French army at Puebla in 1862. Although the
French emperor Napoleon III eventually withdrew his invading army
from Mexico for reasons other than the Puebla setback, it is a
proud date in Mexican history.
   ``It's a celebration of the underdog,'' said actress Carmen
Zapata, who believes that non-Mexican Americans have adopted Cinco
de Mayo because they can identify with that spirit through American
history.
   Miss Zapata is a founder of the Bilingual Foundation of the
Arts, which named actors Edward James Olmos and Jorge Rivero to
receive its ``El Angel'' awards for contributions to Hispanic arts
at a dinner Friday night.
   ``I think that we are beginning to take our place in society
here,'' said Miss Zapata before the annual banquet, ``Ole Salsa,''
at the Biltmore Hotel.
   ``I feel that we have and will have a tremendous impact on the
American culture in the years to come.''
   But Cinco de Mayo wasn't just fun and food. The nation also
sought to deal with obligations to the burgeoning Hispanic
population.
   In Los Angeles _ a considerably shortened version of the name
originally bestowed in 1769 _ county Supervisor Kenneth Hahn
repeated his call for adding two seats to the Board of Supervisors
to boost ethnic representation. All five seats are now held by
Anglos.
   ``Hispanics comprise approximately 35 percent of the population
in Los Angeles County, but there is only a handful of Hispanic
elected officials to represent their interests. This is unfair and
unjust, and the situation must change,'' Hahn said.
   Immigration and Naturalization Service officials observed Cinco
de Mayo with festivities at a Hollywood legalization office to urge
temporary residents to file immediately for permanent status under
the amnesty law enacted two years ago.
   About 250,000 temporary residents have signed up for permanent
residency in the Western Region _ consisting of California,
Arizona, Nevada, Hawaii and Guam _ out of 1.8 million eligible
applicants, he said.
</TEXT>
