<FIRST>r a AM-PromDate     05-05 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prom Date,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shut Out of Iowa Dance, Prom Couple Gets Invitations Elsewhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBURNETT, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school student and his married
date have been getting invitations to dance at proms across the
country since they were denied permission to attend his hometown
prom.
   Jayme Wessels, 17, wanted to take Delores Washburn, 35, to the
Alburnett High School prom last Saturday but the school board
denied permission, saying it was inappropriate for a student to
bring a married date to a school event.
   A judge upheld the school, saying the school board's decision
wasn't out of bounds, and the couple stayed home. But word of their
case spread around the country and invitations to attend other
proms are streaming in.
   ``I think they've had a dozen invitations from high school proms
across the country,'' said Mrs. Washburn's husband of 19 years, Don.
   Jayme has said he and Mrs. Washburn have been friends about two
years and that he often joins her family, including Don Washburn
and four children, on social outings.
   ``She treats me as a friend and I treat her as a mother,'' he
said. Wessels' parents are divorced. He lives with his father,
while his mother lives in San Diego.
   Wessels said a Jacksonville, Fla., radio station is trying to
line up a prom for them, and one Chicago station has arranged for
the couple to attend a prom May 12. Both have agreed to pay for the
couple's airplane trip.
   ``I'm real excited about it,'' said Wessels. ``The only problem
is I have a landscaping project the following day for extra credit
at school. So, we're not sure where we're going.''
</TEXT>
