<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Fire 1stLd-Writethru a0703 05-05 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0703,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Blazes in Legislative Palace; Kills Security Guard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with cause of fire, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANITA SNOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire burned out of control in the
legislative palace for more than an hour before dawn Friday,
killing a security guard and destroying much of the huge,
marble-faced building, officials said.
   ``There is nothing left inside. Everything is charred,'' said
Radio Mil reporter Sergio Perdomo.
   Congressman Rogelio Montemayor said, ``All this is terrible,''
as he stood by an entrance strewn with shattered glass and the
fallen busts of Mexico's heroes.
   The federal attorney general's office discounted arson and said
the blaze broke out in the electrical system.
   Red Cross spokeswoman Leticia Calderon identified the victim as
Miguel Soriano, 33, who suffocated.
   Another guard, Juan Arias, was treated for smoke inhalation at
nearby Balbuena Hospital. Doctors said his condition is not serious.
   Nine hours after the fire broke out, plumes of dark smoke rose
from the San Lazaro palace. Fire officials said only embers
remained, and the fire was under control.
   Police superintendent Arturo Reyes Ojeda said a short-circuit
apparently started the fire in the main chamber, where national
deputies gather and where joint congressional sessions are held.
The fire destroyed the chamber, officials said.
   The national Senate meets in another part of Mexico City.
   The chief of the nearby Balbuena fire station faulted the
8-year-old smoke detection system.
   ``If those in charge of security had known right away there was
smoke in the building, they could have called the station, which is
one minute's drive away,'' Jose Luis Chavez said. ``The flames
would not have caused destruction of such magnitude.''
   The state news agency Notimex quoted Fire Chief Ignacio Ponce de
Leon as saying the fire damaged at least 40 percent of the palace.
At least 160 firefighters worked for more than an hour to bring it
under control.
   Perdomo said the chamber floor, which can seat more than 500
legislators, was a shambles. An ornate sculpted mural, about 60
feet long and 30 feet wide with 50 tons of bronze relief, was
destroyed, he said. Scorch marks marred the entrance to the
building, which was completed in 1981.
</TEXT>
