<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0727 05-05 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0727,0811</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half of Oil Dissipated but Many Tar Balls Remain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Yost newes conference; picks
up 6th graf pvs: `After a ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coast Guard Commandant Paul A. Yost, in
charge of cleaning up the nation's largest oil spill, on Friday
told Exxon to put more crews to work and ``do whatever it takes''
to clean Alaska's fouled beaches.
   ``What I said to Exxon this morning is that they are going to
have to produce a significantly greater effort,'' the admiral said.
   ``That means an increase in the work unit productivity'' in
Exxon's revised proposal for cleanup operations this summer. Yost
must approve Exxon's clean-up plan before it goes into effect, but
said he has not yet made a decision.
   Earlier this week, Yost criticized the plan as poorly drafted
and lacking in specifics. The state also has criticized it and
urged extensive changes. But on Friday, he called the plan
``workable ... but it needs expansion.''
   Yost was chosen by President Bush to supervise the cleanup of
the March 24 spill, when the tanker Exxon Valdez slammed into a
reef and poured more than 10 million gallons of Alaska crude into
Prince William Sound.
   ``Some of the cleanup is difficult to the point that one wonders
if restoration will ever be possible,'' Yost said.
   ``Restoration will probably be done by the Lord in the next few
years. I don't think restoration is going to be done by Exxon in
the next few months on all of the beaches. It's not possible.''
   A state official said that half of the oil in Alaskan waters has
dissipated, and much of what's left has been churned into a
taffylike goo and tossed up on beaches.
   ``Exactly how that's going to be dealt with I don't know,'' said
Bill Lamoreaux, an environmentalist with the Alaska Department of
Environmental Conservation. ``A lot of it is tar balls. The cleanup
procedures are going to have to be tailored.''
   After a wind- and rain-swept six-hour tour of the area late
Thursday, Vice President Dan Quayle said he believes ``Exxon's
going to have to do more than they think they're going to have to
do.''
   Quayle, returning from a 12-day Pacific tour, met with a group
of Cordova residents before heading to the USS Juneau, a Navy ship
used as a base of operations for part of the spill cleanup, and to
Smith Island.
   Accompanied by his wife, Marilyn, and joined by Yost and U.S.
Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner, Quayle abandoned a wooden
platform built specially for his visit, and tried his hand at
hosing some of the oil off a rocky beach.
   ``It's going to be an enormous effort,'' he said after looking
at the blackened island, an important resting and birthing area for
seals.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez slammed into a reef in Prince William
Sound on March 24, causing the nation's largest oil spill and
sullying hundreds of miles of Alaska coastline.
   Under Exxon's proposal, 364 miles of coastline will be cleansed
by Sept. 15, although nearly 200 of those miles may be left
untouched _ to be scoured by wind and wave action.
   The plan also seeks to dispose of waste by burying it, burning
it or discharging it through a wastewater treatment plant in
Valdez. The company has asked for permission to bypass some
environmental laws in order to dispose of the wastes.
   In other developments Friday:
   _The lawyer for Joseph Hazelwood said the fired tanker captain
was not drunk when he left the vessel in command of his third mate
prior to the shipwreck.
   Hazelwood left the bridge to do paperwork in his cabin below,
which was part of his normal routine, attorney Michael Chalos told
reporters after a brief court proceeding at Suffolk County Court in
New York.
   Chalos asserted the accident could have been prevented had the
Coast Guard been monitoring the vessel, as was its responsibility.
   Hazelwood, 42, of Huntington, N.Y., surrendered to Alaskan
authorities this week on three misdemeanor charges of operating a
vessel while intoxicated, reckless endangerment and negligent
discharge of oil.
   His attorneys were in court to formally request that the
fugitive from justice warrant issued last month be canceled. Judge
Edward Green granted the request.
   _The Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. in Valdez, which pipes oil to
tankers from the trans-Alaska pipeline, said it will require that
tankers leaving Valdez be escorted by special, 200-foot-long
spill-recovery boats.
   ``Under the new plan, every tanker leaving Port Valdez will be
escorted by a tug and a large emergency response vessel loaded with
oil containment and recovery equipment,'' said George M. Nelson,
president of the company.
</TEXT>
