<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>South African Troops Will Remain Deployed Until May 13</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African troops will remain on
patrol in northern Namibia until May 13 to make sure all SWAPO
guerrillas have left the territory, officials said Friday.
   The statements by Louis Pienaar, South African-appointed
administrator-general of Namibia, and Pik Botha, South Africa's
foreign minister, followed a comment by U.N. Secretary-General
Javier Perez de Cuellar urging that South African soldiers be
restricted to barracks immediately because police could handle the
situation.
   South Africa has agreed to implementation of a U.N. plan leading
to elections in November and independence for the territory South
Africa has ruled for 74 years. The plan is tied to an agreement
among South Africa, Cuba and Angola that guerrillas of the
South-West African People's Organization remain in their bases in
Angola until their scheduled return to Namibia as unarmed refugees
in June.
   The U.N. plan was interrupted April 1, when hundreds of
guerrillas crossed into Namibia. South African forces were released
from their bases and more than 300 men died in the subsequent
fighting.
   Pienaar told a news conference Cuba, Angola and South Africa
agreed at Cape Town meetings last weekend that South African troops
could spend until May 13 sweeping northern Namibia for guerrillas
and arms caches. Pienaar said about 300 SWAPO fighters still were
in the area and flushing them out would require considerable
military manpower.
