<FIRST>u a AM-WinerySlayings 1stLd-Writethru a0720 05-05 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmates Give Money, `Days of Peace' for Daughter of Alleged Killer</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Salcido arraignment, details,
color; picks up 7th graf: ``In trying ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A winery worker accused of killing his
wife, two of their daughters and four other people in a bloody
rampage pleaded innocent Friday to charges that could send him to
the gas chamber.
   Ramon Salcido, 28, looked glum and unkempt as he entered the
innocent pleas to seven counts of murder and three counts of
attempted murder in connection with an April 14 crime spree through
the wine country north of San Francisco.
   And an expression of sympathy for a victim of that spree emerged
from an unlikely place, with hundreds of prisoners at the Sonoma
County jail collecting $900 during two ``days of peace'' for
Salcido's 3-year-old daughter, Carmina, who survived a cut throat
allegedly inflicted by her father.
   ``I've had enough of violence, and what was done to her was pure
evil,'' said Gabriel Menjou, 42, serving time at the jail on a
forgery conviction.
   ``I wanted her to know that men don't have to be mean and cruel,
but to know that they can be loving, kind and caring,'' said Menjou.
   Salcido in an isolation cell at the jail charged with killing
Carmina's mother and two sisters, his mother-in-law and her two
young daughters, and a winery worker he told detectives he believed
was having an affair with his wife.
   He also is charged with the attempted murder of Carmina, whose
throat was cut, and trying to shoot to death two other people.
   In court Friday, about 20 sheriff's deputies stood guard inside
and outside the courtroom, searching bags and passing metal
detectors over spectators as they came in.
   Salcido listened to the proceedings through a court-provided
Spanish interpreter but answered the judge in English, saying
``Yes, your honor,'' in a barely audible voice.
   In addition to pleading innocent to all the charges, Salcido
denied an allegation of multiple murder, a special circumstance
that if proved could result in a sentence of death or life in
prison without possibility of parole.
   Municipal Court Judge Knoel Owen set a date of Sept. 11 for a
preliminary hearing and refused to lift a gag order he imposed
earlier in the case.
   The fund raising for Carmina was the idea of an inmate
counseling group run by the Rev. Bob Gutleben, the jail's
unofficial chaplain. He had noted that inmates often have an
unwritten code calling for the maiming or murder of pedophiles and
child murderers.
   ``In trying to help inmates deal with some of the really heavy
hatred they've directed at Ramon, we posed the question, thinking
about Carmina: What would be most helpful, to assure her you as
inmates would kill her daddy, or something else,'' said Gutleben.
   ``We asked them instead to give the gift that killers would not
give _ the gift of non-violence,'' he added.
   Gutleben said he was shocked by the inmates' outpouring of
concern for the child. Numerous prisoners who have only $1.50 in
their jail accounts gave $1 to the fund, and several gave the full
amount.
   Those who donated gave an average of half their savings, he
estimated.
   ``These guys dug down to every cent they literally had in their
pockets. They are going to go without cigarettes and other basic
necessities because they want to reach out of their anger and
despair and direct something positive to Carmina,'' Gutleben said.
   Gutleben, who runs Sebastopol-based Covenant Connection, a
non-denominational ministry to inmates and ex-convicts, said 90
percent of the jail's 690 prisoners participated in the collection
drive and the two-day pledge of non-violence.
   Sheriff's deputies have been concerned about the safety of
28-year-old Salcido since he was captured in Mexico April 19. He
was brought to the county jail the next night, where a furious
crowd of 200 people shouted ``Kill him.''
   Weather stripping was added to his cell door to prevent inmates
from slipping anything harmful inside. Authorities also put up a
large metal plate to keep inmates from looking into Salcido's cell
through a window.
   Whenever he is moved from this third-floor cell _ for showers,
exercise or court appointments _ all of the 50 to 60 inmates on the
floor are confined to their cells. Salcido also is accompanied by
three guards.
   Twenty-four hour supervision, which also serves as a suicide
watch, is provided by an officer watching Salcido through a window
in the wall of his cell.
   Carmina has been showered by hundreds of gifts at Petaluma
Valley Hospital and donations have poured into a trust fund set up
for her. Carmina's grandfather, who has applied for custody, has
not disclosed how much has been raised.
</TEXT>
