<FIRST>r i AM-Bolivia     05-05 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Campaigning Ends as Bolivians Prepare for Sunday Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0762 to fix category code</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ban on campaigning went into effect
here Friday, two days before presidential and congressional
elections in which former military dictator Hugo Banzer Suarez is
expected to emerge as president.
   Ten parties are competing in the elections. Besides the
presidency, all 27 Senate seats and all 130 seats in the House of
Deputies are at stake.
   About two dozen foreign observers are on hand, most of them from
Latin American countries and organizations. Foreign diplomats said,
however, that they did not expect any widespread fraud.
   Electoral officials distributed ballot boxes, freshly painted a
pale green, and numbered, multicolored ballots on Friday to polling
places in school gymnasiums and other public buildings.
   ``Everything is ready for Sunday,'' Mauro Cuellar, president of
the National Electoral Court, told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview. ``Voting material will be distributed to all
polling places today and tomorrow.''
   Under Bolivian law, all campaigning must halt two full days
before balloting.
   Police were out in force late Thursday night, controlling the
streets as party activists staged last-minute rallies and marches.
No heavy security presence was evident on Friday, but officers
guarded polling places.
   The independent Permanent Human Rights Assembly of Bolivia asked
its ranks to ``monitor the voting process and denounce any attempts
at fraud.'' It said its effort was aimed mainly ``at marginal city
neighborhoods and rural areas.''
   The presidential front-runner in most polls was Banzer, 62, a
retired army general and standard-bearer of the rightist National
Democratic Action. The two other major candidates are industrialist
Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, 58, of the conservative Revolutionary
Nationalist Movement and Jaime Paz Zamora, 50, a former vice
president, of the Social Democratic Movement of the Revolutionary
Left.
   None is expected to win more than 50 percent of the total vote.
In such a case, congress is given authority to choose the president
from among the top three finishers when it convenes Aug. 4.
   Banzer finished first in the last presidential election in 1985,
with 28.6 percent of the vote, but congress picked runner-up Victor
Paz Estenssoro, with 26.4 percent, to be president. Paz Estenssoro,
now 81, is retiring from politics.
   Banzer seized power in a 1971 coup that toppled a leftist
military dictatorship and ruled until 1978, when popular pressure
forced him to call elections.
</TEXT>
