<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-05 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0839</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents pulled traders off the floors of
at least two New York commodity exchanges, issued subpoenas and
seized documents as part of a criminal and civil investigation of
the chaotic markets.
   Authorities said the government subpoenaed more than 50 traders
from four of New York's five commodities exchanges, seeking
information about trading practices by firms and individuals.
   No arrests were made Thursday or arrest warrants issued.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's major retailers said sales picked up moderately in
April, but not enough to imply consumers have forgotten about
credit costs and inflation creeping up.
   Store executives and industry analysts said Thursday that better
weather in parts of the country in late April helped stir shoppers'
interest in seasonal clothing and merchandise, partially
compensating for a weak first half.
   One big general merchandise retailer that reported a negative
impact on business from early April's unfavorable weather was K
mart Corp., the second largest chain store in the country.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc.'s chairman reiterated at the
company's annual shareholders meeting that the cosmetics giant
intends to remain independent and focus on its core beauty and
direct selling businesses.
   The assertion Thursday came a day after Minneapolis investor
Irwin Jacobs and rival Amway Corp. disclosed they had amassed a
10.3 percent stake in Avon and might seek to acquire the company.
   But talk at the Avon meeting was dominated by animal rights
issues, not takeovers, as shareholders rejected a proposal to force
the company to disclose details of animal testing used for its
products.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The typical American household, nearly six
members strong when the nation was new, is down statistically to
just over 2{ people, a record low, the Census Bureau said.
   The decline reflects ``changes in the age structure of the
American population,'' said Census Bureau demographer Campbell
Gibson in a telephone interview Thursday.
   The household is shrinking as families have fewer children, more
young people set up housekeeping on their own and the number of
elderly maintaining their own households grows.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the town of Kimry, soap rationing began in
April, limiting each man and woman to one bar of household soap and
1} pounds of bath soap in local shops. Not each week or month, but
each year.
   The residents of Ufa, a city of 1 million people in the Urals,
are loading up on salt and matches due to rumors of pending
shortages.
   Sugar rationing went into effect in Moscow on May 1 for the
first time since World War II, and even the Soviet minister of
trade, Kondrat Terekh, has been issued a card entitling him to 4.4
pounds of sugar per month and no more.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House and Senate, upholding a
much-criticized agreement with President Bush, moved toward
approval of $1.2 trillion budget measures which promise to reduce
the deficit without cutting spending or significantly raising taxes.
   Each chamber rejected several attempts Thursday to overhaul the
blueprint for tax and spending policy in fiscal 1990 as they
approached final votes.
   As laid out by the White House agreement, the budgets claim to
shrink the federal deficit to just below $100 billion, as required
by the Gramm-Rudman law. They would allow federal programs to grow
but, especially at the Pentagon, at less than the rate of inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SELAH, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tree Top Inc., the nation's largest apple
processor, announced it will break contracts with growers who use
the chemical Alar on this season's crop.
   The growers' cooperative in Idaho, Oregon and Washington said
Thursday the move was to assuage consumer fears, which have been
inflamed by allegations about Alar's cancer-causing properties.
   In the past, Tree Top rejected apples that were treated with the
chemical, which makes apples redder and crisper.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's Supreme Court unanimously
upheld all of Proposition 103's long-term restrictions on insurance
rates and practices, but it punched a hole in a 20 percent rate
rollback and freeze.
   The ruling by the conservative-dominated court Thursday still
was a serious blow to insurance companies, who had predicted that
Proposition 103 would cost them $4 billion a year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market recorded another small decline Thursday,
continuing its week-long pullback. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials dropped 8.80 to 2,384.90.
   The dollar finished at varied levels against major foreign
currencies.
   Bond prices were at a near standstill as traders stayed on the
sidelines in anticipation of Friday's release of employment figures
for April.
   Energy futures were mixed as crude oil futures rose over
increased concern with North Sea oil production. Grain and soybean
futures were mixed; livestock prices were higher and pork futures
lower; and precious metals were mixed.
</TEXT>
