<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales Bjt   05-05 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales, Bjt,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apparel Sales Help Build Retail Sales Momentum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Retail Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Major American retailers are benefiting from a turnaround in
women's apparel sales, which helped produce a modest boost in
business at several chain stores during April.
   Department stores and specialty apparel merchants generally had
good news to report in results issued Thursday. Women's clothing
sales continued to rebound from last year's low levels and analysts
cited keen interest in career wardrobes as one cause.
   Among the apparel-oriented merchants that posted decent sales
were: Dayton Hudson Corp., a Minneapolis-based department-store
operator; May Department Stores Co., a St. Louis-based owner of
department stores and discount home and shoe shops; J.C. Penney Co.
Inc., the Dallas-based nationwide chain; and, Limited Inc., which
has specialty apparel shops and is based in Columbus, Ohio.
   One big general merchandise retailer reported a negative impact
on business from early April's colder-than-normal weather in many
parts of the country, particularly the Midwest and Northest.
   But the retailer, Troy, Mich.-based K mart Corp., the second
largest chain store in the country, said sales of things such as
spring and summer clothing, do-it-yourself gadgetry, patio
furniture, barbecue grills and other outdoor gear improved as the
weather warmed up during the second half of April.
   Meanwhile, the largest U.S. retailer, Sears, Roebuck and Co.,
was pleased with its take. Sears, which is banking on a new
low-pricing policy to boost customer traffic, also benefited from
the rollout of its Brand Central superstores.
   Helped by the marketing of more national brands alongside its
flagship Kenmore label, Sears' sales of home electronics and
appliances rose by double-digit percentages in April.
   Jeffrey Edelman, a retail industry analyst at Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., said the April numbers looked good overall partly
because they were being compared with last year's depressed
tallies. Still, he said, April represented a significant
improvement from March's very sluggish volumes.
   ``This in an indication that the consumer is not dead, spending
is just slowing down,'' Edelman said.
   Expenditures on things that are typically financed with bank
loans have been curbed a bit by increases in interest rates this
year.
   Jeffrey Feiner, an analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., said sales
industry-wide this year have barely outpaced the inflation rate,
indicating that consumer spending, a key element in economic
growth, is easing.
   Feiner has scaled down his forecast for average 1989 retail
sales growth to 5.5 percent from 6 percent, based on sales results
so far this year.
   Thomas Tashjian, an analyst with Seidler Amdec Securities Inc.
in Los Angeles, said one of the positive factors in this year's
retail equation is that big chains have refrained from slashing
prices to clear out slow-moving goods. This, combined with tight
inventory management, will help preserve profitability in the
retail business.
   The results Thursday were from some of the biggest general
merchandise chains in the United States, including purveyors of
special apparel lines and accessories. Monthly retail sales figures
from the government are more comprehensive and include the take at
other types of establishments such as auto dealerships,
supermarkets and restaurants.
   Here are some of the figures:
   Chicago-based Sears said its sales rose 9.2 percent in the four
weeks ended April 29 from the comparable 1988 period and sales at
stores open at least a year, called same or comparable store sales,
rose 6.8 percent.
   Retailers and industry analysts consider same-store sales a more
accurate indication of a company's performance than totals that
include sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports
same-store sales.
   K mart said its sales in the four weeks to April 26 were up 2.3
percent but, on a same-store basis, sales fell 1 percent.
   The third-largest retailer, Wal-Mart Stores Inc., said its April
sales rose 25 percent while its same-store sales gained 11 percent.
The fast-growing discounter, based in Bentonville, Ark., routinely
reports double-digit same-store sales growth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890505-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RetailSales-Table     05-05 0403</FIRST>
