<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Exxon     05-05 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Continuing Efforts To Diffuse Negative Publicity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. President Lee R. Raymond says too
much bureaucracy could hinder the mop-up of the nation's worst oil
spill and denied the company was trying to cut corners in the
cleanup.
   At a news conference Thursday in his New York office, Raymond
said that as many as 14 government agencies may be involved in
approving and carrying out Exxon's final cleanup plan.
   ``I want some one person in charge _ I don't care who it is _
because there has to be one person that finally says `hey, it's
midnight and we gotta do something. And here's what we're going to
do.''
   Raymond said Exxon was continuing to operate under a plan
approved April 17 by the U.S. Coast Guard until a revised plan is
given the go-ahead. Exxon submitted the latest proposal to the
Coast Guard on Monday after portions of the current plan were
criticized as inadequate.
   The oil tanker Exxon Valdez crashed into a reef March 24,
spilling more than 11 million gallons of crude oil into Price
William Sound. Exxon accepted responsibility for the spill but has
been criticized for dragging its feet in its initial response to
the disaster.
   Raymond defended the latest proposal, _ which he said was
formulated with the help of state and federal environmental
officials _ despite ongoing criticism by some state regulators. The
proposal calls for cleaning up 364 miles of shoreline by Sept. 15.
   He also rejected reports alleging that Exxon was attempting to
bypass environmental regulations to dispose of waste accumulated
from the spill.
   The first page of Exxon's new waste disposal plan calls for use
of existing treatment and disposal facilities at the Alyeska Valdez
Terminal. ``Use of the Alyeska facilities will also require
cooperation from the regulatory agencies to rapidly issue letters
of non-objection, waivers, or permit modifications as required,''
the plan says.
   Raymond said, however, that the wording was misinterpreted and
that ``everything can be accomplished within environmental laws.''
   Raymond also said Exxon would do ``anything reasonable'' to
cleanse Alaska's soiled waters and beaches and that it placed the
cleanup of 191 miles of lightly oil beaches last on the list of
priorities after consultations with environmental officials. He
said Exxon would clean even those areas, except in cases,
particularly wildlife habitats, judged better left untouched.
   ``Anything that makes sense that they would say you ought to do
in addition to what you have in the plan, we'll do it,'' Raymond
said.
</TEXT>
