<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 0245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TrumpGame     05-05 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trump Game,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheeler-Dealer Faces New Type Of Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST LONGMEADOW, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald J. Trump, the
quintessential wheeler-dealer, faces a new kind of board in his
newest venture, ``Trump The Game.''
   The real estate mogul has joined forces with board game
manufacturer Milton Bradley Co., which expects the game to be the
biggest seller in its 129-year history.
   Trump flew in his private helicopter to Milton Bradley
headquarters here Thursday to fulfill a promise to the company.
   ``They were intent on having me come up to meet the real
people,'' he said. ``These are the people doing the work. To hell
with the executives.''
   Many of the 2,300 workers at the western Massachusetts factory
clapped at each stop in the 45-minute visit, women sighed ``Isn't
he handsome?'' and men lined up for autographs of the paper money
that bears his likeness and comes in denominations no smaller than
$10 million.
   More than 2 million of the games are scheduled for production by
year's end. It is the No. 1 seller in the 300 stores that have
received advance copies, Milton Bradley President George Ditomassi
said.
   Neither the company nor Trump will reveal his royalties, but
both said he is donating proceeds to charities for the homeless and
for research into AIDS, cerebral palsy and multiple sclerosis.
   The board game is a sophisticated battle in which players first
bid against each other _ using the fake cash and Trump cards, of
course _ for airlines, casinos, luxury hotels and other Trump
properties, then try to negotiate deals.
   Trump said the game is tough even for a veteran of the
high-stakes business world like him, but he resisted explaining its
appeal. ``If I said it, you'd say I have a big ego, so why say it?''
   The idea for the game came from an independent inventor from
Chicago, who suggested Milton Bradley, a division of Hasbro Inc.,
as the manufacturer.
   Trump said he settled on the nation's largest board game maker
because ``the loyalty, decisiveness and professionalism of this
company is just unbelievable.'' As the applause died down, he
barked at workers: ``OK, get some overtime.''
   During a news conference later, Trump denied rumors that he
planned to run for mayor of New York, which had surfaced after he
took out a full-page newspaper advertisement recently supporting
the death penalty and increased police presence.
   And he sneered at the suggestion that a new bidder for the
Eastern Airlines shuttle could affect his $365 million offer.
``It's not serious,'' he said of the bid from America West Airlines
Inc. ``I have not even heard of them.''
   Besides, he said, his contract with Eastern guarantees him a lot
of money even if the deal falls through.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
