<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Judge     05-05 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Judge,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC-Drexel Settlement Still in Limbo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The architects of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s
landmark settlement of civil securities fraud charges will have to
wait even longer for the agreement to be finalized.
   That's because the judge who could approve the deal is blocked
by court order from doing so and a panel of judges declined to
assign the case to another judge Thursday.
   The assignment committee for the U.S. District Court for the
Southern District of New York held that ``no circumstance has
arisen'' that would ``make it appropriate to reassign the case or
any part of it to another judge.''
   The settlement has been placed on hold for nearly a month
because of a legal challenge to U.S. District Judge Milton Pollack,
who is assigned to the case.
   Former Drexel junk bond chief Michael Milken, who is not part of
the settlement, is challenging Pollack's impartiality. The matter
is before the U.S. Supreme Court.
   A federal appeals court has issued a stay, preventing Pollack
from taking any further action, including considering _ and
possibly approving _ the settlement until the Supreme Court decides
whether it will consider Milken's appeal.
   Meanwhile, the appeals court's refusal to assign a different
judge continues to delay the civil settlement as well as Drexel's
record plea bargain to criminal charges.
   Resolution of the SEC pact also is needed before Drexel can
formally plead guilty to six felonies and pay $650 million to
settle criminal charges brought by the U.S. attorney's office in
Manhattan.
   ``We're going to meet and decide what to do next,'' SEC
Solicitor Paul Gonson said Thursday. ``We're obviously very
disappointed.''
   A Drexel spokesman, Steven Anreder, said the investment banking
giant also was disappointed.
   ``We believe it would be in everyone's best interest to have the
settlement reviewed and approved.''
   Drexel and the SEC have twice asked the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals to reconsider its stay to allow Pollack to handle the
settlement or else assign the case to a different judge.
   But the appeals court said it didn't have authority.
   The SEC and Drexel then tried to get the district court
assignment committee to temporarilly assign the case to another
judge to consider the settlement.
   The SEC said it ``strongly believes it is in the public interest
and important to the protection of investors'' to finalize the
settlement ``as expedititously as possible.''
   But the three-judge panel, headed by Chief Judge Charles L.
Brieant, also nixed the idea, saying it hadn't been shown any
evidence ``that such delay, which may result from awaiting action
by the Supreme Court, will affect the public interest adversely.''
   The panel also noted that Pollack ``has not requested of this
committee that all or any part of this action be assigned to
another judge, and gives us no present indication of intending to
do so.''
   Drexel originally battled to get Pollack to excuse himself from
the case because his wife stands to make a hefty profit from a
debt-financed acquisition Drexel helped arrange.
   Pollack refused to step down from the case and the 2nd Circuit,
which delayed further district court proceedings pending its
decision, upheld Pollack in November.
   Drexel eventually dropped its objections to Pollack but the
delay was extended, when Milken and his brother, Lowell, who were
both indicted for racketeering and securities law violations last
month, sought to argue the issue before the Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
