<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     05-05 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Moving in Narrow Range, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was fluctuating in a narrow range in
Europe this morning, with trading made nervous by the prospect of
central bank intervention later during the session.
   Gold prices fell.
   Supported by relatively high U.S. interest rates, and
expectations that interest rates may rise even further, the market
was bidding the dollar up, traders said. International monetary
authorities, on the other side, were ready to intervene and stop
the dollar's advance, they said.
   One Italian trader said the central banks were likely to wait
until after the release today of the U.S. unemployment report for
April.
   The Tokyo market was closed for Children's Day, a national
holiday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 134.25 yen compared
with 133.95 yen Thursday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.8955 West German marks, up from 1.8915
   _1.6910 Swiss francs, up from 1.6860
   _6.3970 French francs, up from 6.3875
   _2.1361 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1290
   _1,384.50 Italian lire, up from 1,380.00
   _1.1835 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1841
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6768, compared with
$1.6841 Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at $376.80 a troy ounce, down from $378.25
bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $377.30.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $377.20, down from $379 bid late
Wednesday. The market was closed Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at $378.41.
   Silver was quoted in London today at $5.63 a troy ounce, down
from Thursday's $5.66.
</TEXT>
