<FIRST>r f PM-ManufacturersHanover     05-05 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Manufacturers Hanover,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>UMW, Community Group Join To Pressure Bank</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grass-roots housing group from Brooklyn,
N.Y., and the United Mine Workers joined to pressure Manufacturers
Hanover Trust because the bank extended credit to a company the
union is striking, a spokesman for the housing organization says.
   The UMW went on strike against Pittston Coal Group Inc. of St.
Paul, Va., last month.
   ``We're sort of joining hands with them in terms of trying to
put pressure on an entity which, in one way or another, is
supporting Pittston,'' said Peter Sawell, a spokesman for the
Association of Community Organization for Reform Now (ACORN).
   ACORN and UMW filed papers with the Federal Reserve on Thursday
asking it to block Manufacturers's purchase of 11 branches of
Goldome Federal Savings Bank.
   The groups claim Manufacturers broke the law by failing to make
mortgage loans in predominantly black or Hispanic neighborhoods in
Brooklyn.
   The Community Reinvestment Act requires that banks meet the
credit needs of their entire communities, and not just
higher-income neighborhoods in their service areas.
   Asked why UMW was concerned about banking practices in Brooklyn,
where it has no members, UMW spokesman Kenneth Zinn said:
   ``... the role that they're playing is to generally forsake
low-income and poor people in the community for large companies for
leveraged buyouts, for high-income neighborhoods, and we think
there's something the matter with that.''
   UMW has been attempting to put pressure on Pittston through
several banks, including Manufacturers Hanover, that extended a
$100 million line of credit to Pittston in December 1987.
   UMW has charged the credit line was Pittston's ``strike fund.''
About 1,500 miners in Virginia and West Virginia had been working
without a contract for 14 months when they went on strike April 5.
   In February, the UMW announced the withdrawal of $30 million
from Crestar Fianancial Corp., one of the five banks extending the
line of credit to Pittston. The UMW's international union withdrew
$6.7 million from the bank, while the Bakery and Confectionery
Union's pension fund pulled out $23 million.
   ``Clearly, we started looking at Manufacturers Hanover when we
saw what they were doing with their capital assets in terms of the
loan to Pittston,'' Zinn said. ``Whether this puts pressure on
them, I don't know. That's for the bank to decide.''
   MHT spokesman John Stefans said his company has been found by
federal and state banking regulators to be in compliance with the
Community Reinvestment Act.
   Stefans said a UMW official spoke at the bank's annual meeting
April 21 in New York and asked the bank to withdraw its portion of
the line of credit.
   The bank spokesman said he had not seen the ACORN-UMW papers and
could not respond directly. But he said the bank had not made loans
for one- to four-family houses until recently.
   The union and ACORN charged in their papers that while 43
percent of Brooklyn's population lives in predominantly white
census tracts, ``Manny Hanny has progressively made more of of its
loans _ 67 percent in 1986, 68 percent in 1987 and 69 percent in
1988 _ in these tracts.''
   They said that in census areas with more than 75 percent
minority residents, ``where 57 percent of Brooklyn's population
lives, Manufacturers Hanover granted far fewer loans.''
</TEXT>
