<FIRST>r f PM-Trump-Casino     05-05 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trump-Casino,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump's Bid for Atlantis Challenged By Other Offers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five offers higher than Donald
Trump's $63 million agreement to buy Elsinore's Atlantis Casino
Hotel have been made to the casino's state-appointed conservator.
   Bob Stupak, owner of Vegas World Hotel-Casino in Las Vegas,
offered $64 million on Thursday for the Atlantis, just above
Trump's signed agreement.
   Trump intends to close the Atlantis casino and operate it as a
hotel, but Stupak said he would keep the casino open.
   ``The senior citizens and disabled of New Jersey will continue
to benefit from the approximately $6 million in casino win taxes
paid by the Atlantis, and I have every intention of retaining the
Atlantis employees on their jobs,'' he said in a statement.
   Joseph M. Nolan, the conservator operating the Atlantis since
its license expired April 14, said he is accepting purchase offers
for the financially failing gaming hall.
   Nolan told the state Casino Control Commission he questions the
validity of Trump's agreement with Elsinore Corp. because it may
have been signed after he became conservator.
   Trump was not available for comment Thursday, said his secretary
in New York, Norma Foerderer.
   Nolan said he has already received four bids for the Atlantis,
either in writing or by telephone, but refused to identify the
interested parties or their bids. He said all the new bids would
keep the Atlantis casino in tact.
   Stupak said he would keep the Atlantis' three-floor casino open
even though it has not proven to be a financial success.
   Stupak has challenged Trump before. In March, Stupak bet $1
million that he could beat the billionaire developer at the board
game titled ``Trump: The Game.'' Trump refused the challenge.
   Stupak, 47, is a colorful Las Vegas figure who lost a close race
for mayor in 1987. A Pittsburgh native, he settled in Las Vegas in
1972 and established a Dine Out coupon club. He opened the Million
Dollar Historic Gambling Museum in 1974, which mysteriously burned
down six weeks later.
   He built Vegas World on the same site, opening in 1979.
</TEXT>
