<FIRST>r f PM-Prime-MAIBasic     05-05 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime-MAI Basic,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suitor Says Two-Thirds of Prime Stock Tendered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc. shareholders have tendered
more than 66 percent of the company's outstanding stock to MAI
Basic Four Inc. under a $20-per-share hostile takeover bid, MAI
Basic says.
   The tender offer is still enjoined by a federal court in Boston,
but MAI said this week it was preparing to satisfy the sole
remaining condition for ending the injunction.
   MAI Basic said Thursday it was mailing Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc.'s year-end financial statements to all Prime stockholders to
comply with an order from U.S. District Judge A. David Mazzone.
   Mazzone previously ruled the statements from Drexel, MAI's
investment bank and adviser, needed to be provided to shareholders
to comply with federal disclosure requirements. He said he would
lift the injunction 10 days after MAI certifies the statements have
been sent out.
   MAI, a Tustin, Calif.-based computer company, said it has
extended its offer, valued at about $970 million, until May 31.
   The injunction does not prevent stockholders from tendering
their shares. But it does block MAI, controlled by New York
investor Bennett S. LeBow, from taking ownership of the stock.
   Natick-based Prime is a minicomputer maker with a second largest
share of the market for computer-aided design and manufacturing
systems behind International Business Machines Corp.
   Prime's board of directors has rejected MAI's bid as too low. A
Prime spokeswoman, Paula Levis, said it is continuing to look for a
buyer willing to pay more than $20 per share.
   MAI also has announced plans to wage a proxy battle for control
of Prime's board at its June 14 annual meeting.
