<HEAD>Pennsylvania Moves To Block Gate Sale To USAir</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 6th graf pvs with USAir comment; PICKS UP
7th graf pvs, `Court papers...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state is challenging USAir's proposed
purchase of eight Eastern Airlines gates in Philadelphia, saying
the transaction could reduce competition and lead to higher ticket
prices.
   The sale, worth about $85 million to strike-bound Eastern, would
give USAir 23 of 49 gates at Philadelphia International Airport,
Pennsylvania Attorney General Ernie Preate said in a motion filed
in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York.
   USAir already controls 36 of 51 gates the Greater Pittsburgh
International Airport, he said.
   ``USAir's fares per mile for flights of 200 to 500 miles to or
from Pittsburgh are 12 percent higher than the average fare for
short-haul flights to or from other cities,'' Preate said.
   ``The lack of competition is hurting Pennsylvania consumers, and
the situation will only worsen if USAir is able to increase its
dominance over Philadelphia,'' he said.
   The petition, filed Thursday, asks Bankruptcy Court Judge Burton
R. Lifland to reject the proposed sale and order Eastern to offer
the gates to other airlines before a scheduled May 23 court hearing.
   USAir spokesman John Bronson called the arguments ``seriously
flawed'' and said they will ``inhibit growth of air service in
hiladlephia.''
   Court papers also said Braniff, Midway and Pan Am Express, an
East Coast shuttle, are seeking gates in Philadelphia, and TWA is
considering establishing a Philadelphia hub.
   USAir on the fifth day of the Machinists strike against Eastern
that started March 4 announced it had agreed to buy the gates after
months of negotiations.
