<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market staged a broad rally today,
inspired by new evidence of slowing economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 13.74 to
2,398.64 in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 1 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 755 up, 184 down and
483 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 28.68 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Labor Department reported that the civilian unemployment
rate took an unexpected 0.3 percentage point jump in April, to 5.3
percent.
   The monthly data also showed an increase of 117,000 in nonfarm
payroll employment, substantially less than most advance estimates
on Wall Street.
   The figures reinforced the spreading belief on Wall Street that
the economy has been slowing in recent months, responding to
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve.
   What remains less clear, analysts said, is whether the Fed is
starting to see any results in its primary mission of reining in
inflation.
   Nevertheless, the news sparked a rally in the bond market,
sending interest rates lower, and stocks followed suit.
   Gainers among the blue chips included General Electric, up ] at
48~; International Business Machines, up | at 111\; Exxon, up \ at
42|; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph, up \ at 34}, and Eastman
Kodak, up ] at 43|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.80 to 173.01. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .64 at 346.53.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 8.80 to
2,384.90.
   Declining issues slightly outnumbered advances on the NYSE, with
661 up, 723 down and 546 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 153.13 million shares, against 171.69
million in the previous session.
