<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv08   05-05 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 08,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday May 8</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wall Street Sees No Severe Housing Slump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like a good many other American industries,
housing and real estate have lately felt the pinch of high interest
rates.
   But some Wall Street analysts maintain that the homebuilding
business is going through nothing much worse than a moderate down
cycle that won't have dire or far-reaching consequences for the
economy.
   In fact, a few observers argue that stocks of homebuilding
companies, which generally have turned in an uninspired showing
over the past year or two, could soon start to revive if interest
rates are ready to come down.
   Figures published by the Value Line Investment survey show that
housing starts, the historical gauge of the homebuilding industry's
health, have been declining steadily from a peak they reached more
than three years ago.
   In the first quarter of 1986, work was started on new private
dwelling units at the rate of 1.94 million a year.
   In the second quarter of this year, by contrast, Value Line
estimates the total will come in at an annual rate of 1.40 million.
   Still, the investment advisory firm says it believes housing
starts will bottom out toward the end of this year not far below
current levels.
   ``That would be the culmination of a historically mild decline
that has developed gradually from the 1986 peak,'' says analyst
Stephen Grant in Value Line's recently published quarterly
appraisal of the industry outlook.
   ``Most of this decline has occurred in multi-family housing, due
to previous overbuilding stimulated by tax laws that have since
been changed.
   ``Single-family housing starts have a good shot at topping the 1
million level in 1989 for an unprecedented seventh consecutive
year, after troughing at 660,000 in 1982.''
   Even if housing is in for a more extended period of weakness
than analysts now expect, some observers contend that it need not
drag the rest of the economy down with it.
   In the past, weakness in housing traditionally ushered in
recessions in the overall economy. When tight money sent home
buying and homebuilding into a slump, demand dropped off for
building materials, home furnishings, appliances _ and a ripple
effect occurred.
   In the 1980s, however, past patterns haven't held, says Robert
Barbera, economist at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   While housing has been strong ever since the early 1980s, he
notes, manufacturing is in the early stages of recovery from a
severe mid-'80s slump.
   ``Housing and factory activity are out of phase at present,''
Barbera says, ``and that enhances the prospects for a slide in U.S.
housing activity without an economy-wide downturn.''
   Barbera acknowledges that it's always dangerous in financial or
economic forecasting to adopt the premise that ``things are
different this time than they were in previous cycles.''
   But analysts say several things have indeed occurred lately to
change the nature of the homebuilding business _ including the
advent of the adjustable-rate mortgage and the growth of the
mortgage-backed securities market, which channels additional money
into real estate finance.
   Says Grant: ``We believe the housing cycle will go through
narrower swings than in the past.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday May 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
