<FIRST>u f PM-Exxon-NewYork     05-05 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon-New York,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Pension Fund Threatens Exxon Board Members Over Valdez Oil Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the city pension system says other
stockholders should join him in voting against the Exxon Corp.
board unless the company gives assurances that it has taken steps
to prevent another disaster like the Alaskan oil spill.
   City Finance Commissioner Anthony E. Shorris and Comptroller
Harrison J. Goldin met with Exxon President Lee R. Raymond on
Thursday.
   Shorris said they wanted to ensure the safety of the city's $250
million investment in Exxon stock and expressed concern that such
an environmentally devastating spill not happen again.
   Shorris said Exxon management ``listened to our concerns and
asked for a couple of days'' in which to come back with a response.
   ``We told them that depending on your answers, we will vote
against the board'' at the company's May 18 stockholders meeting,
he said.
   Although the pension fund holds 6 million shares, or less than 1
percent of Exxon stock, Shorris said, ``We would obviously be in
contact with other pension systems throughout the country to see if
we could get them to back us.''
   Exxon spokeswoman Sarah Johnson declined to comment on
Thursday's meeting, saying that meetings with investors are private.
   Shorris is chairman of the New York City Employees Retirement
System which, together with police, fire and teacher pension
systems, controls about $20 billion in investments.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch commented later that the oil spill at
Valdez, Alaska, and Exxon's slow response ``are two outrages that
cannot adequately be described in words.''
   He said he supported Shorris' decision to ``use NYCERS' leverage
to make Exxon the environmentally sound corporate citizen it should
have been long ago.''
   Shorris said the city was willing to wait a ``couple of days''
to hear back from the oil company, but cautioned that ``time is
short.''
   He said the city wanted to know if any changes were contemplated
in management structure of the firm, what kind of research and
development programs it has to deal with oil spills of the Valdez
magnitude and what contingency plans it has to deal with such
mishaps.
   He said that while the city is concerned with the environment,
the pension trustees also have ``a fiduciary obligation to the
pensioneers to make sure their funds are safe.''
</TEXT>
