<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed this
morning in light trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat prices were down following a week of steady advances.
Analysts say there is some reluctance to buying into wheat futures
at current price levels.
   However, wheat prices will get support from forecasts calling
for hot and dry conditions next week in winter crop areas.
   Corn and soybean futures were higher despite forecasts for more
rain over the weekend.
   In early trading, wheat was } cent lower to 2{ cents higher,
with the contract for delivery in May at $4.35 a bushel; corn was 1
