<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   05-05 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices closed higher on Friday, encouraged
by renewed institutional buying on the first day of a new trading
period and some bullish signals from the U.S. unemployment figures
for April.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 13.8
points, or 0.7 percent higher, at 2,132.8.
   It was the highest closing level since the October 1987 stock
market crash, topping the previous closing high of 2,125.4 set on
March 14.
   News that the unemployment rate rose to 5.3 percent in April
suggested the U.S economy was cooling and U.S. interest rates
wouldn't have to be raised again, dealers said.
   London share prices gained more support later in the trading
session with the start of a new two-week trading account, dealers
added.
   London's Stock Exchange divides trading into two-week and
three-week trading periods for accounting purposes.
   Volume was a moderate 589.2 million shares, up from 541.7
million shares Thursday.
</TEXT>
