<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     05-05 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up in Europe Despite Intervention; Gold Off</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version for AMs is planned by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mostly higher in Europe Friday,
reovering from a selloff on news of a rise in the U.S. unemployment
rate and defying a concerted effort by central banks to stem its
advance.
   Gold prices moved lower.
   The dollar dropped sharply after the U.S. Labor Department
reported a jump in the U.S. unemployment rate to 5.3 percent in
April from 5 percent in March.
   The increase was consistent with recent statistics showing
slower economic activity. Some analysts say slower growth will
induce the Federal Reserve to pursue a more generous credit policy.
   Interest rates have headed up this year because the U.S. central
bank has been trying to stifle inflationary pressures by putting
the brakes on economic growth. High U.S. interest rates have
boosted demand for dollars and dollar-denominated investments.
   The Fed, the West German Bundesbank and several European central
banks pounced on the dollar when it reached the 1.89-level to the
West German mark, dealers said
   But they said the intervention was moderate and that the
underlying demand for dollars remained strong.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6740 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6841 Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with rates late
Thursday included: 1.8988 West German marks, up from 1.8915; 1.6985
Swiss francs, up from 1.6860; 6.4080 French francs, up from 6.3875;
2.1285 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1290; 1,379.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,380.00; and, 1.1842 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1841.
   The Tokyo market was closed for Children's Day, a national
holiday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 134.31 yen compared
with 133.95 yen in London late Thursday.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $376.25 a troy ounce from
$378.25 late Thursday.
   In Zurich, gold fell to close at a bid of $375.85 compared with
$379 bid late Wednesday. The market was closed Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at $378.41.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.60 a troy ounce, compared
with Thursday's $5.66.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
