<DOCNO> AP890505-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1515EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-05 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wheat Continues Strong Showing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed higher
Friday in quiet trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as
expectations of additional export of U.S. grains spurred the market.
   Wheat futures continue to show strength as a result of the offer
this week by the United States to sell 1.5 million metric tons of
grain to the Soviet Union under the export subsidy program.
   ``I think even if they are not bidding now, they will be in the
market in the near future,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``That is keeping wheat
prices firm.''
   A day after the United States made the offer, the Soviets
announced a bid for 300,000 metric tons of wheat.
   Wheat prices were also helped along by the poor condition of the
winter crop in Kansas, caused by dry weather and heat.
   Expected Soviet demand for U.S. corn also spurred prices for
that commodity.
   ``The Soviets have made sporadic buys of corn in the past,'' Mao
said. ``The market is waiting to hear how much more buying will be
done.''
   Soybean futures rose on word of tightness in the U.S. and
Brazilian cash soybean markets.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3\ cents higher with May at
$4.37{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 5 cents higher with May at
$2.80} a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 6\ cents higher with May at
$1.97 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 10 cents higher with May
at $7.60 a bushel.
</TEXT>
