<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HeraldExaminer     05-05 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Herald Examiner,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>LA Daily Management Discusses Buyout from Hearst</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top executives of the Los Angeles Herald
Examiner are exploring the possibility of a management-led buyout
of the paper from Hearst Corp. by a group that would include
employees.
   The discussions are in a very preliminary stage, said John J.
McCabe, the Herald's chief operating executive.
   ``I think it's a long shot,'' McCabe said. ``We have to develop
a strategic plan and ascertain if there would be equity funding
available.''
   McCabe announced his plans to a group of the paper's editors
Wednesday.
   He said the proposal would be based on converting the
242,000-circulation Hearst daily to a tabloid format. The
possibility of such a conversion has been under study at the paper
for several years.
   Earlier this year representatives of the Toronto Sun Corp. had
discussions with Hearst about a possible joint venture involving
the Herald Examiner.
   But the president of the Toronto Sun, Douglas Creighton, said
that because of the Sun's heavy commitments to a new daily
newspaper in Ottawa and its simultaneous start-up of a daily
financial newspaper in Canada, his company had decided not to
proceed.
   In April, Los Angeles billionaire Marvin Davis approached Hearst
about possibly buying the Herald Examiner. But Davis, who recently
launched a $2.7 billion bid for Northwest Airlines, decided against
the move.
   Heart plans ``to continue exploring different options,'' McCabe
said. ``Obviously (Hearst) decided some months ago they were
interested in looking for a buyer.''
   Privately held Hearst has acknowledged financial losses at the
Herald Examiner but does not disclose specific figures for the
newspaper.
   In 1967, when nine unions embarked on a long strike, the Herald
had a daily circulation of 729,000, making it the nation's largest
afternoon daily.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
