<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HughesSuit     05-05 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hughes Suit,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hughes Accused Of Overcharging Federal Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high-level manager at Hughes Aircraft Co.
has accused the firm in a federal lawsuit of overcharging the
government by $40 million on the radar system for the F-18 fighter
jet and B-2 stealth bomber.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court last January and
unsealed late last month, alleges that top officers at Hughes
conspired to defraud the government by shifting development charges
among programs.
   Hughes Aircraft, a unit of General Motors Corp., said Thursday
in a statement that its own investigation found that all the
charges made to the government were proper.
   Filed under the Federal False Claims Act, the suit seeks $120
million in triple damages. The act allows a plaintiff to bring
lawsuits on behalf of the government and share in the recovery of
damages.
   The suit refers to a special program contract instead of
specifically identifying the B-2 program, but unidentified sources
told the Los Angeles Times that the project involved is the stealth
bomber.
   The suit was brought by William J. Schumer, who was division
contracts manager at the Hughes Radar System Group in nearby El
Segundo. Schumer is still employed by Hughes, but in a different
division.
   Attorney Dean Francis Pace, who is representing Schumer, said
the Justice Department is investigating the allegations.
  
</TEXT>
