<FIRST>r f AM-SEC-Shearson     05-05 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Shearson,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Affirms Action Against Churner Of Widow's Account</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission said
Friday it has affirmed the censure and fining of a Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. broker accused of dissipating a 70-year-old widow's
$100,000 insurance settlement.
   The widow, identified in SEC documents only as Mrs. G, received
a $100,000 insurance settlement when her son, Michael, died of
cancer and deposited the money in October 1982 with Ronald L.
Salyer, a broker in the firm's Washington, D.C., office.
   According to the agency, Salyer ``churned'' the account, making
83 trades totaling $2.22 million. In only 13 months, commissions
and margin account interest had consumed $54,081 of the money.
   The SEC, in the ruling, upheld a finding by the National
Association of Securities Dealers, which censured Salyer and the
manager of his branch office, Randolph G. Peyton, and fined both
$3,000. The document noted that earlier Salyer had settled Mrs. G's
claim for $41,000.
   The SEC faulted Peyton and the firm for failing to more closely
supervise Salyer and agreed with the NASD that the penalty levied
was mild.
   Salyer, according to the document, maintained that Mrs. G gave
him full authorization to manage her account aggressively and had
said she did not need the money to live on.
</TEXT>
