<FIRST>r f AM-AlamoSuit     05-05 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Alamo Suit,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rental Company Sued Over Arrest of Customer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WALES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury has awarded $185,000 to a man who
was handcuffed at work and jailed after Alamo Rent A Car agreed to
extend his rental but then accused him of not returning the car on
time.
   An Orange County jury agreed Thursday that Alamo maliciously
prosecuted Howard Lee by falsely accusing him of keeping the rental
car and then having him arrested.
   The jury awarded the electrical contractor $80,000 in
compensatory damages for loss of reputation and $105,000 in
punitive damages.
   Although Lee said he was satisfied with the verdict, he said he
still hurts inside as a result of the cold shoulders he got from
friends after being handcuffed on the job and jailed briefly in
1986.
   Liz Clark, spokeswoman at Alamo's corporate headquarters in Fort
Lauderdale, was out of the office late Friday when sought for
comment, her office said.
</TEXT>
