<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2122EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Apples-AdCancelled     05-05 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apples-Ad Cancelled,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ads Pulled From CBS Stations in Support of Apple Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a show of solidarity with troubled apple
growers, the Washington State Fruit Commission on Friday decided to
pull $71,000 worth of television advertising for Northwest cherries
from CBS affiliates in St. Louis, Atlanta and Tampa, Fla.
   The action is a protest against the CBS television show ``60
Minutes,'' which apple growers feel damaged their industry with a
recent report on the chemical Alar.
   The move came as apple sales continued to rebound, climbing 9
percent in the past week, according to the latest industry report,
released Friday.
   ``Our association wanted to voice its displeasure over the way
the CBS broadcast of the `60 Minutes' program chose to
sensationalize the Alar story,'' commission spokesman Pat Dunlop
said.
   The television ads were part of a $900,000 promotion of
Northwest cherries the directors of the marketing and promotion
group approved Thursday.
   Roy Brunett, a ``60 Minutes'' spokesman in New York, declined
comment on the action because it does not directly involve the
network.
   Alar is not used on cherries, but many of group's members grow
both crops and ``we're trying to take a united stance on this
issue,'' Dunlop said.
   Atlanta, St. Louis and Tampa had been targeted for extensive
television advertising because sales of Northwest cherries in those
areas are below the national average, Dunlop said.
   The $71,300 budgeted for advertising buys on the CBS affiliates
in those three cities will instead be spent on advertising on other
television stations there, said Dennis Miller of the Evans-Kraft
advertising agency in Seattle, which handles the commission's
accounts.
   On Feb. 26, ``60 Minutes'' ran an exclusive account of a Natural
Resources Defense Council report on pesticides in children's food.
The study concluded that eating apples treated with Alar increased
cancer risks in children.
   The report findings have been disputed by the apple industry and
federal regulators have declared apples safe to eat.
   But the NRDC report sent apple sales into a tailspin, and
growers contend they have lost millions of dollars as a result.
   Washington grows half the nation's apples, and nearly all the
domestic production this late in the season. The industry still has
16.8 million 42-pound boxes in storage that must be sold before the
next harvest in the fall.
   The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has said it plans to
ban Alar next year, based on preliminary studies, but the chemical
is still legal to use.
</TEXT>
