<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished mixed Friday, giving
up a strong early gain in an erratic response to new evidence of
slowing economic growth.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up more than 20 points
in early trading, closed with a 2.94 loss at 2,381.96.
   That left the average with a loss of 36.84 points for the week.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 4 to 3 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
820 up, 603 down and 539 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 180.81 million
shares, up from 153.13 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 212.39 million shares.
   The Labor Department reported Friday morning that the civilian
unemployment rate took an unexpected 0.3 percentage point jump in
April, to 5.3 percent.
   The monthly data also showed an increase of 117,000 in nonfarm
payroll employment, substantially less than most advance estimates
on Wall Street.
   The figures reinforced the spreading belief on Wall Street that
the economy has been slowing in recent months, responding to
credit-tightening by the Federal Reserve.
   What remains less clear, analysts said, is whether the Fed is
starting to see any results in its primary mission of reining in
inflation.
   In addition, brokers said, some investors apparently began to
worry about what a slowing economy would mean for corporate profits.
   Losers among the blue chips included International Business
Machines, down 1\ at 109]; Exxon, down [ at 42\; DuPont, down 1 at
107}; Eastman Kodak, down \ at 43, and General Motors, down ] at
39|.
   Pittston climbed 1[ to 20|. The company, faced with a challenge
to its finances by striking coal miners, declared its first
dividend since 1983.
   Motorola gained } to 47. A Wall Street Journal article discussed
prospects for the company's Micro Tac, the smallest cellular
telephone yet produced.
   Bowater Inc. fell 1} to 31\. Abitibi Price Inc., which had been
rumored to be considering a bid for Bowater, said it wasn't in the
market for any large acquisition.
   NWA rose { to 105\. A machinists' union said it was considering
entering the bidding for the airline holding company.
   Castle &amp; Cooke, mentioned as a target of insider buying in
Business Week magazine, jumped 2[ to 33{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $0.33 billion, or 0.01
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .07 to 172.14.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell .53 to 354.16, and S&amp;P's
500-stock composite index was down .16 at 307.61.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
climbed 1.51 to 430.71. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 346.84, up .95.
