<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 1729EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold Bjt   05-05 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold, Bjt,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Despite Intervention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar spurted higher in worldwide trading
Friday despite waves of concerted central bank intervention and the
government's report of higher U.S. unemployment during April.
   ``The dollar still seems to be king,'' said Jack Barbanel,
senior vice president at Gruntal &amp; Co.
   Early in the session, the U.S. currency fell sharply on the
Labor Department's report indicating the jobless rate had climbed
to 5.3 percent in April from 5.0 percent the previous month. But
the currency's recovery was quick and dramatic.
   As the currency pushed against the level of 1.90 West German
marks, the Federal Reserve, joined by West Germany's Bundesbank and
other European central banks, began the first in a series of rounds
of dollar-selling.
   Traders noted that the intervention, though frequent, was
moderate in volume. They interpreted that as a sign the Fed only
intended to slow the dollar's rise, rather than completly curtail
it.
   ``Consistently strong buying took the dollar back through the
intervention levels,'' said Jim McGroarty senior vice president of
Greenwich Capital Markets Inc. in Greenwich, Conn. ``What the day
showed is that there is a consistent strong demand for dollars for
investment in the U.S., be it in the stock or bond market,'' he
said.
   While the unemployment report was consistent with recent
statistics showing slower economic activity, observers note that
interest rates in the United States do not appear to be easing.
   High U.S. interest rates have boosted demand for dollars and
dollar-denominated investments.
   The Fed would like to keep the dollar from rising too far _
which would make U.S. goods more expensive overseas _ in order to
help ease the U.S. trade deficit.
   ``As long as the dollar still is a high-yielding currency,
you're going to see it maintain pretty good strength,'' Barbanel
said, adding that only a severe economic slowdown or a swelling
trade deficit are likely to stifle demand for the U.S. currency.
   The Tokyo market was closed for Children's Day, a national
holiday. In London, the dollar was quoted at 134.31 yen, compared
with 133.95 yen late Thursday. In New York, the dollar rose to
134.25 yen from 134.20 yen Thursday.
   In London, the British pound dipped to $1.6740 from $1.6841
Thursday. In New York sterling fell to $1.6755 from Thursday's
$1.6813.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with rates late
Thursday, included: 1.8977 West German marks, up from 1.8958;
1.6963 Swiss francs, up from 1.6911; 6.4020 French francs, up from
6.4005; 1,384.63 Italian lire, up from 1,380.00; and 1.1842
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1831.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with rates late
Thursday, included: 1.8988 West German marks, up from 1.8915;
1.6985 Swiss francs, up from 1.6860; 6.4080 French francs, up from
6.3875; 2.1285 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1290; 1,379.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,380.00; and 1.1842 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1841.
   Gold prices were little changed in U.S. trading after falling
overseas. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a troy ounce of
gold bullion at $377.00 as of 4 p.m. EDT, up 30 cents from
Thursday's late bid.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
settled at $377.70 a troy ounce, unchanged from Thursday.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid of $376.25 a troy ounce from
$378.25 late Thursday. In Zurich, gold fell to close at a bid of
$375.85 from $379 bid late Wednesday. The market was closed
Thursday. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell 75 cents to close at
$378.41.
   Silver bullion for current delivery closed on New York's Comex
at $5.598 a troy ounce, down from Thursday's settlement of $5.613.
Earlier in London, silver was trading at a late bid of $5.60 a troy
ounce, compared with Thursday's $5.66.
</TEXT>
