<FILEID>AP-NR-05-05-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Pittston-Dividends     05-05 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pittston-Dividends,0383</SECOND>
<UNK>Pittston Announces First Dividends In Six Years</UNK>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pittston Co. announced its first
dividends in six years Friday, but a spokesman said the decision
wasn't a response to striking coal miners who have recently raised
doubts about the company's finances.
   ``This had been talked about in the annual report and talked
about by analysts,'' said William J. Byrne Jr., a Pittston
spokesman. ``People can read into these things what they want.''
   Members of the United Mine Workers had questioned the company's
failure to pay dividends since 1983 as part of a union strategy to
take its disputes with the company directly to shareholders. The
union also has three proposals on the company's proxy ballot that
will be voted during Pittston's annual meeting Wednesday.
   Officials at the union headquarters in Washington, D.C., weren't
available Friday for comment on the payment of dividends, according
to a secretary reached by telephone.
   Pittston's board of directors, meeting in Greenwich, agreed to
pay a 5-cent dividend on each share on June 1 to all stockholders
of record as of May 16. Rumors about the dividend had caused a
50-cent rise in the company's stock Thursday, to $19.50 a share on
the New York Stock Exchange.
   In addition to announcing the dividend, the company's directors
approved a plan that will allow the company to repurchase up to 3
million of its common shares. Since July 1986, Pittston has bought
5.2 million of its shares at a cost of $66.5 million, or about
$12.65 a share.
   The company will purchase the shares from time to time as
conditions warrant, Byrne said.
   ``It's the kind of program that Wall Street expects you to do.
We believe our stock is undervalued,'' Byrne said.
   About 1,500 miners in Virginia and West Virgina went on strike
against the company on April 5 in a dispute over wages and
benefits. Two hundred other miners at the company's operations in
Kentucky have remained on the job.
   Representatives of the miners' union have formed the so-called
Pittston Independent Shareholders Committee, which owns 1,721 of
the company's 37.8 million shares outstanding.
   Pittston is a diversified company with interests in coal mining,
home security, security transportation services and air freight
services.
</TEXT>
