<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-05 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rise in Jobless Rate Drops Precious Metal Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Precious metal futures prices dropped Friday in dull trading on
New York's Commodities Exchange in the wake of news that the
nation's unemployment rate shot up 0.3 percent to 5.3 percent in
April.
   On other markets, grain and soybean prices were up, livestock
and meat prices were mixed, and oil prices were down.
   Gold settled $1.20 to 30 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in June at $379.60 a troy ounce; silver was 1.5 cents to
3.9 cents lower with May at $5.598 a troy ounce.
   ``There was more weakness in the economy than expected,'' said
Stephen W. Platt, an analyst for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago. ``Initial selling was on the belief that the unemployment
news would temper a surge in inflation.'' Inflation increases the
desirability of investment in gold and silver.
   Platt also attributed the selloff to the strong dollar.
   Gold futures were able to recover most of their losses in late
trading as investors began to believe the market was oversold.
   Silver, which was trading within a 6-cent range, was also able
to attract some support late.
   ``Metals have been hit by lack of participation,'' Platt said,
adding that with the bad market and adequate supplies, there is not
a rush to buy.
   Grain and soybean futures prices were higher in quiet trading on
the Chicago Board of Trade as expectations of additional export of
U.S. grains spurred the market.
   Earlier this week, the United States offered to sell 1.5 million
metric tons of grain to the Soviet Union under the export subsidy
program.
   The Soviets have announced a bid for 300,000 metric tons of
wheat, leaving about 1.2 million metric tons available to them.
   ``I think even if they are not bidding now, they will be in the
market in the near future,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York. ``That is keeping wheat
prices firm.''
   Expected Soviet demand for U.S. corn also spurred prices for
that commodity.
   ``The Soviets have made sporadic buys of corn in the past,'' Mao
said. ``The market is waiting to hear how much more buying will be
done.''
   Soybean futures rose on word of tightness in the U.S. and
Brazilian cash soybean markets.
   Wheat was 1{ cents to 3 cents higher with May at $4.37 a bushel;
corn was 1} cents to 4} cents higher with May at $2.80{ a bushel;
oats were 3{ cents to 6\ cents higher with May at $1.96} a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 9{ cents higher with May at $7.59{ a bushel.
   Energy futures declined in light trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange on expectations of a surplus of gasoline.
   ``Crude oil took a beating because of the weakness in
gasoline,'' said Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D. &amp; F Man
International Futures Inc. in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 21 cents to 56 cents lower
with June at $20.02 cents a barrel; heating oil was .95 cent to
7.74 cents lower with June at 40.85 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .55 cent to 2.12 cents lower with June at 67.50 cents
a gallon.
   Live cattle prices were mixed and pork futures slightly higher
in light trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   The drop in cattle futures were limited by expected stronger
cash prices in coming weeks and strong boxed meat purchases by
retailers, said analyst Tom O'Hare of Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp;
Co. in New York.
   Hog prices were helped by an anticipated decline in marketings
next week. But futures were weighed down by weak cash prices at the
wholesale level.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .20 cent higher with June at
72.42 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .07 cent
higher with May at 76.97 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent lower to
.17 cent higher with June at 47.27 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .37 cent lower to .13 cent higher with May at 30.95
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
