<FIRST>u f AM-Exxon-Stock     05-05 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon-Stock,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Investors Moving To Influence Exxon Management</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's state employee pension fund, the
nation's biggest, said Friday it might back an attempt by other
major Exxon Corp. shareholders to pressure the company to better
prepare for future environmental disasters in the wake of its
Alaskan oil spill.
   A spokesman for the California Public Employee Retirement
System, which owns 8 million shares amounting to about 0.6 percent
of Exxon's outstanding common stock, said the fund may back New
York City's plan to use its holdings in an effort to advocate the
company change its spill strategies.
   ``We are looking very closely at what New York City is doing,''
said James Burton, deputy comptroller for the state of California
``... If they are able to reach an agreement with Exxon that would
address our concerns we would endorse that.''
   New York officials said Thursday after meeting with Exxon
executives that three city pension funds owning 6 million shares of
Exxon stock would vote against company management at the May 18
annual meeting of shareholders if Exxon failed to act on the
group's recommendations.
   Among other requests, the group is asking for the formation of a
subcommittee of the board to handle environmental matters as well
as for a new contingency plan to deal with future disasters.
   Alaska officials and environmentalists have criticized Exxon for
what they consider its slow response to the March 24 spill, which
has fouled hundreds of miles of waters and coastline.
   New York City's employee, firefighter and police funds together
own Exxon stock amounting to less than 1 percent of the company's
1.33 billion outstanding common shares.
   About 35 percent of Exxon's shares are owned by institutional
investors. The company has some 713,000 shareholders.
   Burton said all pension funds with large holdings of Exxon stock
are worried that the spill would have financial consequences for
the company. California investors are particularly concerned about
the ``inadequate state of preparedness'' by Exxon, he said.
   ``We're concerned about its management. Management has made
statements in the past, representations that they are capable of
handling oil spills,'' Burton said. ``It appears that they were in
fact not prepared and that their representations are not accurate.''
   Burton said that if California decides to take a position for or
against Exxon management, the California State Teachers Retirement
Fund, which holds 5.5 million Exxon shares, also would be included.
California comptroller Gray Davis is the trustee for both funds,
owning 13.5 million Exxon shares, or about 1.01 percent of the
outstanding common.
   Separately, a spokesman for New York State's Employee Retirement
Fund indicated it was considering its own course of action. Tom
Pandick, director of investor affairs for the state, said the
pension fund does not normally send an official representative to
Exxon annual meetings but would do so this year.
   A spokesman for New York City Comptroller Harrison J. Goldin
said Goldin has been talking with the executive director of the
Council of Institutional Investors, which represents 65 large
pension funds with $300 billion in assets.
   ``We have indications of interest of 22 million shares from
other pension funds,'' said Steven Cohen, deputy counsel for the
comptroller. Cohen said all of the pension funds are members of the
Council.
   Alaska pension fund officials said earlier this week they would
withhold votes on their 650,600 shares at this year's meeting as a
symbolic gesture to underscore the state's concern about the spill.
</TEXT>
