<HEAD>RESENDING FOR ALL NEEDING</HEAD>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices declined in light trading
Friday on a wave of profit-taking after gains earlier in the week.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, closed at
$20.02 a barrel, 56 cents lower than Thursday's session. The
contract traded as low as $19.99 but rose shortly before the close,
traders said.
   Other crude contracts also closed the day lower.
   Among refined products, unleaded gasoline for June delivery fell
2.12 cents to 67.50 cents a gallon, while June heating oil declined
1.22 cents to settle at 47.37 cents a gallon. All other contract
months were down, but less sharply.
   Prices surged late Wednesday and Thursday after an announcement
that repairs on a North Sea oil platform would take longer than
expected. Brent crude production may be disrupted until the end of
May, officials said.
   Friday's decline reflected concern that the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries has increased production and might
boost its quota in the second half of the year, traders said.
</TEXT>
