<FIRST>u f AM-PirelliArmstrong     05-05 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pirelli Armstrong,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mamma Mia! Learning Italian Not Easy For Armstrong Execs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after Armstrong Tire Co. was
acquired by the Italian tiremaker Pirelli, several dozen employees
of the new Pirelli Armstrong Tire Corp. are going the extra mile
and studying the mother tongue of their mother company.
   Treading where they haven't been in years _ the classroom _ the
new Italian language students range from vice presidents to
engineers.
   Some of the employees are spending extra time at work to take
classes being offered in the cafeteria of the company's
headquarters. Others, including some vice presidents, are being
trained by tutors who come to their offices or are taking college
courses.
   In the hallways of the company's headquarters, and out on the
building's grounds, it is not uncommon to hear employees practicing
their new language skills.
   Pirelli Armstrong officials say it was their idea to start the
program, and that participation in the crash-language courses has
been strictly voluntary.
   ``It's our way of saying we like being part of the Pirelli
organization,'' said Jan Colella, employee relations manager at
Pirelli Armstrong.
   ``It was our idea. They (executives in Italy) said slow down,
you don't have to learn so fast,'' she said.
   While most of the people from the Pirelli Group in Milan, Italy,
speak English, not all do so well, ``so it is helpful if we can
meet each other halfway sometimes,'' Collella said.
   About 15 employees have finished a beginner's class and have
moved on to the next level of instruction. Meanwhile, a second
beginner's class has also started. The classes are held two days a
week, from 4 to 6 p.m., so that the employees are taught partly on
their own time and partly on the company's. The work day ends at 5
p.m.
   Collella said her office drew up a list of employees, from the
300 who work at the headquarters, who might find knowledge of
Italian useful either because of contacts they will be making with
Italians or because of materials they must read.
   When the employees were approached about taking lessons, ``we
didn't have anyone say `No,'' she said. ``We got a very positive
response.''
   At least seven management-level employees are learning Italian
through the Berlitz method, including William Bruce, who is a vice
president and corporate counsel.
   ``It's tough to go back to school after all these years,'' said
Bruce, who is 37. It's even tougher, he said, to find the time for
visits by a tutor and for studying.
   ``I'm not entirely satisfied with my progress at this point,''
he said. ``I can read it better than I can speak it.''
   A tutor has visited Bruce's office at least a couple dozen
times, but some weeks he has had to skip lessons, he said. He also
has instructional tapes to play in his car, but he said, ``I can't
say I've listened to them as religiously as I should.''
   Bruce said there has been absolutely no attempt by executives in
Milan to pressure their American employees into learning Italian.
``The opposite happened,'' he said. ``When I was over there, they
said, `Why are you learning it?'''
   ``They seemed to be pleased by it,'' he said.
   Bruce said he has found even his beginner's knowledge of Italian
very useful on visiting Milan, and that he would like to attain a
reasonable degree of fluency ``so I can communicate in a basic
business conversation.''
   ``It's fun. It's different,'' Bruce said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
