<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     05-05 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prices Spurt on Unemployment Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices closed moderately higher Friday
after an unexpectedly weak employment report gave investors hope
that the Federal Reserve might loosen the reins on interest rates.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond rose ] point, or $3.75
per $1,000 face amount. Its yield, which moves in an opposite
direction from price, fell to 8.95 percent from 8.99 percent late
Thursday.
   Bonds rallied after the Labor Department reported non-farm
business payrolls expanded by only 117,000 jobs in April, the
weakest showing since a drop of 92,000 jobs in June 1986.
   The department also reported that last month's unemployment rate
rose to 5.3 percent from 5 percent in March and reached its highest
level since January.
   Mitchell Held, chief financial economist with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co., said the increase was smaller than expected and
fueled the market's hopes that the Fed would relax credit in
response to an apparent cooling of the economy.
   If the Fed eases credit, interest rates would likely fall while
bond prices would rise.
   The employment report said hourly earnings rose a seasonally
adjusted 0.7 percent in April after climbing 0.3 percent a month
for two months, but Held said the rise, which could have ignited
fears of higher inflation and a resulting tightening of credit, was
not enough to offset the non-farm payroll drop.
   However, Held said, trading was restrained in advance of the
Treasury's quarterly refunding auction, scheduled for next week.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term governments rose 7-32 point to 5-16 point, intermediate
maturities were up about ] point and long-term issues were 7-16
point higher, according to Telerate Inc., the financial information
service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, jumped up by 4.67 to 1,137.47.
   In corporate trading, industrials also gained. Moody's
Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return
on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years
or longer, rose 1.72 to 306.20.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.73 percent as the
discount slid 9 basis points to 8.44 percent. Yields on six-month
bills fell to 8.87 percent as the discount declined 9 basis points
to 8.39 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to 8.96 percent as
the discount went down 14 basis points to 8.29 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 913-16, compared to 9~ percent late Thursday.
</TEXT>
