<HEAD>Head of Equity Trading, Another Trader Forced Out of Prudential-Bache</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 4th graf to DELETE surname.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two senior stock traders at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. were asked to resign Friday for violating the
investment company's policies, a Prudential-Bache spokeswoman said.
   She said the two have submitted their resignations.
   Prudential-Bache declined to identify the individuals or provide
details of the violations said to have been discovered during an
internal investigation of trading activities.
   Company investigators noticed irregularities which were
``inconsistent with firm policy'' in accounts handled by the two
traders, the Pru-Bache spokeswoman said. The accounts involved were
Prudential-Bache company accounts, not ones containing clients'
money, she said.
   A Wall Street source said the two traders were Dan Marciano,
head of Pru-Bache's equity trading desk, and William Grace, a block
trader, meaning a specialist in transactions comprising large
quantities of shares.
   Marciano had been head of equity trading for three years and had
been with Prudential-Bache since 1984. Information about Grace's
employment history at Prudential-Bache was not immediately
available.
   Prudential-Bache stated it gave a full report of the trading
improprieties to the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Lawrence Iason, the SEC's New York regional administrator, said
he could not comment on whether the regulatory agency had received
a report from Prudential-Bache. Law prohibits the SEC from
disclosing whether it is conducting an investigation.
