<HEAD>Icahn Interested in Buying Eastern's Philly Operations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with new grafs 1-15 to UPDATE with Icahn expressing interest,
other details, picks up 9th graf pvs, Eastern has...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn has signaled
his interest in buying strikebound Eastern Airlines' Philadelphia
airport hub, an Icahn associate said late Friday.
   Icahn filed documents with the federal bankruptcy court Friday
expressing his interest in the hub without specifying the price
he'd be willing to pay, Trans World Airlines General Counsel Mark
Buckstein told The Associated Press. Icahn, who publicly expressed
interest in all of Eastern some time ago but hasn't formally
bidded, is the owner and chairman of TWA.
   On Thursday, the state of Pennsylvania filed a challenge to
USAir Group Inc.'s proposed purchase of eight Eastern gates at
Philadelphia airport, saying the transaction could lead to higher
ticket prices in Pennsylvania.
   The sale, worth about $85 million to Eastern, would give USAir
23 of the 49 gates at the airport. TWA only has four gates there
currently, Buckstein said.
   Icahn also filed Friday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission for permission to sell $300 million in 5-year notes,
with the proceeds to be used for working capital and possible
acquisitions. Buckstein said the notes aren't specifically intended
to raise money to buy Eastern.
   Separately, Eastern said former airline executive William
Howard, who is spearheading a group interested in buying Eastern,
has met with officials of the ailing carrier.
   Howard, who has joined with investment firm Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in formulating a possible bid for Eastern, met
Thursday with executives of the airline at its Miami headquarters,
Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said. He declined to disclose
details or identify the Eastern officialsinvolved.
   Howard is a former senior vice president of Eastern and was
chairman of Piedmont Airlines until it was acquired by USAir Group
Inc. in 1987. The Howard group also met recently with officials of
Eastern's unions and the committee representing its major creditors.
   Attempts to reach Howard by phone in Miami and at his home
Friday were unsuccessful.
   Matell reiterated the company's position that Eastern was not
for sale and was proceeding with its recently announced plan to
rebuild as a smaller carrier and raise some $1.8 billion by selling
aircraft and other assets.
   ``We're committed to the rebuilding plan as the most sensible
course,'' he said.
   The Eastern officials gave Howard information as requested by
U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland, Matell said. At a hearing
on Wednesday, the judge requested that the Howard group be given
confidential financial data on Eastern which is to be provided to
all serious bidders for the airline.
   Billionaire hotel executive Jay Pritzker, who formally submitted
an offer for Eastern last week, already has received the
information. So has Icahn, according to his general counsel.
   ``We're going to have a lot of people reading a lot of pieces of
paper over the weekend,'' Buckstein said.
   
   Eastern has been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the start of a strike by
the Machinists union that was supported by pilots and flight
attendants, virtually grounding the airline.
   Lifland has set next Wednesday as a deadline for all interested
bidders to submit their offers to the court, which must approve any
sales of Eastern assets.
   A source close to the situation said the Howard group would have
a formal offer ready by the May 10 deadline.
   Attorney Lewis Kaden, who represents the Howard group, has
declined to give specifics of the proposal but said it would
include Eastern's Northeast shuttle service, slated to be sold to
developer Donald Trump for $365 million. America West Airlines, an
aggressive regional carrier, on Wednesday offered $726 million for
the shuttle routes and landing slots, along with 10 Boeing 757
jetliners.
   Lifland has set a hearing for next Friday over the Trump shuttle
deal.
   As part of its offer, the Howard group plans to propose a
bankruptcy reorganization plan for Eastern, Kaden said. He did not
return phone calls seeking comment on the meeting with Eastern
officials.
</TEXT>
