<FIRST>u f AM-Time-Warner     05-05 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Warner,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time, Warner Ask Court To Resolve Dispute With Chris-Craft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. and Warner Communications Inc.,
seeking to complete their planned $15 billion merger, asked a
Delaware court Friday to resolve a dispute with Chris-Craft
Industries Inc. over the disposition of Chris-Craft's shares of
Warner stock.
   Time and Warner said in a statement they disagreed with
Chris-Craft, Warner's largest shareholder, over the terms of an
agreement between Chris-Craft, Warner and BHC Inc., a Chris-Craft
subsidiary.
   The 1986 agreement was intended to cover the disposition of
Chris-Craft's stake in Warner and also the disposition of BHC
shares held by Warner.
   Despite the disagreement, Time and Warner said they were willing
to accept Chris-Craft's interpretation ``in order to put this issue
behind us once and for all.''
   The two companies asked the court in Delaware _ where all three
companies are incorporated _ to issue a declaration that would
determine the rights of the parties and allow the merger to proceed.
   ``Our complaint seeks to compel Chris-Craft and BHC to choose an
arrangement as dictated by the terms of the existing agreement and
to avoid any effort by Chris-Craft to delay or otherwise interfere
with the merger,'' Time and Warner said in a statement.
   Chris-Craft became Warner's largest stockholder in 1984 after
helping Warner Chairman Steven Ross fight an unwanted takeover bid
from publisher Rupert Murdoch. However, Ross and Chris-Craft
Chairman Herbert Siegel have been at loggerheads ever since,
quarreling over a number of issues.
   Siegel did not comment publicly after Time and Warner announced
plans to form Time Warner Inc., the world's largest media concern.
The combined stock market value of the two companies at the time of
the announcement was about $15 billion.
   Media industry analysts had expected the Chris-Craft chairman to
raise some objection to the proposed merger.
   Chris-Craft did not immediately return a reporter's phone call
seeking comment on the statements by Time and Warner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
