<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest 2ndLd-Writethru   05-05 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Machinists Union Plans Bid for Northwest</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: NEW grafs 3-5 to UPDATE with more detail, CLARIFY that Davis
bid turned friendly, SEC filing and ``poison pill'' plan; picks up 4th
graf pvs bg'ng, Kevin Whalen, ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Machinists union at Northwest Airlines
has told the carrier's parent it plans to mount its own bid to buy
the airline holding company, union sources said Friday.
   The International Association of Machinists District Lodge 143,
Northwest's largest union, made the proposal in a letter to the
board of directors of NWA Inc., Northwest's parent, the sources
told The Associated Press.
   NWA is believed to be the target of several suitors, including
two to four that NWA Chairman Steven Rothmeier said last week are
friendly. Billionaire oilman Marvin Davis has made the only formal
bid, a $2.7 billion, $90-a-share offer that he this week switched
from a hostile to a friendly effort.
   NWA said it filed an amended document Thursday with the
Securities and Exchange Commission, stating that it plans to
provide additional confidential information and access to an
unspecified number of interested parties.
   NWA also said it plans on May 12 to distribute certificates
representing preferred stock purchase rights under the
corporation's ``poison pill'' shareholder rights plan to holders of
NWA common stock as of the close of business May 4.
   Kevin Whalen, a Northwest spokesman, confirmed receipt of the
letter but said he hadn't seen it and couldn't describe its
contents.
   ``We're going to study the letter before we have a response to
it,'' Whalen said. ``We haven't digested all the things in it.''
   The letter said the union was ``determined to explore initiation
of our own program as an alternative'' to other bids for NWA, said
the sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Machinists union represents about 21,500 mechanics, baggage
handlers and other employees at Northwest.
   The letter said the union's proposal is at a preliminary stage.
However, it outlined several elements likely to be included in its
bid:
   _It would avoid the heavy debt burden typical of leveraged
buyouts.
   _It would reduce labor costs while increasing NWA's business and
still not ``adversely affect the compensation'' of individual
employees.
   _It would involve a substantial employee stake in NWA.
   _It would put a block of NWA stock in the hands of a ``patient
investor'' acceptable to employees, as opposed to a speculator
interested in short-term gain.
   Meanwhile, NWA stock, which shot to record highs Thursday on
signs that potential suitors were preparing for a bidding war, rose
even higher Friday. The stock closed at $105[ a share, up ] on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Bankers Trust Corp. of New York confirmed Thursday that it was
working on a proposal with Los Angeles investor Al Checchi, who
leads a group holding 4.9 percent of NWA stock. Bankers Trust
Senior Vice President Thomas Parisi said the firm is prepared to
advise Checchi and arrange financing, including an equity stake of
its own. Parisi said details of a financing package have yet to be
arranged.
   Mike Hamilton, a financial analyst with Piper, Jaffray &amp;
Hopwood, said stock traders also were intrigued by signs that
another apparent suitor may be preparing an offer. The company,
leveraged buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.,
reportedly has affiliated with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., and
apparently sold a large block of stock Wednesday in
Cincinnati-based Kroger Co., netting a $19 million profit.
   In another development Thursday, NWA Chairman Steve Rothmeier
and the leaders of Northwest's 5,000-member pilots union said the
unsettled labor contract covering the pilots remains a major wild
card in the takeover battle.
   Pete Dodge and Kirk Faupel, officials of the Air Line Pilots
Association, also confirmed that they had been approached by four
potential suitors: Checchi; Davis, who started the bidding March
30; Kelso &amp; Co., a New York investment firm; and Wesray Capital
Corp., an investment firm founded by former treasury secretary
William Simon.
   But they said all four broke off contact after NWA announced its
ground rules.
   In a separate interview, Rothmeier reiterated that the open
labor contract is scaring off friendly bidders who don't want to
buy or invest in an airline with excessive wage costs or labor
trouble.
   The company and the pilots continued their contract talks
Friday, according to another ALPA spokesman, Jim Halvorson, who
said he had no immediate word on whether progress had been made.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
